"An experienced trail guide once said that a group moving through wilderness is only as fast as its slowest member. He always positioned himself at the rear of the column, not the front."

What can be inferred about why the guide positioned himself at the rear?', '["He wanted to avoid leading the group in case he made a navigation error.","Positioning at the rear let him monitor the slowest members and ensure no one fell behind.","He preferred the view from the back of the column.","Walking at the rear is the safest position in dangerous terrain."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The guide''s saying is the key: a group "is only as fast as its slowest member." If the slowest person sets the pace, the guide gains the most leverage by watching that person directly, which means staying at the back. Choice B draws that link. Choice A invents a fear of leading that contradicts the experienced-guide framing. Choice C reduces a deliberate tactical choice to personal preference. Choice D overreaches by adding terrain danger and a safety theory the passage never raises. Only B connects the stated belief to the observed behavior.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-INF-B4-8', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

