  ('PC-ATP-B4-8', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The glacier that covered this valley 12,000 years ago left behind the hills to the north, the flat plain to the south, and the scattering of boulders that farmers have been removing from their fields ever since. Ice, it turns out, is not merely weather. Given enough time and weight, it becomes geology."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["alarmed by the ongoing effects of ancient glaciation","wryly reflective, finding meaning in the slow scale of geological time","strictly scientific and data-driven","mournful about the disappearance of glaciers"]'::jsonb, 1, '''It turns out'' and the observation that ice ''becomes geology'' are quiet, reflective moments — the author finds something worth remarking on in the long view of time. This is contemplative, slightly wry, not alarmed or data-driven. Glacial disappearance is not the subject.', true, 'trusted'),
