The author''s implied attitude toward the committee''s handling of the report is:', '["supportive — a 847-page report demonstrates thoroughness","critical — the details suggest the report was released to minimize public attention","neutral — the author is simply presenting facts without judgment","hopeful — the follow-up report may address unresolved questions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Friday afternoon December releases, no press conference, ''preliminary'' findings, and a delayed follow-up are classic bureaucratic tactics for burying unwanted information. The author selects these details deliberately to imply criticism without stating it. A neutral author would not stack these signals.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-10', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The soldier who does not think about the mission — who moves on instinct, reflex, and training alone — is often called battle-hardened. We praise him for it. We decorate him for it. And then, when the war ends and he cannot stop moving on instinct, we call it a disorder and wonder why the training does not switch off when the war does."

The author''s primary purpose is to:', '["argue that soldiers should not be given combat training","criticize soldiers for seeking recognition through combat","highlight a contradiction in how society values and then pathologizes combat instincts","propose a new approach to treating veterans with post-traumatic stress"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage traces one cycle: we train the response, reward the response, then diagnose the same response as a disorder. The author''s purpose is to expose this contradiction, not to argue against training or propose clinical solutions. ''We praise him'' and ''we call it a disorder'' shows the critical symmetry is the point.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-11', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"There is something both useful and troubling about the word ''closure.'' Useful, because it gives people permission to move forward after loss. Troubling, because it implies that grief has a terminal state — that the missing weight of a person eventually becomes light enough to carry without noticing. People who have lost someone they love report, almost universally, that they do not stop missing them. They simply learn to carry the weight differently."

The author''s tone toward the concept of ''closure'' is best described as:', '["firmly opposed — the author believes the word should be abandoned","fully supportive — closure is essential for healthy grieving","nuanced — the author acknowledges its usefulness while questioning its implied finality","clinical and detached, reporting grief research without personal interpretation"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The author calls closure ''both useful and troubling,'' then unpacks both halves. This is not opposition or support — it is a nuanced critique that preserves the word''s value while questioning its misleading implication of completeness. The lyrical ending (''carry the weight differently'') rules out clinical detachment.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which organelle is known as the powerhouse of the cell because it produces most of the cell''s energy?', '["Nucleus","Ribosome","Mitochondria","Vacuole"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Mitochondria run cellular respiration, converting glucose and oxygen into ATP, the energy currency cells spend on every active process. Muscle cells and neurons pack in extra mitochondria because they burn through ATP fast. The nucleus stores DNA and directs gene expression, but it does not generate energy. Ribosomes are the protein-assembly stations that read mRNA and link amino acids. Vacuoles store water, food, or waste, especially in plant cells. Confusing the nucleus with mitochondria is the most common slip since both are major organelles students hear about first.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which gas do plants release as a byproduct of photosynthesis?', '["Carbon dioxide","Nitrogen","Oxygen","Hydrogen"]'::jsonb, 2, 'During photosynthesis the plant splits water molecules to harvest electrons, and the leftover oxygen is released through stomata. That is why forests and ocean phytoplankton drive Earth''s oxygen supply. Carbon dioxide is the opposite: plants pull it in as a raw material and lock its carbon into glucose, so they consume it rather than release it. Nitrogen is the dominant gas in the atmosphere but plants cannot use it directly from the air, so it is not part of photosynthesis. Hydrogen ends up bound inside glucose, not released as gas.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'The primary role of the cell membrane is to:', '["Produce proteins for the cell","Control what enters and exits the cell","Store genetic information","Convert sunlight into energy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The cell membrane is a phospholipid bilayer studded with proteins that acts as a selective gate, letting some substances pass freely (small nonpolar molecules), pumping others in or out actively (ions, glucose), and blocking the rest. Protein production happens at ribosomes attached to rough ER or floating in cytoplasm, not at the membrane. Genetic information lives in the nucleus in eukaryotes or in the nucleoid region in bacteria. Converting sunlight to energy is the chloroplast''s job, found only in plants and algae. The membrane is gatekeeper, not factory.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'In an ecosystem, which organisms are the primary producers?', '["Herbivores","Carnivores","Decomposers","Plants and algae"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Primary producers capture energy from sunlight (or chemicals at deep-sea vents) and turn it into stored chemical energy, building the base of every food web. Plants, algae, and photosynthetic bacteria do this. Herbivores like deer or grasshoppers are primary consumers because they eat producers. Carnivores eat other animals and sit higher in the chain. Decomposers like fungi and bacteria recycle dead matter into nutrients, which is essential but not the same as producing energy from sunlight. The distinction is whether the organism makes food or eats food.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'Which blood component is primarily responsible for fighting bacterial infections?', '["Red blood cells","Platelets","White blood cells","Plasma"]'::jsonb, 2, 'White blood cells, also called leukocytes, are the immune system''s frontline. Neutrophils swallow bacteria, lymphocytes produce antibodies and kill infected cells, and macrophages clean up debris. Red blood cells carry oxygen and have no role in fighting infection. Platelets are cell fragments that plug wounds and start clotting cascades. Plasma is the straw-colored liquid that carries everything else, including antibodies the white cells produce, but plasma itself is the transport medium rather than the attacker. White cell count rises during infection, which is why doctors order a CBC to check it.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 3, 'A food chain reads: grass → grasshopper → frog → hawk. If the frog population is removed, what is the most likely short-term result?', '["Hawks will increase in number","Grasshoppers will increase in number","Grass will decrease","Hawks will switch to eating grasshoppers directly and maintain balance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Remove the predator and the prey explodes. With frogs gone, grasshoppers face no consistent predator at their trophic level, so their numbers surge in the short term. Hawks lose a major food source and would decline, not increase. Grass would also decline as more grasshoppers eat it, but that secondary effect lags behind the grasshopper boom itself, making the grasshopper increase the more immediate result. Hawks switching directly to grasshoppers ignores that food chains are not infinitely flexible and that adapting prey preferences takes time and may not maintain population balance.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 3, 'Osmosis is best defined as:', '["The active transport of glucose across a membrane","The movement of water from low solute concentration to high solute concentration across a semipermeable membrane","The diffusion of oxygen from lungs into the bloodstream","The breakdown of food in the digestive tract"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Osmosis is the passive movement of water through a semipermeable membrane from an area of lower solute concentration to an area of higher solute concentration. It does not require energy and moves water, not solutes.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 3, 'Which organ system is responsible for removing gaseous waste (carbon dioxide) from the body?', '["Digestive system","Urinary system","Respiratory system","Circulatory system"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The respiratory system handles gas exchange in the alveoli of the lungs, where oxygen diffuses into the blood and carbon dioxide diffuses out and gets exhaled. The circulatory system transports CO₂ from tissues to the lungs but does not actually remove it from the body, which is a common slip because blood is involved in both transport and removal. The urinary system removes liquid nitrogen waste as urine. The digestive system removes undigested solid waste as feces. Match the waste type to the system: gas to lungs, liquid to kidneys, solid to intestines.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 4, 'A plant cell placed in a highly concentrated salt solution will most likely:', '["Swell and burst as water rushes in","Remain unchanged because the cell wall prevents movement","Shrink as water moves out through osmosis","Absorb the salt ions and increase in size"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The salt solution has a higher solute concentration than the cell''s interior. By osmosis, water moves from the cell (lower solute) into the solution (higher solute), causing the cell to shrink (plasmolyze). The cell wall limits swelling, not shrinking.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-11', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 4, 'Mitosis results in:', '["Two genetically identical daughter cells, each with the same chromosome number as the parent","Four daughter cells, each with half the parent''s chromosome number","One parent cell that doubles its DNA but does not divide","Two cells with different genetic makeup due to chromosome shuffling"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Mitosis produces two genetically identical cells that each carry the same number of chromosomes as the original cell — used for growth and repair. Meiosis (not mitosis) produces four cells with half the chromosome count for sexual reproduction.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-12', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 4, 'Which process do decomposers like fungi and bacteria perform that is essential to the nutrient cycle?', '["Photosynthesis — converting CO₂ to glucose","Nitrogen fixation — converting N₂ gas to ammonia","Decomposition — breaking organic matter into inorganic nutrients","Transpiration — releasing water vapor from leaves"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Decomposition is the breakdown of dead organisms and waste into simpler inorganic molecules like CO₂, ammonia, and mineral ions that return to soil, water, and air. Without it, carbon and nitrogen would stay locked in corpses and dead leaves and ecosystems would starve. Photosynthesis is what plants and algae do, not fungi. Nitrogen fixation is a narrow process performed by specific bacteria (Rhizobium, cyanobacteria) on N₂ gas, not the general decomposer role. Transpiration is water loss from plant leaves, completely separate from nutrient cycling driven by decomposers.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-13', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 5, 'A recessive genetic trait will be expressed in an individual when:', '["The individual carries at least one dominant allele","The individual is heterozygous (one dominant, one recessive allele)","The individual inherits two recessive alleles, one from each parent","The trait skips a generation before appearing"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Recessive traits are masked when a dominant allele is present. Expression requires two copies of the recessive allele (homozygous recessive). Heterozygous individuals carry the trait but do not express it; ''skipping a generation'' describes the pattern, not the cause.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-14', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 5, 'During aerobic cellular respiration, where in the cell does the Krebs cycle take place?', '["In the cytoplasm","In the nucleus","In the mitochondrial matrix","On the outer mitochondrial membrane"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The Krebs cycle (citric acid cycle) occurs in the mitochondrial matrix — the innermost compartment. Glycolysis happens in the cytoplasm. The electron transport chain is located on the inner mitochondrial membrane, not in the matrix itself.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Which state of matter has a definite volume but no definite shape?', '["Solid","Liquid","Gas","Plasma"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Liquids hold a fixed volume because their molecules stay close together, but they flow to take the shape of whatever container holds them. Pour a liter of water into a tall cylinder or a flat tray, and it remains a liter while changing outline. Solids lock in both shape and volume because their molecules are fixed in place. Gases expand to fill the entire container, so they lack both a fixed shape and a fixed volume. Plasma is ionized gas found in stars and neon signs; like ordinary gas, it conforms to no fixed shape or volume.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Which of the following is a chemical change?', '["Ice melting into water","Cutting a piece of paper","Iron rusting","Sugar dissolving in water"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Rusting is iron combining with oxygen to form a new compound, iron oxide, with different color, hardness, and chemical properties. New substance means chemical change. Ice melting is a physical change because the H₂O molecules are identical before and after, just rearranged from rigid crystal to flowing liquid. Cutting paper changes shape, not composition. Sugar dissolving spreads sucrose molecules through water but does not transform them; evaporate the water and the sugar returns unchanged. The test is whether a brand-new substance with new chemistry has appeared.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'On the periodic table, elements in the same column (group) share similar properties primarily because they have the same:', '["Atomic mass","Number of protons","Number of neutrons","Number of valence electrons"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Valence electrons are the outermost shell electrons that participate in chemical bonding, and elements in the same group share the same valence count. That is why all Group 1 alkali metals react violently with water and all Group 18 noble gases barely react at all. Atomic mass increases steadily down a group, so it cannot be the cause. Proton count defines the element itself and is unique to each element, never shared. Neutron count varies among isotopes even within a single element and has no bearing on chemical behavior, only on stability and mass.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'What happens to the pressure of a gas inside a sealed container when the temperature increases, assuming volume stays constant?', '["Pressure decreases","Pressure stays the same","Pressure increases","The gas liquefies"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Heating a gas speeds up its molecules. They hit the container walls harder and more often, which is exactly what pressure measures. With volume fixed, pressure rises in direct proportion to absolute temperature; double the Kelvin temperature and pressure doubles. This is Gay-Lussac''s Law. A sealed aerosol can in a hot car can rupture for this reason. The gas does not liquefy from heating; liquefaction usually requires cooling or compressing. Pressure cannot stay the same because faster molecules cannot avoid more forceful collisions when the walls do not move.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'In a chemical reaction, the substances that are present before the reaction begins are called:', '["Products","Reactants","Catalysts","Compounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Reactants are the starting materials that get consumed and rearranged during a reaction, written on the left side of the arrow. Products are what comes out on the right side, so swapping the two reverses the equation. Catalysts speed up reactions by lowering activation energy but are not consumed and are not counted among reactants or products; they often appear above the arrow. Compound describes a category of substance, not a reaction role; both reactants and products can be compounds or elements. The arrow direction is the visual cue: left equals reactant, right equals product.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-6', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 3, 'A substance has a pH of 2. Which statement best describes this substance?', '["It is strongly basic and will feel slippery","It is weakly acidic and slightly corrosive","It is strongly acidic with high hydrogen ion concentration","It is neutral and safe to drink in any quantity"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A pH of 2 is strongly acidic, only one step away from battery acid at pH 1 and well below the neutral mark at 7. Because pH is logarithmic, pH 2 has 100,000 times more hydrogen ions than neutral water. Calling it weakly acidic underestimates the danger; lemon juice sits around pH 2 and is still capable of dissolving tooth enamel. Strongly basic substances feel slippery and have high pH above 12, not low pH. Neutral substances sit at 7, not 2, and nothing at pH 2 is universally safe to drink in unlimited amounts.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 3, 'When a substance undergoes sublimation, it transitions directly from:', '["Liquid to gas","Solid to liquid","Solid to gas","Gas to liquid"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Sublimation skips the liquid phase, going straight from solid to gas. Dry ice (solid CO₂) is the textbook example because at room pressure it cannot exist as a liquid, so it simply turns into CO₂ gas. Solid air fresheners and mothballs also sublime slowly. Liquid to gas is evaporation or boiling, not sublimation. Solid to liquid is plain melting. Gas to liquid is condensation, the reverse of evaporation. The reverse of sublimation, gas straight to solid, is called deposition, which is how frost forms on a cold windshield without dew first.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 3, 'Which type of chemical bond results from the transfer of electrons from one atom to another?', '["Covalent bond","Hydrogen bond","Ionic bond","Metallic bond"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ionic bonds form when one atom hands off electrons to another, creating a positively charged cation and a negatively charged anion. The opposite charges attract and lock the ions in place, as in sodium chloride where sodium gives up an electron to chlorine. Covalent bonds work differently, with atoms sharing electron pairs rather than transferring them, common in water and methane. Hydrogen bonds are weak attractions between polar molecules, like the ones holding water''s strands together, not full bonds. Metallic bonds let electrons flow freely through a lattice of metal atoms, giving conductivity.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 4, 'A catalyst speeds up a chemical reaction primarily by:', '["Increasing the temperature of the reactants","Providing energy to break all molecular bonds","Lowering the activation energy required for the reaction","Increasing the concentration of products"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Catalysts provide an alternative reaction pathway with lower activation energy, allowing more reactant molecules to have sufficient energy to react. A catalyst is not consumed and does not change the energy of reactants or products.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 4, 'In a neutralization reaction, an acid and a base react to form:', '["Another acid with different strength","Salt and water","Carbon dioxide and oxygen","A metal oxide"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An acid donates H⁺ ions, a base donates OH⁻ ions, and when they meet the ions combine to form H₂O while the leftover spectator ions pair up as a salt. Hydrochloric acid plus sodium hydroxide gives sodium chloride and water: HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O. The pH moves toward 7. Producing another acid would mean the reaction never neutralized anything. Carbon dioxide and oxygen come out of combustion or photosynthesis, not acid-base neutralization. Metal oxides form when metals burn or corrode with oxygen and have nothing to do with mixing an acid and a base.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-11', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 4, 'Which of the following correctly identifies the number of moles in 44 grams of CO₂? (C = 12 g/mol, O = 16 g/mol)', '["0.5 moles","1 mole","2 moles","44 moles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Molar mass of CO₂ is 12 (one carbon) plus 2 times 16 (two oxygens), which equals 44 g/mol. Moles equals mass divided by molar mass, so 44 grams divided by 44 g/mol gives exactly 1 mole. The 2-mole answer comes from doubling because there are two oxygens, but the formula already accounts for that in the molar mass. The 0.5-mole answer halves correctly only if the substance were O₂ or someone forgot the carbon. The 44-mole answer mistakes grams for moles entirely and ignores the conversion.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-12', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 5, 'In the balanced equation 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, how many moles of water are produced from 3 moles of H₂ and excess O₂?', '["1.5 moles","2 moles","3 moles","6 moles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Read the coefficients: 2 moles of H₂ produce 2 moles of H₂O, a 1 to 1 ratio. So 3 moles of hydrogen produce 3 moles of water when oxygen is plentiful. Dividing 3 by 2 to get 1.5 misreads the ratio by treating the 2 in front of H₂ as a divisor rather than recognizing it pairs evenly with the 2 in front of H₂O. Doubling to 6 mistakenly multiplies by 2. Answering 2 moles ignores that the limiting reactant is H₂ and that excess O₂ means hydrogen sets the cap.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-13', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 5, 'Which of the following best explains why noble gases (Group 18) rarely form chemical bonds with other elements?', '["They have very high atomic masses that prevent bonding","They have complete outer electron shells with no tendency to gain or lose electrons","They are radioactive and unstable at normal temperatures","Their electrons orbit so quickly that other atoms cannot bond to them"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Noble gases have full valence electron shells (8 electrons, or 2 for helium), giving them maximum stability. With no need to gain, lose, or share electrons, they have virtually no chemical reactivity. Their stability is electronic, not related to mass or speed.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'The layer of Earth that we live on, which makes up the surface and outer crust, is called the:', '["Mantle","Core","Lithosphere","Asthenosphere"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The lithosphere is the rigid outer shell of Earth, including the crust and the cool uppermost portion of the mantle, and it is the layer broken into tectonic plates that carry continents and oceans. The mantle as a whole sits below the lithosphere and is much hotter and more deformable. The core is the metallic center, an outer liquid layer and an inner solid layer of mostly iron and nickel. The asthenosphere is the partly molten zone right beneath the lithosphere where plates ride and convection occurs. We live on top of the lithosphere.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'What causes the seasons on Earth?', '["Earth''s varying distance from the Sun as it orbits","The tilt of Earth''s axis relative to its orbital plane","Changes in the Sun''s energy output throughout the year","The Moon blocking different amounts of sunlight"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Earth''s axis is tilted approximately 23.5° relative to its orbit. This tilt causes one hemisphere to receive more direct sunlight during part of the year (summer) and less during another (winter). Earth''s distance from the Sun varies only slightly and is not the primary cause.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'Metamorphic rock is formed when existing rock is subjected to:', '["Rapid cooling of magma at the surface","The compaction of layers of sediment over time","High heat and pressure deep within Earth","Erosion by wind and water"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Metamorphic rock starts as another rock (igneous, sedimentary, or even older metamorphic) and gets reshaped by intense heat and pressure deep underground without fully melting. Limestone becomes marble, shale becomes slate, sandstone becomes quartzite. Rapid cooling of magma at the surface produces extrusive igneous rocks like basalt, not metamorphic. Compaction of sediment layers makes sedimentary rocks like shale and sandstone. Erosion by wind and water is the breakdown step that creates sediment in the first place; it does not form rock by itself. The key word is transformed, not melted, not crushed, not weathered.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'The water cycle step in which water vapor cools and changes into liquid water droplets to form clouds is called:', '["Evaporation","Condensation","Precipitation","Transpiration"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Condensation is the phase change from gas back to liquid. As warm moist air rises and cools, vapor molecules slow down enough to stick together as tiny droplets around dust or salt particles, forming clouds and fog. Evaporation is the opposite direction, liquid turning to vapor when surface water absorbs heat. Precipitation comes after condensation, when droplets grow heavy enough to fall as rain, snow, or hail. Transpiration is plant-driven evaporation through leaf stomata; it adds moisture to the air but is not the cloud-forming step. Cooling vapor equals condensation.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 3, 'Which atmospheric layer, positioned just above the stratosphere, is where meteors typically burn up upon entering Earth''s atmosphere?', '["Troposphere","Stratosphere","Mesosphere","Thermosphere"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The mesosphere extends from roughly 50 to 80 km up, sitting directly above the stratosphere. The air there is thin but dense enough that friction with incoming meteoroids generates the heat that produces shooting stars. The troposphere is the bottom weather layer and is too low to see most meteor burns. The stratosphere holds the ozone layer but is below where meteors flame. The thermosphere is the next layer up, where the ISS orbits and auroras glow, and although it is hot, the air is too thin to ignite meteors efficiently.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-6', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 3, 'According to the rock cycle, which process can convert igneous rock into sedimentary rock?', '["Melting followed by rapid cooling","Heat and pressure deep underground","Weathering, erosion, and compaction of the rock fragments","Volcanic uplift pushing the rock to the surface"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An igneous rock at the surface is exposed to weather. Rain, wind, ice, and biological activity break it into fragments, which rivers and gravity carry to lower ground. Layers pile up, get buried, and compact and cement into sedimentary rock through lithification. Melting and rapid cooling would just produce another igneous rock, not sedimentary. Heat and pressure deep underground transform existing rocks into metamorphic rocks like slate or marble. Volcanic uplift moves rock around but does not by itself change what type of rock it is. The route to sedimentary always passes through sediment.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 3, 'At which location would a hurricane most likely begin to weaken significantly?', '["Over warm tropical ocean water","When moving toward the equator","After making landfall or moving over cooler water","When it absorbs a nearby low-pressure system"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Hurricanes are heat engines fed by evaporation from ocean water warmer than about 26°C. Cut off that energy source and the storm dies. Moving over land removes the moisture supply and adds frictional drag, so storms decay quickly inland. Moving over cooler water has the same effect of starving the convection. Warm tropical ocean water is what fuels hurricanes, so it strengthens rather than weakens them. Hurricanes do not move toward the equator (they curve poleward due to Coriolis steering). Absorbing a low-pressure system can actually feed energy in, not drain it.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 4, 'Which type of plate boundary is associated with the formation of most of Earth''s major mountain ranges?', '["Divergent boundary, where plates move apart","Transform boundary, where plates slide past each other","Convergent boundary, where plates collide and compress","Subduction boundary, where oceanic plates sink under oceanic plates"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Major mountain ranges form where plates collide. The Himalayas rose from India ramming Eurasia, and the Alps rose from Africa pushing into Europe. Collision compresses and folds the crust upward over millions of years. Divergent boundaries pull apart and form rift valleys and mid-ocean ridges, not tall continental mountain belts. Transform boundaries grind past each other and produce earthquakes along faults like the San Andreas, not big ranges. Oceanic-on-oceanic subduction creates island arcs like Japan, which are mountainous but not the world''s major continental ranges. The biggest mountains come from continental crash.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 4, 'As altitude increases in the troposphere, air temperature generally:', '["Increases at a steady rate","Remains constant","Decreases","Increases then decreases"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Within the troposphere, temperature drops about 6.5°C for every 1,000 meters of climb, known as the environmental lapse rate. That is why mountaintops carry snow while valleys stay green and why airliner cabins need heating at cruise altitude. The pattern flips in the stratosphere right above, where ozone absorbs UV and warms the air with altitude. A constant temperature would describe the isothermal tropopause boundary, not the bulk troposphere. Increase then decrease describes the overall atmospheric profile across all layers, not the troposphere alone. Inside the troposphere the direction is simple: up means cooler.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 4, 'A star''s color is most directly related to its:', '["Size","Distance from Earth","Surface temperature","Age in the stellar lifecycle"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A star''s color is determined by its surface temperature: blue-white stars are hottest, yellow stars (like our Sun) are mid-range, and red stars are coolest. Distance affects apparent brightness, not color. Age and size influence temperature but are not the direct cause of color.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-11', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 5, 'Which phenomenon best explains why oceanic crust is generally younger than continental crust?', '["Oceanic crust forms faster due to more volcanic activity on land","Continental crust is recycled through subduction more rapidly","Oceanic crust is continuously created at mid-ocean ridges and destroyed at subduction zones","Tidal forces from the Moon preferentially age continental crust"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Oceanic crust is born at mid-ocean ridges where magma rises and solidifies, spreads outward like a conveyor belt, and is eventually pulled back into the mantle at deep-sea trenches. The full cycle takes about 200 million years, which is young in geological terms. Continental crust is less dense, so it floats and resists being subducted, accumulating ages up to 4 billion years. Saying continents recycle faster reverses the truth. Oceanic crust does not form on land. The Moon''s tides influence the oceans and slow Earth''s rotation but do not selectively age continental rock.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-12', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 5, 'During a lunar eclipse, the Moon appears reddish because:', '["The Moon reflects red light from nearby stars","Earth''s atmosphere scatters shorter wavelengths and refracts red light onto the Moon","The Moon''s own iron-rich surface reflects at a red wavelength","Sunlight heats the Moon''s surface, causing it to glow red"]'::jsonb, 1, 'During a lunar eclipse, Earth''s atmosphere acts like a lens: it scatters away blue wavelengths but bends (refracts) longer red and orange wavelengths into Earth''s shadow, illuminating the Moon with a reddish glow — the same physics that makes sunsets red.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Which type of energy does a moving car possess?', '["Chemical energy","Potential energy","Kinetic energy","Nuclear energy"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kinetic energy is the energy of motion, calculated as one-half mass times velocity squared. Any object moving has it: a rolling car, a thrown football, flowing river water. Chemical energy is stored in molecular bonds, like the gasoline in the tank before combustion, but once the engine burns it the energy converts and the car''s motion now carries kinetic energy. Potential energy is positional, like the same car parked at the top of a hill before it rolls. Nuclear energy comes from atomic nuclei in reactors or stars and has nothing to do with a normal car in motion.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'A wedge is a type of simple machine. The primary mechanical purpose of a wedge is to:', '["Change the direction of a force along a rope","Multiply rotational force through gears","Convert a downward force into an outward splitting force","Store energy that can be released later"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A wedge is essentially a moving inclined plane that takes a single push along its blunt end and redirects that force outward along its sloped faces, prying or splitting material apart. Axes, chisels, knives, and splitting mauls all work this way. Changing direction along a rope describes a pulley. Multiplying rotational force through gears describes a wheel-and-axle system or gear train, not a wedge. Storing energy describes a spring or capacitor, not a wedge, which simply redirects force during contact. The signature move of a wedge is conversion of one push into two outward separations.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'When you stretch a rubber band and hold it motionless, it has:', '["Kinetic energy only","No energy because it is not moving","Elastic potential energy","Thermal energy from being stretched"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Stretching a rubber band stores elastic potential energy — energy due to deformation. When released, this potential energy converts to kinetic energy. Thermal energy might increase slightly, but the dominant stored energy is elastic potential.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'Newton''s Second Law states that force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). If the net force on an object doubles while its mass stays the same, its acceleration will:', '["Stay the same","Double","Quadruple","Decrease by half"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rearrange F = ma to a = F/m. With mass held constant, acceleration scales directly with net force, so doubling force doubles acceleration. Quadrupling would only happen if force quadrupled or if mass were also halved. Decreasing by half would require mass to double (a is inversely proportional to mass at fixed F), but mass is fixed here. Staying the same is only true if force is unchanged. The mental shortcut: in F = ma, if one side doubles and one variable is held, the remaining variable must move in lockstep to keep the equation balanced.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 3, 'A first-class lever has the fulcrum between the effort and the load. Which of the following is an example of a first-class lever?', '["A wheelbarrow","A pair of scissors","A baseball bat","A bottle opener"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Scissors place the pivot pin between your hand on the handles (effort) and the material being cut at the blades (load), which is the defining setup of a first-class lever. Seesaws and crowbars work the same way. A wheelbarrow is a second-class lever because the load (cargo) sits between the fulcrum (wheel) and the effort (hands lifting handles). A baseball bat is a third-class lever because the effort (hand near the knob) sits between the fulcrum (other hand or shoulder) and the load (the ball at the barrel). A bottle opener is also second-class.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-6', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 3, 'If a 10-kg object is lifted 5 meters, how much gravitational potential energy does it gain? (Use g = 10 m/s²)', '["15 joules","50 joules","500 joules","5,000 joules"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Gravitational potential energy equals mass times g times height: 10 kg times 10 m/s² times 5 m equals 500 joules. The 50-joule answer drops the g factor and just multiplies mass by height, a common slip when students think of weight as a single number. The 15-joule answer adds the values instead of multiplying. The 5,000-joule answer adds an extra factor of 10, perhaps by using g = 100 by mistake. Keep the formula PE = mgh in mind and plug in carefully; each piece must be there and in the right units.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 3, 'Friction always acts in what direction relative to an object''s motion?', '["Perpendicular to motion","In the same direction as motion","Opposite to the direction of motion","Downward due to gravity"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Friction is a resistive force that always points opposite to the direction of motion (or the tendency to move). Slide a box right and friction pushes left; brakes work because friction between pads and rotor opposes the wheel''s spin. Acting in the same direction as motion would describe a propelling force, not friction, which would mean friction speeds objects up instead of slowing them. Perpendicular to motion describes the normal force, the support force from a surface. Downward describes gravity, which is unrelated to friction''s direction. Friction always pushes back against whatever motion is happening.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 4, 'A 4-kg block slides down a frictionless ramp and reaches the bottom with a speed of 6 m/s. What is its kinetic energy at the bottom?', '["24 joules","48 joules","72 joules","144 joules"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kinetic energy equals one-half mass times velocity squared: 0.5 times 4 kg times 6² equals 0.5 times 4 times 36, which equals 72 joules. The 144-joule answer forgets the one-half factor and just multiplies 4 times 36. The 48-joule answer uses 6 instead of 6², dropping the velocity-squared term entirely. The 24-joule answer halves 48, compounding two errors. The KE formula has three pieces (½, mass, velocity squared); skip any one and the answer drifts to a distractor. Always square the velocity before multiplying by mass and half.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 4, 'What is the mechanical advantage of a lever when the effort arm is 3 meters and the load arm is 1 meter?', '["0.33","1","3","4"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Mechanical advantage of a lever equals the effort arm length divided by the load arm length: 3 divided by 1 equals 3. This means a force applied at the effort end can lift a load three times heavier. The 0.33 answer inverts the ratio (load divided by effort) and would describe a lever working against you, useful only for speed or distance multiplication. The MA of 1 implies the arms are equal, like a balance scale, which they are not here. The MA of 4 would require the effort arm to be 4 times the load arm, not 3. Always: effort length over load length.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 5, 'A 2-kg ball is dropped from 20 meters above the ground. At 10 meters height (halfway down), ignoring air resistance, what is its approximate kinetic energy? (g = 10 m/s²)', '["100 joules","200 joules","300 joules","400 joules"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Initial PE at 20 m = mgh = 2 × 10 × 20 = 400 J. At 10 m, remaining PE = 2 × 10 × 10 = 200 J. By conservation of energy, KE gained = 400 − 200 = 200 J. You do not need to calculate velocity separately.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'According to Ohm''s Law, if the voltage across a resistor is 10 volts and the resistance is 5 ohms, the current through the resistor is:', '["0.5 amperes","1 ampere","2 amperes","50 amperes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ohm''s Law: I = V / R = 10 V / 5 Ω = 2 A. Current is 2 amperes. Choice A (0.5 A) inverts the formula and divides R by V (5 / 10). Choice B (1 A) subtracts instead of dividing (10 minus 5, halved by some misstep) or applies a guessed ratio. Choice D (50 A) multiplies V by R, treating Ohm''s Law as if voltage times resistance produces current. The formula is strictly division: voltage over resistance equals current.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'Electrical power in a circuit is calculated using the formula P = IV. If a device draws 3 amperes from a 12-volt source, its power consumption is:', '["4 watts","9 watts","15 watts","36 watts"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Power formula: P = I × V = 3 A × 12 V = 36 W. The device consumes 36 watts. Choice A (4 W) divides V by I (12 / 3), confusing the power formula with Ohm''s Law for resistance. Choice B (9 W) squares current (3²) and ignores voltage. Choice C (15 W) adds the two values (12 + 3) instead of multiplying. Power in a DC circuit is always the product of voltage and current, never the sum or quotient of those quantities.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'Using P = I²R, what power is dissipated by a 4-ohm resistor carrying 5 amperes?', '["20 watts","40 watts","80 watts","100 watts"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Use P = I²R. Square the current first: 5² = 25. Then multiply by resistance: 25 × 4 = 100 W. The resistor dissipates 100 watts. Choice A (20 W) computes I × R (5 × 4) and forgets to square. Choice B (40 W) doubles I × R or applies 2 × I × R, which is not a power formula. Choice C (80 W) doubles the I × R result. Squaring current is essential because power grows with the square of current, not linearly.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 3, 'Four resistors of 10 ohms each are connected in series. What is the total resistance of the circuit?', '["2.5 ohms","10 ohms","40 ohms","1,000 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Series resistors add directly: Rt = 10 + 10 + 10 + 10 = 40 Ω. Total resistance is 40 ohms. Choice A (2.5 Ω) misapplies the parallel formula, computing 10 / 4 instead of 10 × 4. Choice B (10 Ω) leaves resistance unchanged, ignoring that each added resistor stacks more opposition in the single current path. Choice D (1,000 Ω) multiplies the resistors (10 × 10 × 10) instead of summing them. In series, the values stack additively because current crosses each in sequence.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 3, 'A 100-watt appliance runs on 200 volts. Using P = V²/R, what is its resistance?', '["2 ohms","50 ohms","400 ohms","20,000 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Rearrange P = V² / R to R = V² / P. Square voltage: 200² = 40,000. Divide by power: 40,000 / 100 = 400 Ω. Resistance is 400 ohms. Choice A (2 Ω) divides V by P (200 / 100) and skips squaring entirely. Choice C (50 Ω) divides P by an arbitrary factor or computes V / (2P). Choice D (20,000 Ω) divides V² by 2 instead of P, or otherwise mishandles the divisor. The V² term is non-negotiable when the formula uses V² / R.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 3, 'Three resistors — 2 ohms, 3 ohms, and 5 ohms — are connected in series to a 20-volt battery. What is the current in the circuit?', '["0.5 amperes","1 ampere","2 amperes","4 amperes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add series resistances: Rt = 2 + 3 + 5 = 10 Ω. Apply Ohm''s Law: I = V / Rt = 20 V / 10 Ω = 2 A. Current is 2 amperes. Choice A (0.5 A) divides Rt by V (10 / 20) and inverts the formula. Choice B (1 A) uses only part of the resistance or divides by 20 instead of 10. Choice D (4 A) uses only the 5-ohm resistor (20 / 5), forgetting that current sees the full series stack, not one component.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 4, 'A 24-volt source powers three identical resistors connected in parallel. If each resistor is 12 ohms, what is the total current drawn from the source?', '["0.67 amperes","2 amperes","4 amperes","6 amperes"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Each parallel branch sees the full 24 V. Branch current = 24 / 12 = 2 A. With three identical branches, total current = 3 × 2 = 6 A. Cross-check: parallel resistance = 12 / 3 = 4 Ω; total I = 24 / 4 = 6 A. Choice A (0.67 A) divides voltage by series total (24 / 36) as if the resistors were in series. Choice B (2 A) reports only one branch. Choice C (4 A) reports only two branches or uses parallel resistance as branch current.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 4, 'A 10-ohm resistor and a 15-ohm resistor are connected in parallel. What is the combined resistance? (Express your answer as a fraction or decimal.)', '["25 ohms","12.5 ohms","6 ohms","5 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, '1/R = 1/10 + 1/15 = 3/30 + 2/30 = 5/30 = 1/6, so R = 6 ohms. Adding resistances (25) is the series formula. Averaging (12.5) is not a valid circuit rule. In parallel, result is always less than the smallest individual resistor (10 ohms).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 5, 'A series circuit with a 30-volt source contains two resistors: R₁ = 6 ohms and R₂ = 4 ohms. What is the voltage drop across R₁?', '["6 volts","12 volts","18 volts","24 volts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total resistance = 6 + 4 = 10 Ω. Circuit current = 30 V / 10 Ω = 3 A. Voltage across R1 = I × R1 = 3 × 6 = 18 V. By the voltage divider rule, R1 takes 6/10 = 60% of source voltage, and 60% of 30 V is 18 V. Choice A (6 V) reports the resistance value as if it were a voltage. Choice B (12 V) gives the drop across R2 instead. Choice D (24 V) inverts the ratio and assigns R1 80% of the source.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 5, 'A device with 50 ohms of resistance must dissipate exactly 200 watts. What supply voltage is required?', '["10 volts","50 volts","100 volts","4 volts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use P = V² / R, so V² = P × R = 200 × 50 = 10,000, and V = √10,000 = 100 V. Cross-check with two-step path: I = √(P/R) = √4 = 2 A, then V = IR = 2 × 50 = 100 V. Choice A (10 V) takes √(P) and ignores R, or divides incorrectly. Choice B (50 V) reports the resistance value. Choice D (4 V) divides P by 50 to get 4 and stops, skipping the square root step that the V² relationship requires.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 4, 'If resistance in a circuit doubles while voltage stays constant, what happens to the current?', '["It doubles","It remains the same","It is cut in half","It increases by the square of the resistance"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ohm''s Law: I = V / R. With V constant and R doubled, new current = V / (2R), which is half the original. Current is cut in half. Choice A (doubles) assumes a direct relationship, but current is inversely proportional to resistance, not directly. Choice B (stays the same) ignores the formula entirely. Choice D (squares the resistance) confuses Ohm''s Law with the I²R power expression. Only one variable changed here, and the inverse relationship between I and R settles the result.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'In a parallel circuit, the voltage across each branch compared to the source voltage is:', '["Less than the source voltage","Equal to the source voltage","Greater than the source voltage","Divided equally among branches"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In a parallel circuit, every branch connects directly to the same two source nodes, so each branch sees the full source voltage. That is the defining property. Choice A (less than source) describes a series component, where voltage divides across each resistor. Choice C (greater than source) violates energy conservation; no passive component creates voltage. Choice D (divided equally among branches) confuses parallel voltage behavior with current behavior, where current does split among branches according to each branch''s resistance, but voltage stays equal across all branches.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'In a series circuit, the current through each component is:', '["Different for each component based on its resistance","The same throughout the entire circuit","Zero if any component has high resistance","Split between components based on their resistance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A series circuit has one path for current, so the same current passes through every component. Voltage divides across them based on resistance, but current does not. Choice A (different per component) confuses current with voltage; voltage varies in series, current does not. Choice C (zero with one high resistor) is wrong because high resistance reduces current but does not stop it unless the component is fully open. Choice D (splits among components) describes parallel behavior, where multiple paths share the total current.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-3', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'Three light bulbs are connected in parallel to a battery. One bulb burns out (open circuit). What happens to the other two bulbs?', '["They also go out because the circuit is broken","They dim slightly because total resistance decreases","They continue to glow normally","They burn brighter because they now draw more current"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Each bulb in a parallel circuit has its own independent loop from source to source. When one bulb opens, only that branch breaks; the other branches still see the full source voltage and full branch current. The remaining bulbs glow normally. Choice A (all go out) describes series behavior. Choice B (dim slightly) gets the direction wrong; if anything, total resistance rises and total current falls, but per-branch voltage and current do not change. Choice D (burn brighter) confuses branches with a series voltage redistribution that does not happen here.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'A series circuit with a 9-volt battery and two resistors (3 ohms and 6 ohms) carries a current of 1 ampere. What is the voltage drop across the 6-ohm resistor?', '["1.5 volts","3 volts","6 volts","9 volts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'V = I × R = 1 × 6 = 6 volts across the 6-ohm resistor. The 3-ohm resistor drops 3 volts, and 3 + 6 = 9 V confirms Kirchhoff''s Voltage Law. Using the full 9 volts across one resistor is a common error.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 3, 'Adding more resistors in parallel to an existing circuit will:', '["Increase total resistance and decrease total current","Decrease total resistance and increase total current","Have no effect on total current from the source","Decrease voltage at the source"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Adding parallel resistors means 1/Rt = 1/R1 + 1/R2 + 1/R3 + ..., and each new term increases the right side, which lowers Rt. With source voltage fixed, I = V / Rt rises. Choice A reverses the direction; parallel branches do not raise resistance, they lower it. Choice C ignores Ohm''s Law; total current must respond when total resistance shifts. Choice D confuses load behavior with source behavior; an ideal source holds voltage constant, and even a real source''s voltage drop would be a secondary effect, not the primary outcome.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 3, 'In a series circuit, adding a resistor will:', '["Decrease total resistance and increase current","Increase total resistance and decrease current","Keep current the same because voltage adjusts","Only affect the components after it in the circuit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Series resistances add: Rt = R1 + R2 + R3 + ... So a new series resistor raises total resistance. By Ohm''s Law I = V / Rt, with V constant, higher Rt means lower current through the entire loop. Choice A reverses the direction; series additions cannot lower resistance. Choice C invokes a self-adjusting voltage that the source does not perform. Choice D claims only downstream components feel the change, but a series loop carries one current value everywhere; every component upstream or downstream sees the same reduced current.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 3, 'Kirchhoff''s Current Law states that the total current entering a junction in a circuit equals the total current leaving it. This law applies to which circuit type as a core analysis tool?', '["Series circuits only","Open circuits only","Parallel and combination circuits","Only DC battery circuits"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kirchhoff''s Current Law operates at junctions where current splits or merges. Pure series circuits have no junctions; the same current flows through every component, so KCL is trivially true and offers no analytical leverage. Parallel and combination circuits are where KCL earns its keep, balancing inflow against outflow at each node. Choice A picks the one topology where KCL is unnecessary. Choice B (open circuits) carries no current at all. Choice D (DC battery only) invents a restriction; KCL holds for AC and DC alike.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 4, 'A circuit has two branches in parallel: Branch A draws 4 amperes and Branch B draws 2 amperes. The source voltage is 12 volts. What is the resistance of Branch B?', '["2 ohms","4 ohms","6 ohms","24 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In parallel, each branch sees 12 volts. R_B = V/I_B = 12/2 = 6 ohms. Do not add the branch currents before calculating resistance — each branch is analyzed independently with the full source voltage.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 4, 'A switch is placed in the main line of a parallel circuit (before the branches split). If this switch is opened, what happens?', '["Only the first branch loses power","All branches lose power simultaneously","Branches alternate between on and off","The branch with the highest resistance loses power first"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A switch in the main line sits before the current splits into parallel branches. Opening it breaks the only path connecting all branches to the source, so every branch loses power at once. This is exactly how a main breaker cuts a whole panel. Choice A (only first branch) describes a switch placed inside one branch, not the main line. Choice C (alternating on/off) describes oscillator behavior, not a static switch. Choice D (highest-resistance branch first) invents a sequencing rule that does not exist in DC circuit analysis.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 4, 'A combination circuit has a 2-ohm resistor in series with a parallel combination of a 4-ohm and 4-ohm resistor. What is the total circuit resistance?', '["10 ohms","6 ohms","4 ohms","2 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'First combine the parallel pair: 4 Ω || 4 Ω = 4 / 2 = 2 Ω. Then add the series 2 Ω: Rt = 2 + 2 = 4 Ω. Total circuit resistance is 4 ohms. Choice A (10 Ω) adds all three values as if everything were in series. Choice B (6 Ω) leaves the 4-ohm pair uncombined or sums 2 + 4 once. Choice D (2 Ω) reports only the parallel combination and forgets the series 2-ohm resistor. Combination circuits demand reducing parallel sections first, then summing what remains.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 5, 'In a series circuit with a 48-volt source and three resistors (R₁ = 8 Ω, R₂ = 4 Ω, R₃ = 4 Ω), what percentage of the source voltage appears across R₁?', '["25%","33%","50%","75%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Series total: Rt = 8 + 4 + 4 = 16 Ω. Current = 48 / 16 = 3 A. Voltage across R1 = 3 × 8 = 24 V. Percentage = 24 / 48 = 50%. Voltage-divider shortcut: R1 is 8/16 = 50% of total resistance, so it takes 50% of source voltage. Choice A (25%) treats R1 as one of four equal parts. Choice B (33%) divides by component count (3) instead of resistance share. Choice D (75%) inverts the ratio, giving R1 the share that belongs to R2 and R3 combined.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 5, 'Two batteries, each 6 volts with internal resistance of 1 ohm, are connected in series and power a 10-ohm external load. What is the current through the load?', '["0.5 amperes","1 ampere","1.2 amperes","2 amperes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total voltage = 6 + 6 = 12 V. Total resistance = 1 + 1 + 10 = 12 Ω (internal resistances add in series). Current = 12/12 = 1 ampere. Ignoring internal resistance gives 12/10 = 1.2 A — a common error on multi-battery problems.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A capacitor in an electrical circuit primarily functions to:', '["Amplify the voltage in the circuit","Allow current to flow in one direction only","Store electrical energy in an electric field","Convert AC to DC"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A capacitor stores energy in an electric field between two conductive plates separated by an insulator (dielectric). It charges when voltage is applied and releases that energy when the circuit demands. A diode, not a capacitor, allows one-directional current flow.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A resistor is used in an electrical circuit mainly to:', '["Store charge for later use","Limit the amount of current flowing through a component","Convert AC voltage to DC voltage","Step up or step down voltage levels"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Resistors oppose current flow, with opposition measured in ohms. Ohm''s Law (I = V / R) shows directly how a resistor sets the current for a given voltage, which is how engineers limit current to protect LEDs, transistors, and other sensitive parts. Choice A (store charge) describes a capacitor, which holds energy in an electric field. Choice C (AC to DC) describes a rectifier built from diodes. Choice D (step voltage) describes a transformer, which uses electromagnetic induction to change AC voltage levels.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-3', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'An inductor stores energy in a:', '["Chemical battery cell","Magnetic field","Electric field between plates","Mechanical flywheel"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An inductor is a coil of wire. Current through the coil creates a magnetic field, and energy is stored in that field. When current changes, the collapsing or rising field induces a back-EMF that opposes the change. Choice A (chemical cell) describes a battery, where energy is locked in chemical bonds. Choice C (electric field between plates) describes a capacitor, the inductor''s complement, which stores energy in an electric field across a dielectric. Choice D (mechanical flywheel) stores kinetic energy and is not an electrical component at all.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'Which device is used to step up or step down alternating current voltage levels in power distribution systems?', '["Rectifier","Transistor","Transformer","Capacitor"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A transformer uses electromagnetic induction between primary and secondary coils to step AC voltage up or down according to the turns ratio. Power grids step voltage up to hundreds of thousands of volts for low-loss transmission, then step it back down for delivery. Choice A (rectifier) converts AC to DC and does not change AC voltage levels. Choice B (transistor) amplifies or switches signals, mostly in DC and small-signal contexts. Choice D (capacitor) filters and stores charge but cannot transform voltage levels in a sustained AC distribution system.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 3, 'A light-emitting diode (LED) converts electrical energy primarily into:', '["Heat and mechanical energy equally","Light energy with minimal heat","Chemical energy stored in a capacitor","Alternating current from direct current"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LEDs convert electrical energy into light through electroluminescence in a semiconductor junction. They are far more efficient than incandescent bulbs, which waste most energy as heat. LEDs do not convert AC to DC or store chemical energy.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 3, 'A transistor can be used as an electronic switch because it can:', '["Block all current from flowing in either direction","Store charge and release it on command","Control a large output current with a small input (base) current","Convert AC to DC by allowing current in one direction only"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In a bipolar junction transistor, a small base current controls a much larger collector-to-emitter current. Zero base current leaves the transistor off (open switch); enough base current saturates it on (closed switch). That gain is what makes amplifiers and digital logic possible. Choice A describes an open circuit or insulator, not a switching device. Choice B describes a capacitor''s storage behavior, not a transistor''s gain. Choice D describes a diode''s one-way conduction. Transistors do more than diode action; they amplify.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 3, 'Which component would most likely be used to filter out high-frequency noise from a DC power supply while allowing the steady DC current to pass?', '["A resistor in series","A capacitor in parallel with the load","A diode in reverse bias","An additional battery"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capacitors pass AC (and AC noise) but block steady DC. Placing one in parallel with the load creates a low-impedance path for high-frequency noise to bypass the load while the desired DC current continues through. This is called decoupling or bypass capacitor usage.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 4, 'A transformer has 200 turns on its primary and 50 turns on its secondary. If the primary carries 1 ampere, what is the secondary current (assuming 100% efficiency)?', '["0.25 amperes","1 ampere","4 amperes","10 amperes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An ideal transformer conserves power: Vp × Ip = Vs × Is. The turns ratio Np / Ns = 200 / 50 = 4, so this is a step-down transformer for voltage and a step-up for current. Is = Ip × (Np / Ns) = 1 × 4 = 4 A. Choice A (0.25 A) inverts the ratio (50 / 200), which gives the secondary voltage scale, not the current. Choice B (1 A) assumes current is unchanged, ignoring the inverse relationship. Choice D (10 A) uses an invented multiplier rather than the actual turns ratio.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 4, 'A Zener diode is connected in reverse bias in a circuit. Its primary application is to:', '["Block all current completely in that branch","Amplify voltage to a higher level","Regulate voltage by maintaining a constant voltage drop","Convert AC to DC in a rectifier bridge"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A Zener diode is engineered to break down at a precise reverse voltage and then hold that voltage steady across itself, even as current through it varies. That clamp action makes it ideal as a voltage reference or regulator. Choice A (block all current) describes a non-conducting open. Choice B (amplify voltage) describes a transistor or op-amp, not a passive diode. Choice D (AC-to-DC bridge) describes standard rectifier diodes; Zener diodes are used specifically for regulation, not for steering AC into DC pulses.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 4, 'Which effect describes how an inductor resists changes in current by generating a back-EMF (electromotive force)?', '["Capacitance","Self-inductance","Dielectric effect","Zener breakdown"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Self-inductance is the property by which a coil''s own changing current induces a voltage in itself, and that induced voltage opposes the change (Lenz''s Law applied to Faraday''s Law). It is measured in henries. Choice A (capacitance) opposes voltage changes by storing charge, not by generating back-EMF. Choice C (dielectric effect) describes how an insulator between capacitor plates increases capacitance, unrelated to current opposition. Choice D (Zener breakdown) describes a diode entering reverse conduction at a fixed voltage, not an inductor''s reaction to changing current.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 5, 'A full-wave bridge rectifier using four diodes converts AC to pulsating DC. Compared to a half-wave rectifier (one diode), the bridge rectifier:', '["Doubles the output voltage","Uses both halves of the AC cycle, producing smoother DC output at twice the frequency","Reverses the polarity of the DC output","Requires a transformer, whereas the half-wave rectifier does not"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A half-wave rectifier passes only one half-cycle of the AC input, wasting the other half. The bridge rectifier flips the negative half-cycle to positive using a diode arrangement, utilizing both halves. The output pulsates at twice the AC frequency and is smoother (easier to filter). Voltage is not doubled.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 5, 'In a radio receiver circuit, an LC (inductor-capacitor) tank circuit is used primarily to:', '["Amplify received signals across all frequencies equally","Convert radio waves into alternating current","Select a specific resonant frequency and filter out others","Step down the antenna voltage before processing"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An LC tank circuit resonates at a specific frequency f = 1/(2π√LC), creating high impedance at that frequency and low impedance at others. Adjusting L or C (tuning) selects a desired station. The circuit is a tunable bandpass filter, not an amplifier or antenna converter.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Which of the following materials is the best electrical insulator?', '["Aluminum","Graphite","Silver","Ceramic"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Ceramic has extremely high resistivity and is the standard insulator on overhead power-line standoffs and inside spark plugs. Choice A (aluminum) is a common conductor used in transmission lines and wiring. Choice B (graphite) is a form of carbon that conducts well enough to be used in motor brushes and electrodes. Choice C (silver) has the highest electrical conductivity of any metal at room temperature. Three of the four options conduct readily, which is the giveaway that the lone insulator is the answer.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Electrical wiring is typically covered in a plastic jacket primarily because plastic is:', '["A good conductor that improves current flow","Flexible, cheap, and an effective insulator","A semiconductor that limits dangerous voltage spikes","A material that cools the wire during use"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Plastic (PVC and similar polymers) insulates by preventing current from escaping the conductor and causing short circuits or shock hazards. Its flexibility and low cost make it ideal for wire jacketing. Plastic does not conduct or regulate electricity.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-3', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'Gold is used in some high-quality electrical connectors despite its high cost because:', '["Gold has higher conductivity than any other metal","Gold is non-corrosive and maintains low contact resistance over time","Gold''s weight improves mechanical connection strength","Gold stores electrical charge better than copper"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gold does not oxidize in air, so gold-plated contacts keep a low, stable contact resistance for years. That matters more than raw conductivity in connector design, where surface chemistry dominates over time. Choice A (highest conductivity) is wrong; silver and copper both conduct better than gold. Choice C (weight) has no electrical relevance; mechanical force comes from spring contacts, not metal mass. Choice D (stores charge) confuses connector metal with a capacitor; conductors do not store charge in any useful sense in a connector.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'When the temperature of most metals increases, their electrical resistance:', '["Decreases because the electrons move faster","Stays the same regardless of temperature","Increases because atomic vibrations impede electron flow","Drops to zero because the metal becomes a superconductor"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In most metals, higher temperature means more vigorous atomic vibration, which causes more electron-lattice collisions. More collisions mean more resistance. That positive temperature coefficient is what lets PTC thermistors and incandescent filaments self-limit. Choice A (decreases) gets the direction wrong; faster electrons do not overcome the increased scattering. Choice B (unchanged) ignores temperature dependence that is well measured for copper, aluminum, and tungsten. Choice D (superconductivity) only occurs in specific materials cooled well below room temperature, not from ordinary heating.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 3, 'Silicon is classified as a semiconductor because its conductivity:', '["Is equal to that of copper at all temperatures","Can be precisely controlled by temperature, light, or the addition of impurities (doping)","Is zero until voltage exceeds a fixed threshold","Depends only on the current direction, like a diode"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Silicon''s conductivity is tunable. Doping with phosphorus adds free electrons (n-type), doping with boron adds holes (p-type), heating excites carriers across the band gap, and light injects photogenerated carriers. That control is the entire basis for transistors, diodes, solar cells, and integrated circuits. Choice A (equals copper) overstates pure silicon''s conductivity by many orders of magnitude. Choice C (fixed threshold) describes a Zener-like behavior, not the broad tunability of silicon. Choice D (direction-dependent) describes a diode junction, not bulk silicon material.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 3, 'The dielectric in a capacitor is an insulating material placed between the plates. Its primary purpose is to:', '["Allow electrons to tunnel between the plates and store charge","Increase the capacitance by allowing a stronger electric field to build up","Convert stored energy into heat for circuit protection","Conduct alternating current while blocking direct current"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The dielectric material has a high permittivity that allows the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage, increasing capacitance (C = ε × A/d). The insulator prevents electrons from crossing between plates; charge is stored in the electric field, not by electron transfer.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 3, 'An electrical wire''s resistance depends on which of the following properties?', '["Only the length of the wire","Length, cross-sectional area, and material resistivity","Cross-sectional area and the voltage applied","The current passing through it at any given moment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Wire resistance R = ρ × L / A, where ρ is material resistivity, L is length, and A is cross-sectional area. Longer, thinner wire of more resistive material has higher resistance. Applied voltage and current are results of resistance, not causes of it.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 4, 'Two copper wires are identical in length. Wire A has twice the cross-sectional area of Wire B. How does the resistance of Wire A compare to Wire B?', '["Wire A has twice the resistance of Wire B","Wire A has the same resistance as Wire B","Wire A has half the resistance of Wire B","Wire A has four times the resistance of Wire B"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Resistance follows R = ρL / A. With L and ρ constant and A_A = 2 × A_B, R_A = ρL / (2 × A_B) = R_B / 2. Doubling cross-sectional area halves the resistance, because a thicker wire offers more parallel paths for electrons. Choice A (double) gets the direction backward; more area lowers resistance, not raises it. Choice B (same) ignores that area appears in the resistance formula at all. Choice D (four times) treats area as if it appeared squared in R = ρL/A, which it does not.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 4, 'Which statement correctly explains why copper is preferred over iron for electrical wiring despite iron being more abundant?', '["Copper has a lower melting point, making it easier to form into wire","Copper has much lower resistivity than iron, meaning less energy is lost as heat","Copper is magnetic, which helps carry alternating current","Iron corrodes rapidly in air, and copper does not oxidize at all"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Copper''s resistivity (~1.68 μΩ·cm) is about six times lower than iron''s (~10 μΩ·cm), so copper wire wastes far less energy as heat. This efficiency advantage outweighs the cost difference. Copper does oxidize slightly but forms a stable, low-resistance patina; iron rusts severely.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 5, 'A 10-meter copper wire has a resistance of 0.2 ohms. If the wire is replaced with a 20-meter wire of the same material and the same cross-sectional area, what is the new resistance?', '["0.1 ohms","0.2 ohms","0.4 ohms","0.8 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'R = ρL / A is linear in length. Doubling L from 10 m to 20 m while holding A and material constant doubles the resistance: 2 × 0.2 = 0.4 Ω. Choice A (0.1 Ω) halves resistance, which would happen if length were halved instead of doubled. Choice B (0.2 Ω) leaves resistance unchanged, ignoring the length dependence entirely. Choice D (0.8 Ω) quadruples resistance, treating length as if it appeared squared in the formula, when in fact only the cross-section can change resistance non-linearly through area.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 5, 'N-type semiconductor material is created by doping silicon with an element that has more valence electrons than silicon. Which of the following dopants creates an n-type semiconductor?', '["Boron (3 valence electrons)","Aluminum (3 valence electrons)","Phosphorus (5 valence electrons)","Carbon (4 valence electrons)"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Silicon has 4 valence electrons. Phosphorus has 5, so each phosphorus atom contributes one extra electron not needed for covalent bonding. That free electron becomes a mobile negative charge carrier, producing n-type silicon. Choice A (boron, 3 valence) creates p-type silicon by introducing holes. Choice B (aluminum, 3 valence) also creates p-type material. Choice D (carbon, 4 valence) matches silicon''s valence count exactly, so it contributes neither extra electrons nor holes and would not produce useful doping for n-type or p-type behavior.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 4, 'Which of the following most accurately describes why distilled water is a poor conductor while seawater conducts electricity well?', '["Seawater contains more hydrogen, which improves conductivity","Distilled water has no dissolved ions, while seawater''s dissolved salts provide free ions that carry charge","Distilled water molecules resist current because of their polarity","The pressure of the ocean compresses seawater, increasing conductivity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Liquid conduction depends on free charge carriers. Distilled water has almost no dissolved ions, so it has very few mobile charges and conducts poorly. Seawater holds dissolved NaCl, MgCl₂, and other salts that dissociate into Na⁺, Cl⁻, and Mg²⁺ ions, which carry charge freely. Choice A (more hydrogen) is wrong; both waters share the same H₂O molecules. Choice C blames water''s polarity, but polarity alone does not block conduction. Choice D invokes pressure, which has a negligible effect on conductivity compared with ion concentration.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which hand tool is used to tighten or loosen nuts and bolts and has an opening that can be adjusted to fit different fastener sizes?', '["Adjustable wrench","Needle-nose pliers","Cold chisel","Ball-peen hammer"]'::jsonb, 0, 'An adjustable wrench, often called a crescent wrench, has a thumbwheel that slides one jaw in and out so a single tool fits a range of hex nuts and bolts. Needle-nose pliers are for gripping small wires and parts in tight spots and will round the corners of any fastener you try to drive with them. A cold chisel is a striking tool for cutting metal, not for fasteners. A ball-peen hammer is used to shape metal and strike punches. Only the adjustable wrench is designed to set its opening to a fastener size.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'A mechanic needs to grip a round pipe firmly while cutting threads onto it. Which tool is designed specifically to hold cylindrical workpieces without slipping?', '["Slip-joint pliers","Pipe wrench","Box-end wrench","Offset screwdriver"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A pipe wrench has hardened, toothed jaws set at an angle so that pulling on the handle drives the teeth deeper into the round pipe, locking the grip tighter the harder you pull. Slip-joint pliers can hold a pipe but the jaws will rotate around the work under any real torque. A box-end wrench is shaped to wrap a six- or twelve-point hex fastener and will not grip a smooth cylinder at all. An offset screwdriver is for turning screws in cramped spots. Only the pipe wrench is built for round stock.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A torque wrench is used instead of a standard socket wrench when:', '["you need to reach fasteners in deep recesses","tightening fasteners to a precise torque specification is required","the fastener head is stripped and will not grip","you are working in a tight space and need a ratcheting motion"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A torque wrench has a calibrated mechanism that signals or limits at a preset value, letting you tighten a fastener to the exact specification a manufacturer calls out for head bolts, lug nuts, or connecting rods. Reaching deep recesses is what a socket extension solves, not a torque wrench. A stripped fastener head needs an extractor or vise grips, not torque measurement. Tight-space ratcheting is offered by any ratchet handle, including non-torque ones. The defining feature is the calibrated measurement, not the reach or the ratcheting.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'What is the primary purpose of a center punch when working with metal?', '["To scribe a straight line across the workpiece","To mark a starting point so a drill bit does not wander","To remove burrs from a drilled hole","To cut a hole in sheet metal without a drill"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A center punch is struck with a hammer to dimple the metal at the spot where a hole will be drilled, and that dimple cups the drill point so the bit starts where you intended instead of wandering across the surface. Scribing a straight line is the job of a scriber or a square. Removing burrs from a drilled hole is what a deburring tool or countersink does. Cutting a hole in sheet metal without a drill calls for a hole punch or knockout, not a center punch. Center punches mark, they do not cut or scribe.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A technician selects a drill bit with a twist-style cutting flute and a 118-degree included angle tip. This bit is best suited for drilling:', '["concrete and masonry","general-purpose holes in steel or aluminum","glass and ceramic tile","large-diameter holes in wood only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A standard high-speed steel twist bit with a 118-degree tip is the everyday bit for drilling steel, aluminum, and brass, and it is what comes in a typical mechanic''s index. Concrete and masonry require a carbide-tipped masonry bit driven by a hammer drill, because HSS cannot cut stone. Glass and ceramic tile need a spear-point or diamond bit and very slow speed to avoid cracking. Wood-only large-diameter holes are the territory of spade bits, Forstner bits, or hole saws. The 118-degree point geometry is the giveaway for general metal work.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 3, 'A vise-grip (locking pliers) differs from standard slip-joint pliers in that a vise-grip:', '["can be used as a wrench on hex fasteners only","locks onto a workpiece and maintains clamping force without the user squeezing","is used exclusively for cutting wire","adjusts automatically to the size of the fastener"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Locking pliers, often called Vise-Grips, use an over-center toggle linkage that snaps the jaws shut and holds them there without any hand pressure, freeing both of your hands and applying steady clamping force. Slip-joint pliers and channel locks need a constant squeeze to hold anything. The pliers are not limited to hex fasteners and can grip almost any shape. Wire cutting is a feature of dedicated cutters or a small notch on some pliers, not the defining feature here. They do not auto-adjust to fastener size; the user sets the jaw with a thumbscrew.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 3, 'A combination square is primarily used to:', '["apply torque to hex fasteners in tight spaces","measure and mark 90-degree and 45-degree angles on a workpiece","hold a workpiece in place during cutting","thread bolts onto nuts in hard-to-reach locations"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A combination square consists of a rule and a sliding head that provides both 90-degree and 45-degree reference angles. It is used to mark cut lines, check squareness, and verify miters. It does not apply torque or hold workpieces.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 3, 'A snap-ring pliers set includes two types of tips. One type spreads a ring outward to remove an external snap ring; the other type squeezes a ring inward to remove an internal snap ring. Why must the correct type be used?', '["Using the wrong type will damage the pliers'' handles","Using the wrong type moves the ring in the wrong direction and can launch it unexpectedly or distort it","Both types are interchangeable; choice depends only on ring size","The wrong type will strip the threading on the fastener"]'::jsonb, 1, 'External snap rings are compressed to fit into a shaft groove; internal rings are expanded to fit inside a bore groove. Using expanding pliers on an external ring — or compressing pliers on an internal ring — pushes the ring the wrong way, risking sudden release and possible injury or ring damage.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 4, 'A mechanic describes a tool as having a T-shaped handle, with a square drive that accepts interchangeable sockets, and a ratcheting pawl that allows rotation in one direction without removing the tool from the fastener. What tool is being described?', '["Breaker bar","Speed handle","Ratchet wrench","Flex-head torque wrench"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A ratchet wrench has a reversible ratcheting mechanism that lets the user turn the handle back without moving the fastener, then apply torque again on the next forward stroke. A breaker bar provides high torque but does not ratchet; a speed handle spins freely but also lacks a ratchet pawl.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 4, 'When measuring a shaft''s outside diameter, a technician reads a micrometer thimble scale and finds the sleeve reading is 0.350 inches and the thimble adds 0.012 inches. What is the total measured diameter?', '["0.338 inches","0.350 inches","0.362 inches","0.412 inches"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A micrometer reading combines the barrel (sleeve) measurement and the thimble graduation. Total = 0.350 + 0.012 = 0.362 inches. Subtracting instead of adding (0.350 − 0.012 = 0.338) is a common error; the thimble always adds to the sleeve reading.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 4, 'A technician wants to cut an external thread onto a steel rod so a nut can be threaded onto it. Which hand tool accomplishes this?', '["Tap","Die","Reamer","Broach"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A die cuts external threads onto a rod or bolt. A tap cuts internal threads inside a hole (to accept a bolt). A reamer smooths and sizes a drilled hole to a precise diameter but does not cut threads.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 5, 'A star-pattern torque sequence is specified when installing a cylinder head. Why is this sequence used instead of tightening bolts in order from one end to the other?', '["To finish faster by tightening the center bolts last","To distribute clamping load evenly and prevent the gasket from warping or sealing unevenly","Because cylinder head bolts are left-hand threaded on alternating positions","To allow the bolts to be re-tightened after the engine warms up"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A star or criss-cross pattern pulls the cylinder head down against the gasket from the center outward in stepped increments, so clamping load builds evenly across every bolt and the gasket compresses uniformly. Tightening end-to-end pulls one side down first, which can warp the head or pinch the gasket and leak. Finishing faster is not the point of the sequence. Head bolts are not left-hand threaded on alternating positions. Retorquing after warm-up is required on some older engines but is a separate step, not the reason for the pattern itself.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-13', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 5, 'A feeler gauge (thickness gauge) is used to check the valve clearance in an engine. The technician inserts two blades: a 0.006-inch blade slides with slight drag; a 0.007-inch blade will not enter the gap. What does this tell the technician?', '["The clearance is exactly 0.006 inches","The clearance is between 0.006 and 0.007 inches","The clearance is less than 0.006 inches","The clearance is greater than 0.007 inches"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A feeler gauge works by go/no-go logic. The 0.006-inch blade fits (gap is at least 0.006 in), but the 0.007-inch blade does not fit (gap is less than 0.007 in). Therefore the clearance lies between 0.006 and 0.007 inches.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'In a four-stroke gasoline engine, which stroke draws the air-fuel mixture into the cylinder?', '["Compression stroke","Power stroke","Intake stroke","Exhaust stroke"]'::jsonb, 2, 'On the intake stroke, the piston travels down the cylinder while the intake valve is open, and the resulting vacuum pulls the air-fuel charge into the combustion chamber. The compression stroke comes next, with both valves closed and the piston moving up to squeeze that charge. The power stroke is when the spark fires and the burning mixture drives the piston back down. The exhaust stroke is the piston moving up with the exhaust valve open to push spent gases out. The order is intake, compression, power, exhaust.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'The purpose of a vehicle''s clutch in a manual transmission is to:', '["regulate engine idle speed","temporarily disconnect the engine from the transmission to allow gear changes","convert the alternator''s output to DC current","control the flow of coolant to the engine block"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pressing the clutch pedal pulls the pressure plate away from the friction disc, breaking the link between the engine flywheel and the transmission input shaft so you can move the gear lever without grinding gears against engine speed. Engine idle speed is held by the idle air control or throttle body, not by the clutch. Alternator output is rectified by diodes inside the alternator itself, never by the drivetrain. Coolant flow is gated by the thermostat. Each wrong answer points at a different system unrelated to torque interruption.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'What is the function of a vehicle''s differential?', '["It filters fuel before it reaches the injectors","It allows the drive wheels to rotate at different speeds when turning","It regulates the voltage output of the charging system","It compresses refrigerant in the air conditioning system"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When a car rounds a corner, the outer drive wheel travels a longer arc than the inner wheel and has to spin faster, and the differential''s bevel gears let the two axles turn at different rates while still splitting engine torque between them. Filtering fuel is the fuel filter''s job. Regulating charging voltage is done by the voltage regulator inside the alternator. Compressing refrigerant is the air-conditioning compressor''s role. The differential lives in the drive axle, not in the fuel, charging, or HVAC systems.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'A vehicle''s battery provides current to start the engine. Once the engine is running, which component keeps the battery charged?', '["Starter motor","Distributor","Alternator","Voltage regulator only"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Once the engine is running, the alternator is belt-driven off the crankshaft and produces the current that recharges the battery and runs every electrical load on the car. The starter motor only spins while the key is in the start position to crank the engine over; after that it disengages. The distributor, on engines that have one, routes spark to plugs and does not generate current. The voltage regulator alone controls how much output the alternator makes, but it does not produce current by itself. The alternator is the generator in this system.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 3, 'Disc brakes use calipers and rotors. When the brake pedal is pressed, what converts pedal force into hydraulic pressure that actuates the calipers?', '["The brake booster","The master cylinder","The proportioning valve","The ABS modulator"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The master cylinder is a hydraulic pump tied directly to the brake pedal pushrod. When you press the pedal, a piston inside pushes brake fluid through the steel lines, and that pressure pushes the caliper pistons out against the pads. The brake booster only multiplies the foot force you put into the pedal using engine vacuum; it does not generate hydraulic pressure on its own. The proportioning valve balances front-to-rear pressure, downstream of the master cylinder. The ABS modulator pulses the brakes during a skid but does not create the base pressure.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 3, 'Engine oil pressure drops to near zero while the engine is running at highway speed. The FIRST action should be to:', '["Continue driving to the nearest service station","Shut off the engine immediately to prevent catastrophic bearing damage","Add oil while the engine is running","Rev the engine to increase oil pump speed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Engine oil pressure is what keeps a film of oil between the crankshaft and the bearing surfaces. If pressure drops to near zero, the bearings run dry and metal-on-metal contact spins or seizes them in seconds. Shutting the engine off immediately is the only way to save the engine. Driving on to the next station finishes the damage. Adding oil to a running engine is dangerous near hot moving parts and may not even solve the problem if the issue is the pump or a leak. Revving makes the wear faster, not slower.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 3, 'An automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of a clutch. The torque converter:', '["mechanically locks the engine to the transmission at all times","uses hydraulic fluid to transfer and multiply torque between engine and transmission","shifts gears by means of a centrifugal governor","replaces the differential in front-wheel-drive vehicles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A torque converter is a sealed fluid coupling. Engine torque spins a pump impeller that throws transmission fluid against a turbine connected to the transmission input shaft, and a stator in the middle redirects fluid flow to multiply torque at low speeds. It does not lock the engine to the transmission solidly except when an internal lockup clutch engages at cruise. Centrifugal governors selected shift points on old automatics but do not transfer torque. The differential is a separate gearset farther down the drivetrain. The torque converter replaces the clutch with fluid, not gears.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 4, 'A vehicle''s temperature gauge climbs into the red zone. Steam is seen coming from under the hood. The MOST likely cause is:', '["A low transmission fluid level","A burst radiator hose or failed thermostat causing coolant loss","An overcharged battery","A stuck-open EGR valve"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Steam and a rising temperature gauge together indicate coolant is escaping and the engine is no longer being cooled. The most common culprits are a burst hose, blown head gasket, or failed thermostat that traps coolant in the block. Low transmission fluid causes shifting problems, not overheating steam.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 4, 'A fuel-injected engine uses an oxygen sensor (O2 sensor) in the exhaust stream. The engine control module (ECM) uses the O2 sensor signal to:', '["determine ignition timing advance based on knock","adjust the fuel injector pulse width to maintain the proper air-fuel ratio","regulate alternator output voltage","control cooling fan speed based on engine temperature"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The oxygen sensor reads how much unburned oxygen is left in the exhaust, which tells the ECM whether the mixture entering the cylinders was rich or lean. The ECM then trims injector pulse width up or down on the next cycle to hold the air-fuel ratio near 14.7 to 1 for catalyst efficiency. Knock-based timing advance comes from the knock sensor, not the O2 sensor. Alternator voltage is governed by the voltage regulator. Cooling fan speed is driven by coolant temperature sensor input. Each wrong answer pairs a different sensor with its own control loop.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 4, 'A front-wheel-drive vehicle clicks loudly when turning at low speed but is quiet when driving straight. The most likely cause is:', '["A worn constant-velocity (CV) joint","Low power-steering fluid","A cracked brake rotor","A loose exhaust heat shield"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A constant-velocity joint lets a front drive axle send power through the steering angle as the wheel turns and the suspension moves. When the rubber boot tears, grease escapes, dirt gets in, and the joint''s internal balls and races wear, producing a sharp clicking that is loudest on tight, slow turns and quiet when going straight. Low power steering fluid causes a whining or moaning during steering effort, not a click. A cracked brake rotor produces a pulse or grind under braking, not on turns. A loose heat shield rattles with engine RPM, regardless of steering input.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 5, 'A technician notices that the engine temperature rises quickly to normal then a short time later climbs well above normal, cools slightly, then rises again in a repeating cycle. The MOST likely cause is:', '["A clogged catalytic converter","A thermostat that is stuck partially open, cycling the engine through warm-cool oscillations","A blown head gasket allowing combustion gases into the cooling system","A faulty coolant temperature sensor sending erratic signals to the ECM"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A blown head gasket allows combustion gases (under high pressure) to enter the cooling system. These gases displace coolant, form pockets that reduce cooling efficiency, and can cause the temperature to cycle as coolant is intermittently lost and returned. A stuck thermostat causes persistent overheating or chronic under-temperature, not cycling. A faulty sensor changes gauge readings but not actual temperature.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 5, 'An engine knocks heavily under load but the knock nearly disappears at idle. This is most consistent with:', '["A cracked flywheel","Pre-ignition (detonation) caused by low-octane fuel or advanced timing","A broken engine mount","An air leak in the intake manifold"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Detonation, also called spark knock or ping, happens when cylinder pressure and heat are high enough that part of the air-fuel charge ignites on its own before the spark plug fires, slamming a shock wave into the piston. Heavy load is exactly when pressure and temperature peak, which is why the knock fades at idle. Common causes are gasoline with octane below what the engine needs, carbon deposits glowing hot in the chamber, or timing advanced too far. A cracked flywheel makes a noise tied to RPM, not load. A broken motor mount thumps on shifts. An intake leak shows up as a lean miss and rough idle, the opposite load pattern.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'When working in a shop where gasoline or solvent vapors may be present, adequate ventilation is required primarily to:', '["keep tools at the correct operating temperature","prevent accumulation of flammable vapors that could ignite","ensure that paint dries faster","reduce humidity that causes rust on tools"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gasoline and most solvent vapors are denser than air, so they pool at floor level in a closed shop and can build up to a concentration that ignites from a spark, a pilot light, or a piece of running equipment. Moving air through the space keeps the concentration below the lower explosive limit. Tool operating temperature is not driven by shop ventilation. Paint drying is a side benefit on some jobs but not the safety reason for the rule. Rust prevention is about humidity control, which is a different problem with a different solution. Ventilation is fundamentally about explosion and fire prevention.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'A small Class B fire breaks out in the shop. Class B fires involve flammable liquids such as gasoline or oil. Which type of extinguisher is appropriate?', '["Water extinguisher","Class A dry extinguisher","CO2 or dry chemical extinguisher rated for Class B","Any available extinguisher regardless of rating"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Class B fires involve flammable liquids like gasoline, oil, and solvents, and the right answer is a CO2 or dry chemical extinguisher rated for Class B. CO2 smothers the fire by displacing oxygen, and dry chemical interrupts the chemical chain reaction. Water spreads burning liquid because the fuel floats on top of the water and rides the splash. A Class A only extinguisher, designed for wood and paper, will not safely handle a fuel fire. Grabbing any extinguisher regardless of rating risks making the situation worse. Match the extinguisher class to the fuel class.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'Lockout/tagout (LOTO) procedures are required before performing maintenance on a machine. The PRIMARY purpose of LOTO is to:', '["document the maintenance procedure for quality records","prevent the machine from being energized while a worker is inside or working on it","notify supervisors that the equipment is being serviced","ensure tools are returned to their correct storage locations"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Lockout/tagout puts a physical lock on the energy isolation point, a breaker, valve, or disconnect, so the equipment cannot be powered up while a worker has hands or body inside it. The lock and tag stay there until the worker who applied them removes them. Documenting maintenance is a paperwork goal, not a safety control. Notifying supervisors is communication, not energy isolation. Returning tools to storage is housekeeping. Only physical lockout actually prevents the startup that injures or kills the technician.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'A shop worker spills a small amount of motor oil on the floor. The safest IMMEDIATE action is to:', '["Mark the spill with a cone and clean it up at the end of the shift","Spread sawdust or absorbent material and clean it up promptly","Wipe it with a rag and place the rag in an open trash can","Pour water over the spill to dilute it"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An oil puddle is a slip hazard the instant it hits the floor, so the safest move is to spread oil-absorbent material or sawdust, sweep it up, and dispose of it properly right away. Marking the spill with a cone and waiting until end of shift leaves a fall hazard live for hours. Wiping with a rag and tossing it in an open trash can risks spontaneous combustion as the oil oxidizes inside a pile of paper trash. Pouring water spreads the oil and does not remove it, and the floor stays slick. Immediate absorbent cleanup is the standard.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 3, 'A worker is grinding metal and is producing sparks and metal fragments. Besides eye protection, what additional PPE should be worn?', '["Latex examination gloves and a dust mask","Face shield over safety glasses, leather gloves, and hearing protection","Safety glasses only — sparks are not hazardous at short range","Chemical-splash goggles and a rubber apron"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Grinding throws hot sparks, sharp metal fragments, and abrasive grit, and the wheel screams loud enough to damage hearing on a long job, so the worker needs a face shield over safety glasses for the face, leather gloves for hot edges, and hearing protection for the noise. Latex exam gloves and a paper dust mask offer no impact, heat, or noise protection. Safety glasses alone leave the rest of the face exposed to flying debris and slag. Chemical-splash goggles and a rubber apron are dressed for solvent or acid work, not for incandescent sparks that would burn through rubber.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 3, 'Before lifting a vehicle with a floor jack to work underneath it, you MUST also:', '["Remove the wheels first to reduce vehicle weight","Place jack stands under the vehicle''s frame or pinch-weld points to support it","Set the parking brake and leave the floor jack as the only support","Run the engine for 10 minutes to warm the oil before working"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A hydraulic floor jack lifts the vehicle, but a seal can leak or a valve can release, and the jack can drop. Jack stands are rigid steel supports that mechanically hold the load while you work, so you place them under the frame rails or pinch welds before crawling under. Removing the wheels does not address the falling-vehicle hazard. The parking brake on its own, with the jack as sole support, ignores the failure mode that kills people. Warming up the oil is unrelated to whether the car is safely supported. Always pair the jack with stands before going underneath.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 3, 'Oily rags used for wiping up solvent or paint should be stored in a:', '["Cardboard box kept away from windows","Sealed metal container approved for flammable waste","Plastic bin lined with a trash bag","Open drum to allow vapors to escape"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Oils and many solvents react slowly with oxygen and give off heat, and rags piled together insulate that heat until they reach the ignition point on their own, a process called spontaneous combustion. A sealed metal can starves any fire of oxygen and contains the heat away from the rest of the shop. Cardboard burns through in minutes once a fire starts inside it. Plastic bins soften and melt and do not contain a fire at all. An open drum lets vapors escape into the air and feeds any spark that finds them. Metal, sealed, and approved is the standard.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 4, 'A worker is about to use a bench grinder and notices that the grinding wheel has a small crack running from the center outward. The correct action is to:', '["Run it at low speed only to avoid spreading the crack","Replace the wheel immediately; a cracked wheel can shatter at high RPM","Apply epoxy to the crack and allow it to cure before use","Use the wheel on the side face rather than the rim to avoid the crack"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A cracked abrasive wheel can explode at operating RPM, sending fragments outward with great force. Any crack, chip, or damage is grounds for immediate replacement. Running it at lower speed or using the side face does not eliminate the risk of sudden catastrophic failure.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 4, 'Which class of fire involves energized electrical equipment?', '["Class A","Class B","Class C","Class D"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Class C fires involve energized electrical equipment such as panels, motors, or wiring, and the rule is to use a non-conductive extinguisher like CO2 or dry chemical so you do not get shocked through the stream. Class A is ordinary combustibles like wood, paper, and cloth. Class B is flammable liquids such as gasoline, oil, and solvents. Class D is combustible metals like magnesium and sodium. Memorizing the letter-to-fuel mapping is the only way to choose the right extinguisher quickly under stress.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 4, 'Before entering a large tank or enclosed space for maintenance work, a technician should first:', '["Enter quickly and complete the task before vapors build up","Test the atmosphere for oxygen level and toxic or flammable vapors","Bring a lit lamp inside to check for visibility","Seal any ventilation openings to keep temperature stable"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A tank or other confined space can hold an oxygen-deficient atmosphere, leftover toxic vapors, or flammable residues, and you cannot see or smell most of those hazards. A calibrated four-gas meter has to test oxygen, combustibles, and toxic gases before anyone goes in. Entering quickly to beat the buildup ignores that the hazardous atmosphere may already be there. A lit lamp inside an unknown atmosphere is an ignition source. Sealing ventilation makes the atmosphere worse, not safer. Test, ventilate, and only then enter, with a permit.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 5, 'A shop receives a drum of a new cleaning solvent. The Safety Data Sheet (SDS) lists an IDLH (Immediately Dangerous to Life and Health) concentration of 100 ppm. This value means that:', '["100 ppm is the safe, permissible exposure limit for an 8-hour shift","at 100 ppm, a worker without a respirator faces conditions from which escape may be impaired or irreversible harm may occur","100 ppm is the concentration at which the solvent becomes flammable","100 ppm must be measured monthly to comply with OSHA standards"]'::jsonb, 1, 'IDLH is the concentration at which a worker who loses respiratory protection has roughly thirty minutes to get out before symptoms keep them from escaping or before irreversible health damage sets in. It is an emergency-planning value used to pick respirator type for entry or rescue work. The permissible exposure limit, PEL, is the much lower routine-exposure ceiling for an eight-hour shift, so the safe-shift answer is wrong. IDLH says nothing directly about flammability, which is set by the lower explosive limit. The monthly-monitoring rule is invented; OSHA monitoring frequency depends on the specific substance.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 5, 'A shop policy requires that all rotating machinery guards be in place before the machine is started. A supervisor removes a guard temporarily for an adjustment and then leaves without replacing it. The correct action for the next technician who needs to use the machine is to:', '["Use the machine quickly and then replace the guard afterward","Report the missing guard and refuse to operate the machine until the guard is reinstalled","Operate the machine while holding the guard in place manually","Tape cardboard over the exposed area as a temporary barrier"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Machine guards keep hands and clothing out of rotating gears, belts, and pinch points, and they are a primary engineering control required before the machine runs. The right move is to stop, report the missing guard, and refuse to operate until it is replaced. Running it briefly without the guard exposes the worker for exactly the time the hazard is loose. Holding the guard by hand puts the holding hand inside the danger zone. Cardboard taped over the opening is not a guard, will not stop a rotating part, and can be pulled in. The line is clear: no guard, no operation.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'Coolant reservoir level is checked and found to be below the MIN mark while the engine is cold. What is the correct action?', '["Add the correct antifreeze-water mixture to bring the level to the MIN-MAX range","Drain and replace all coolant regardless of level","Add straight water only so coolant does not become too concentrated","The reservoir level is irrelevant; check only the radiator cap"]'::jsonb, 0, 'On a modern engine the overflow reservoir is where you check and add coolant when the engine is cold, and the right top-up is the manufacturer-specified antifreeze and water mix, typically a 50/50 blend, to keep both freeze and boil protection intact. Draining and replacing all the coolant is a full service, not a level correction. Adding straight water dilutes the antifreeze and weakens corrosion inhibitors. The radiator cap is not a service point for level on systems built around a reservoir, and opening a hot cap is a burn risk anyway. Add the correct mix, to the correct mark, when cold.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'The low-oil pressure warning light illuminates while idling at a stoplight. The engine sounds normal. The driver should FIRST:', '["Rev the engine to 3,000 RPM to build oil pressure","Turn off the engine, check the oil level, and add oil if needed before restarting","Continue driving — oil pressure lights are often faulty","Add transmission fluid to the engine to restore pressure quickly"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A low oil pressure warning at idle can mean the level is genuinely low, the pump or bearings are failing, or the sensor itself is bad, and you cannot tell which one without stopping. Shutting the engine off protects the bearings from oil starvation, then a dipstick check shows whether oil is needed before restart. Revving the engine pushes more oil only at the cost of more wear if pressure really is gone. Driving on because the light might be faulty is exactly the gamble that destroys engines. Transmission fluid is not engine oil and will damage seals and clutches that do not belong in an engine.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'A technician checks the brake fluid and finds it is dark brown and appears contaminated. The correct service action is to:', '["Top off with fresh fluid to dilute the contamination","Flush the brake system and fill with fresh fluid of the correct DOT specification","Add a brake fluid conditioner and continue use","No action needed — brake fluid darkens naturally and remains effective"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Brake fluid is hygroscopic, meaning it pulls moisture out of the air over time, and that water lowers the boiling point and corrodes calipers, lines, and the master cylinder from the inside. Dark brown fluid is contaminated and needs to be flushed completely from each wheel and refilled with fresh fluid matching the vehicle''s DOT specification. Topping off only mixes new fluid with bad and leaves the contamination in place. Brake fluid conditioners are not a recognized service for this and cannot undo moisture absorption. The claim that dark fluid is normal and effective is simply wrong; brake fluid should be light amber.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'A driver notices the engine hesitates and stumbles when accelerating from a stop. A mechanic inspects and finds the air filter is completely clogged with dirt. Why would a clogged air filter cause this symptom?', '["The filter restricts airflow, creating an excessively rich fuel mixture that makes the engine stumble under load","The filter blocks cooling airflow to the radiator","A clogged filter increases intake air temperature, advancing ignition timing","The filter restricts oil return to the crankcase"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The engine needs a precise air-fuel ratio. A severely clogged air filter restricts incoming air, causing the mixture to become too rich (too much fuel relative to air). Under load the engine stumbles because combustion is incomplete. At idle, the effect may be minor, but under acceleration it becomes pronounced.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 3, 'A technician replaces a worn serpentine belt. After installation, the belt squeals briefly when the engine is cold but goes away when warmed. The MOST likely cause is:', '["The replacement belt is too long","Slight slipping on a pulley due to condensation or belt material until the belt seats fully","The tensioner pulley bearing has failed","A mismatch in belt rib count"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Brief cold squealing from a new belt is common as the rubber conforms to pulley grooves and surface moisture evaporates. If squealing persists or occurs warm, it indicates a worn tensioner, glazed pulley, or incorrect belt. Rib-count mismatches produce constant noise and would cause the belt to mistrack.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 3, 'When replacing brake pads on a disc brake vehicle, a technician compresses the caliper piston back into the caliper bore. Before doing so, what precaution should be taken?', '["Open the bleeder screw to release pressure while compressing the piston","Remove the master cylinder reservoir cap and siphon out some fluid to prevent overflow as the piston is pushed back","Disconnect the ABS module to prevent error codes","Add brake fluid to the reservoir to prevent air from entering"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pushing the caliper piston back forces fluid backward into the master cylinder reservoir. If the reservoir is full, this fluid has nowhere to go and will overflow, potentially damaging painted surfaces or rubber seals. Removing the reservoir cap and siphoning excess fluid first prevents overflow. (The bleeder screw method also works but requires catching old fluid separately.)', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 4, 'A spark plug removed from a cylinder has a wet, oily black deposit coating the ceramic insulator and electrodes. This most likely indicates:', '["The engine is running too lean","Oil is entering the combustion chamber due to worn piston rings or valve seals","The ignition timing is excessively advanced","The coolant system is leaking into the cylinder"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A wet, oily, black coating on the plug means liquid oil is reaching the combustion chamber, either past worn piston rings from below or past failed valve stem seals from above, and it is being burned along with the fuel. A lean mixture, with too little fuel, leaves a chalky white or very light gray deposit because there is no extra fuel to leave soot. Excessively advanced ignition timing produces detonation symptoms and may erode the electrode, not coat it with oil. A coolant leak into the cylinder bakes onto the plug as a hard white crust, sometimes with a sweet smell, not a wet black film.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 4, 'A vehicle''s power steering pump whines loudly when the steering wheel is turned to full lock in either direction. The fluid level is within the normal range. The MOST likely cause is:', '["Overfilled power steering reservoir","Normal cavitation at the pressure limit — acceptable as long as not held at full lock for extended time","A failing electric power steering motor","A clogged hydraulic return line causing system overpressure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Hydraulic power steering systems reach their maximum pressure limit at full steering lock. The pump continues to build pressure against a closed circuit, causing fluid to cavitate (form vapor bubbles) and produce a whining or moaning sound. This is normal for short periods; holding full lock for extended time can damage the pump. If it whines at all steering positions, that indicates a different problem.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 4, 'A visual inspection of a vehicle''s exhaust smoke reveals continuous white smoke from a cold engine that does NOT clear after warm-up. This most likely indicates:', '["Normal condensation burning off","A rich fuel mixture from a faulty injector","Coolant entering the combustion chamber through a failed head gasket","Burning engine oil due to a cracked piston"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Light white smoke on cold startup that clears quickly is normal condensation. Persistent white smoke after warm-up that has a sweet smell and does not dissipate strongly indicates coolant (antifreeze) burning in the cylinders — a hallmark of a blown head gasket or cracked block. Oil smoke tends to be blue-gray with an acrid odor.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 5, 'A technician performs a cylinder compression test and finds cylinder 3 has 80 psi while all others read 165 psi. Adding a small amount of oil to cylinder 3 through the spark plug hole raises its compression to 150 psi. What does this indicate?', '["A bent intake valve in cylinder 3","Worn piston rings in cylinder 3 — the oil temporarily seals the gap","A cracked cylinder wall in cylinder 3","A leaking head gasket between cylinders 3 and 4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'This is the wet compression test. Adding oil temporarily seals the ring-to-cylinder-wall gap. If compression rises significantly when oil is added, the low reading is caused by ring wear or blow-by, not by a valve or gasket problem. A valve issue would not improve with oil because valves seal above the rings.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 5, 'After replacing a vehicle''s oxygen sensor, the technician clears the fault code and performs a drive cycle, but the check-engine light returns with the same code. The NEXT diagnostic step is to:', '["Replace the oxygen sensor again with a higher-grade part","Check wiring harness continuity and inspect for exhaust leaks upstream of the sensor","Replace the catalytic converter, as it is the usual cause of sensor codes","Reprogram the ECM with updated software"]'::jsonb, 1, 'If a new sensor triggers the same code, the sensor is likely not the root cause. The technician should inspect the wiring harness for shorts, opens, or damaged connectors, and check for exhaust leaks upstream that can introduce false oxygen readings. Replacing parts without checking the circuit is inefficient and costly.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 3, 'A technician finds the battery terminals heavily corroded with a white-blue crusty buildup. After cleaning the terminals, what is the correct follow-up action?', '["Replace the battery immediately regardless of its test results","Apply a battery terminal protector spray or grease to prevent future corrosion","Coat the terminals with motor oil for corrosion protection","Tighten the terminal clamps as hard as possible to ensure good contact"]'::jsonb, 1, 'After cleaning corrosion from battery terminals, a protective spray (petroleum-based terminal spray or anti-corrosion felt pads) applied to the terminals significantly reduces the rate of future corrosion by sealing the metal from battery acid vapors. Motor oil is not intended for this purpose and can attract dirt.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'Which class of lever has the effort force applied between the fulcrum and the load?', '["First-class lever","Second-class lever","Third-class lever","Fourth-class lever"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A third-class lever places the effort between the fulcrum and the load. Common examples include tweezers, fishing rods, and the human forearm lifting a weight. Choice A (first-class) places the fulcrum between effort and load, like a seesaw or pliers. Choice B (second-class) places the load between fulcrum and effort, like a wheelbarrow or bottle opener. Choice D (fourth-class) does not exist in mechanics; only three classes of lever are defined, distinguished by which of the three elements (fulcrum, load, effort) sits in the middle.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'A first-class lever has its fulcrum exactly in the middle, with a 20-pound weight on each side. The lever is:', '["Balanced, with no mechanical advantage","Tipped toward the left side","Tipped toward the right side","Providing a mechanical advantage of 2"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A lever balances when torques are equal: W1 x D1 = W2 x D2. With 20 pounds at equal distances, both torques match and the lever is balanced. Mechanical advantage = effort arm / load arm = 1, so no force is multiplied. Choice B (tipped left) and choice C (tipped right) ignore that the moments are equal. Choice D (MA of 2) requires the effort arm to be twice the load arm; here they are equal. A first-class lever with arms of equal length only redirects force, much like a fixed pulley.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A lever has a 4-foot effort arm and a 1-foot load arm. What is the mechanical advantage?', '["1","2","4","5"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Lever MA equals effort arm divided by load arm: MA = 4 / 1 = 4. This means 1 pound of effort can lift a 4-pound load (ignoring the lever''s own weight). Choice A (1) would require equal arm lengths and corresponds to a balanced first-class lever with no mechanical advantage. Choice B (2) halves the correct ratio. Choice D (5) adds the arm lengths (4 + 1) instead of dividing them. Mechanical advantage is always a ratio of effort arm to load arm, never a sum.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A movable pulley is attached to the load rather than to a fixed point. Compared to a single fixed pulley, a single movable pulley:', '["Provides no change in mechanical advantage","Doubles the mechanical advantage to 2 by supporting the load with two rope segments","Triples the mechanical advantage to 3","Reverses the direction of pull with no force benefit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single movable pulley is attached to the load and supported by two rope segments. Each segment shares half the load, so the effort needed is half the load weight; MA = 2. The trade-off is that the effort end of the rope must travel twice as far as the load rises (conservation of work). Choice A (no change) describes a fixed pulley, not a movable one. Choice C (triples to 3) requires three supporting strands, which a single movable pulley does not have. Choice D (reverses direction with no force benefit) describes a fixed pulley''s behavior, not a movable one.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A 90-pound load is placed 2 feet from the fulcrum of a lever. To balance the load, how much force must be applied at a point 6 feet from the fulcrum on the other side?', '["15 pounds","30 pounds","45 pounds","180 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Lever equilibrium: Load × Load arm = Effort × Effort arm. 90 × 2 = Effort × 6. Effort = 180 / 6 = 30 pounds. The common trap is dividing the load by the load arm (90 / 2 = 45) rather than setting up the full balance equation.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 3, 'A compound pulley system has one fixed pulley and two movable pulleys, resulting in 5 rope segments supporting the load. If the load weighs 200 pounds, how much effort force is needed (ignoring friction)?', '["20 pounds","40 pounds","50 pounds","100 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mechanical advantage = number of rope segments supporting the load = 5. Effort = Load / MA = 200 / 5 = 40 pounds. Dividing by the number of pulleys rather than rope segments is the common error.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 3, 'A crowbar (first-class lever) is 4 feet long. The fulcrum is placed 6 inches from the load end. How long is the effort arm?', '["6 inches","42 inches","3.5 feet","4 feet"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total lever length = 4 feet = 48 inches. Load arm = 6 inches. Effort arm = 48 − 6 = 42 inches. MA = 42 / 6 = 7 — a significant mechanical advantage. The trap is reporting the effort arm as 4 feet (the whole lever).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 3, 'A flagpole uses a fixed pulley at the top. When you pull the rope down, the flag goes up. What does this pulley change?', '["The magnitude of the required force","Only the direction of the applied force","Both the direction and the magnitude of the force","The speed of the rope only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single fixed pulley has a mechanical advantage of 1 — it does not reduce the force needed. Its only benefit is redirecting the force: you pull down to move the load up, which is more convenient. To reduce required force you need a movable pulley or a compound system.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 4, 'A block-and-tackle system supports a 360-pound load with 6 rope segments. You pull the free rope end upward 12 feet. How far does the load actually rise?', '["2 feet","6 feet","12 feet","72 feet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'With 6 rope segments sharing the load, you trade force for distance: MA = 6. Load distance = rope distance / MA = 12 / 6 = 2 feet. You exert 360 / 6 = 60 pounds of effort but must pull 6 feet of rope for each foot the load moves.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 4, 'A wheelbarrow is a second-class lever. The wheel axle acts as the fulcrum; the load sits in the center; the handles are gripped at the far end. If the load weighs 150 pounds and sits 1.5 feet from the axle, and the handles are 4.5 feet from the axle, how much upward force at the handles is needed to lift the load?', '["50 pounds","75 pounds","100 pounds","225 pounds"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Torque balance: Effort x Effort arm = Load x Load arm. So Effort x 4.5 = 150 x 1.5 = 225 lb-ft. Effort = 225 / 4.5 = 50 pounds. Choice B (75 pounds) is half the load weight, the answer for a single movable pulley, not a second-class lever with these arm lengths. Choice C (100 pounds) ignores the load arm and divides 150 by some other ratio. Choice D (225 pounds) is the torque value (in lb-ft) being misread as a force. MA = effort arm / load arm = 4.5 / 1.5 = 3, so effort is one-third of load weight.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 4, 'Two pulleys are connected by a belt. The driving pulley has a diameter of 8 inches and turns at 300 RPM. The driven pulley has a diameter of 4 inches. At what RPM does the driven pulley spin?', '["150 RPM","300 RPM","600 RPM","1200 RPM"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Belt-connected pulleys have rim speeds equal (no slip), so RPM is inversely proportional to diameter: Driven RPM = Driver RPM x (Driver d / Driven d) = 300 x (8 / 4) = 600 RPM. Choice A (150 RPM) inverts the ratio and treats the larger pulley as the faster one. Choice B (300 RPM) leaves the speed unchanged, ignoring the size difference. Choice D (1200 RPM) doubles the correct answer, possibly multiplying by 4 instead of by 2. The smaller driven pulley always spins faster than the larger driver when belt-coupled.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 5, 'A mechanic uses a breaker bar that is 24 inches long to loosen a bolt. She can apply 60 pounds of force. The bolt requires 180 pound-inches of torque to loosen. Can she loosen it, and if not, what minimum bar length is needed?', '["Yes, 24 inches is sufficient","No; she needs at least 3 inches","No; she needs at least 30 inches","No; she needs at least 36 inches"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Torque = Force × Arm length = 60 × 24 = 1,440 pound-inches. The bolt requires only 180 pound-inches, so 24 inches is more than sufficient. The trap is misreading the question; 60 × 24 = 1,440, which greatly exceeds 180.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-13', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 5, 'A lever system is set up with the fulcrum 1 foot from the load end and 5 feet from the effort end (total 6 feet). A 200-pound load is placed at the load end. How much effort is needed, and what is the direction of effort relative to the load for a first-class lever?', '["40 pounds applied upward — same direction as the load pushes","40 pounds applied downward — opposite direction to the load","200 pounds applied downward","40 pounds applied horizontally"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Effort = Load × Load arm / Effort arm = 200 × 1 / 5 = 40 pounds. In a first-class lever the fulcrum is between effort and load, so effort and load forces act in opposite directions — pressing down at the effort end lifts the load end up. The effort is applied downward (opposite to the upward force the load exerts on its end).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'Two meshing spur gears always rotate in:', '["the same direction","opposite directions","alternating directions depending on speed","the same direction only when they are the same size"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When two external spur gears mesh, the teeth push against each other at the contact point. Equal and opposite contact forces (Newton''s Third Law) cause the two gears to spin in opposite directions. Choice A (same direction) only happens with an idler gear between them, or with internal gears. Choice C (alternating depending on speed) is not how gear direction works; direction is set by geometry, not speed. Choice D (same direction when equal size) is also wrong; same-size meshing gears still rotate opposite each other. To get same direction without size change, an idler gear must be inserted.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'A driving gear has 8 teeth and the driven gear has 24 teeth. The gear ratio (driven:driver) is:', '["1:3","3:1","8:1","1:8"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gear ratio (driven to driver) equals teeth on driven divided by teeth on driver: 24 / 8 = 3:1. The driving gear turns three times for every one turn of the driven gear, producing a 3:1 speed reduction and a 3:1 torque multiplication. Choice A (1:3) inverts the ratio, which would describe a speed-up gear set (small driver, larger driven). Choice C (8:1) and choice D (1:8) use the wrong tooth count or completely skip the division step. Direction of the ratio (driven:driver vs driver:driven) must always be matched to context; the convention here is driven first.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'Gear A has 12 teeth and turns at 600 RPM. It meshes with Gear B, which has 36 teeth. How fast does Gear B rotate?', '["100 RPM","200 RPM","300 RPM","1,800 RPM"]'::jsonb, 1, 'RPM is inversely proportional to tooth count: RPM_B = RPM_A x (Teeth_A / Teeth_B) = 600 x (12 / 36) = 600 x (1/3) = 200 RPM. Choice A (100 RPM) divides by 6 instead of 3, doubling the reduction. Choice C (300 RPM) only halves the speed, applying a 2:1 ratio. Choice D (1,800 RPM) multiplies by 3 instead of dividing, treating the larger gear as the faster one. The bigger gear always rotates slower than the smaller gear it meshes with; torque trades up by the same factor speed trades down.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'In a gear train, decreasing rotational speed by using a larger driven gear also has what effect on torque?', '["Torque decreases proportionally","Torque increases proportionally","Torque is unaffected by the gear ratio","Torque doubles regardless of the ratio"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gears trade speed for torque (assuming no friction losses). When the driven gear is larger, it turns slower but the torque multiplies by the same ratio. If speed is halved, torque is doubled. This is why low gears in a vehicle provide more pulling force.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 3, 'Three gears are in a row: Gear 1 (driver, 10 teeth) meshes with Gear 2 (20 teeth, idler), which meshes with Gear 3 (10 teeth). In which direction does Gear 3 turn relative to Gear 1?', '["Opposite direction — the idler reverses the direction once","Same direction — each mesh reverses direction, and two reversals return to original","Gear 3 does not rotate when an idler is present","Gear 3 rotates 90 degrees out of phase with Gear 1"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each external gear mesh reverses the direction of rotation. Gear 1 to Gear 2 is one reversal; Gear 2 to Gear 3 is a second reversal. Two reversals return Gear 3 to the same rotational direction as Gear 1. The idler also makes the final speed ratio depend only on the first and last gears (10 and 10), not the idler in the middle, so the speed ratio is 1:1. Choice A (opposite) counts only one reversal. Choice C (does not rotate) misunderstands what an idler does; it transmits motion. Choice D (90 degrees out of phase) confuses rotational direction with phase angle, which is not a quantity defined for spur gears.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 3, 'A wheel and axle system has a wheel radius of 15 cm and an axle radius of 3 cm. A 60-Newton load is hung from the axle. What force must be applied at the rim of the wheel to hold the load in equilibrium?', '["4 N","12 N","60 N","300 N"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MA of a wheel and axle = wheel radius / axle radius = 15 / 3 = 5. Effort = Load / MA = 60 / 5 = 12 N. A common trap is dividing 60 by 15 (the wheel radius alone) to get 4 N, confusing radius with MA.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 3, 'A gear reduction system uses a 5-tooth pinion driving a 40-tooth ring gear. The input shaft turns at 2,000 RPM. What is the output RPM, and how does the output torque compare to the input?', '["250 RPM output; torque is multiplied by 8","250 RPM output; torque is the same","16,000 RPM output; torque is divided by 8","400 RPM output; torque is multiplied by 5"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Output RPM = Input RPM x (Pinion teeth / Ring teeth) = 2,000 x (5/40) = 250 RPM. The gear reduction ratio is 40/5 = 8:1. In an ideal gear set, what is lost in speed is gained in torque, so output torque = input torque x 8. Choice B (250 RPM, same torque) gets the speed right but ignores the speed-torque trade-off. Choice C (16,000 RPM, torque /8) inverts the formula and treats the small gear as the driven side. Choice D (400 RPM, torque x 5) uses the wrong ratio (5 instead of 8). Gear ratio always equals teeth_driven / teeth_driver.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 4, 'A bicycle chainring has 48 teeth and the rear sprocket has 16 teeth. For each complete revolution of the pedals, how many times does the rear wheel turn?', '["1 time","2 times","3 times","4 times"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Chain drives behave like gears: rear wheel revolutions per pedal revolution = chainring teeth / sprocket teeth = 48 / 16 = 3. Each pedal stroke turns the rear wheel three times, giving a speed advantage at the cost of higher pedaling force. Choice A (1 time) ignores the tooth ratio entirely. Choice B (2 times) halves the correct ratio. Choice D (4 times) uses the wrong division (perhaps 48 / 12 or similar). Larger chainring relative to sprocket means more wheel revolutions per pedal turn, which is the trade-off cyclists make for higher top speed.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 4, 'In a planetary gear set, the sun gear has 20 teeth, each of three planet gears has 10 teeth, and the ring gear has 40 teeth. If the ring gear is held fixed and power is applied to the sun gear, which output produces the highest torque?', '["The planet carrier (output through the arm holding the planets)","The ring gear (despite being held)","The sun gear itself","All outputs produce identical torque"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When the ring gear is fixed and the sun drives the system, the planet gears walk around the fixed ring, carrying the planet carrier (arm) as output. The speed reduction is significant (overall ratio = 1 + Ring/Sun = 1 + 40/20 = 3:1), giving 3× torque multiplication at the carrier — the highest available output torque configuration for this setup.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 4, 'A worm gear pair has a worm with 1 thread (start) and a worm wheel with 50 teeth. If the worm shaft turns at 1,500 RPM, at what speed does the worm wheel turn?', '["1 RPM","30 RPM","50 RPM","75,000 RPM"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single-start worm advances the worm wheel by one tooth per full worm revolution. With 50 teeth on the wheel, the gear ratio is 50:1. Output RPM = Input RPM / 50 = 1,500 / 50 = 30 RPM. Choice A (1 RPM) over-reduces, dividing by 1,500 or otherwise inflating the ratio. Choice C (50 RPM) leaves out one step in the division. Choice D (75,000 RPM) multiplies instead of dividing, treating the worm wheel as a speed-up element. Worm gears are extreme speed reducers and large torque multipliers, often used where high torque at low speed is needed.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 5, 'A 4-speed manual transmission has gear ratios of 3.5:1, 2.2:1, 1.4:1, and 1:1 for first through fourth gear. In first gear with the engine producing 200 Newton-meters of torque, approximately how much torque is available at the transmission output shaft (ignoring drivetrain losses)?', '["57 Nm","200 Nm","440 Nm","700 Nm"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Gear reduction multiplies torque: Output torque = Engine torque x Gear ratio = 200 Nm x 3.5 = 700 Nm. Choice A (57 Nm) divides 200 by 3.5, inverting the formula and treating first gear as a speed-up. Choice B (200 Nm) ignores the gear ratio and just lists engine torque, which would only be the case in fourth gear (1:1). Choice C (440 Nm) uses the 2.2:1 second-gear ratio instead of first gear. First gear has the highest reduction and therefore the highest output torque, which is exactly why vehicles start from rest in first gear.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 5, 'Two meshing gears have a center-to-center distance of 18 cm. Gear A (the driver) has a pitch radius of 6 cm. Expressing gear ratio as driven-to-driver, what is the gear ratio?', '["1:1","1:2","2:1","3:1"]'::jsonb, 2, 'For meshing external gears the center-to-center distance equals the sum of the two pitch radii. So radius_B = 18 minus 6 = 12 cm. Pitch radius is proportional to tooth count, so the driven-to-driver ratio is 12 to 6, which simplifies to 2:1. The driven gear (B) is twice as large, so for every one rotation of the driver it turns half a revolution, and its torque is doubled. ''1:1'' would require equal radii (9 and 9). ''1:2'' inverts the convention and would describe driver-to-driven instead. ''3:1'' would require radius_B = 18, which violates the geometric constraint.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-13', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'A rack and pinion gear system converts which type of motion to which?', '["Rotary motion to linear motion","Linear motion to circular oscillation","Vertical motion to horizontal rotary motion","Torque to electrical energy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A rack is a straight, flat gear; a pinion is a circular gear. When the pinion rotates, its teeth engage the rack and push it along its length, converting rotary motion into linear motion. This is the operating principle of rack-and-pinion steering, where steering-wheel rotation becomes linear motion of the tie rods. Choice B (linear to circular oscillation) reverses the input/output and adds oscillation, which is not what a rack-and-pinion does. Choice C (vertical to horizontal rotary) garbles the geometry; the conversion is rotary-to-linear, not vertical-to-horizontal. Choice D (torque to electricity) describes a generator, not a mechanical gear set.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'A 50-pound box sits on a rough surface. A horizontal force of 20 pounds is applied but the box does not move. Which statement correctly describes the friction force acting on the box?', '["Friction is 50 pounds, opposing the weight of the box","Friction is 20 pounds, exactly opposing the applied force","Friction is zero because the box is not moving","Friction is 70 pounds, combining weight and applied force"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Static friction adjusts to exactly cancel the applied horizontal force when the object is not moving. The box is in equilibrium, so the horizontal forces must balance: static friction = 20 pounds directed opposite to the applied force.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Compared to static friction, kinetic (sliding) friction for the same object on the same surface is generally:', '["Greater","Equal","Less","Dependent only on velocity"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kinetic (sliding) friction is generally less than the maximum static friction for the same surfaces. Once an object breaks free of static friction and begins sliding, fewer microscopic surface interlocks form, so the resisting force drops. Choice A (greater) reverses the well-established relationship. Choice B (equal) ignores the difference between coefficients of static and kinetic friction. Choice D (depends only on velocity) is wrong; for most practical surfaces, kinetic friction is approximately constant with velocity at typical speeds. This is why a heavy object takes more force to start moving than to keep moving.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A 100-pound block rests on a horizontal surface with a coefficient of static friction of 0.4. What minimum horizontal force is needed to start the block moving?', '["20 pounds","40 pounds","60 pounds","100 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Maximum static friction equals the coefficient of static friction times the normal force: f_s = mu_s x N = 0.4 x 100 = 40 pounds. On a horizontal surface, normal force equals the object''s weight, so 40 pounds of push is the minimum to start motion. Choice A (20 pounds) halves the coefficient or uses 0.2 by mistake. Choice C (60 pounds) inflates the coefficient to 0.6. Choice D (100 pounds) ignores the coefficient and uses the full weight as the friction force, which would only be true if mu_s equaled 1.0.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A 200-pound box is being dragged across a floor. The coefficient of kinetic friction is 0.25. What is the friction force resisting the motion?', '["25 pounds","50 pounds","80 pounds","200 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Kinetic friction equals the coefficient times the normal force: f_k = mu_k x N = 0.25 x 200 = 50 pounds. On a flat floor the normal force equals the box''s weight. Choice A (25 pounds) halves the coefficient to 0.125. Choice C (80 pounds) uses a coefficient of 0.4 instead of 0.25. Choice D (200 pounds) ignores the coefficient and uses the full weight, which would only apply if mu_k were 1.0 (an extreme value rarely seen). Friction always scales with normal force, not with the applied force.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 3, 'A 60-pound block is placed on a ramp inclined at 30 degrees. The normal force on the block from the ramp surface equals the component of the block''s weight perpendicular to the ramp surface. If the ramp is smooth (frictionless), the normal force is approximately:', '["30 pounds","52 pounds","60 pounds","120 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Normal force = W × cos(θ) = 60 × cos(30°) = 60 × 0.866 ≈ 52 pounds. The component pulling the block down the ramp = W × sin(30°) = 60 × 0.5 = 30 pounds. The normal force is NOT equal to the full weight on a ramp — it is reduced by the cosine of the angle.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 3, 'A person pushes down at an angle on a lawnmower handle. The downward component of the pushing force increases the normal force on the mower''s wheels. What effect does this have on friction?', '["Friction decreases because the mower moves forward","Friction increases because friction depends on normal force","Friction is unchanged because only horizontal force causes motion","Friction is eliminated by the forward-directed component"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Friction force equals the coefficient of friction times the normal force: f = mu x N. Adding a downward component of push increases the normal force the floor exerts upward on the mower wheels, and friction scales directly with that normal force. Choice A (decreases) reverses the relationship; pushing down increases, not decreases, the resistance. Choice C (unchanged) ignores that the vertical force component adds to the weight, raising the normal force. Choice D (eliminated) is physically impossible; no horizontal component can cancel friction. This is why pulling at an upward angle is easier than pushing at a downward angle.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 3, 'A 120-pound crate is on a frictionless surface. Two horizontal forces act on it: 50 pounds to the right and 30 pounds to the left. What is the net force and the resulting acceleration? (Use weight ÷ 32 ft/s² to find mass in slugs.)', '["Net 20 pounds right; acceleration ≈ 5.3 ft/s²","Net 80 pounds right; acceleration ≈ 21 ft/s²","Net 20 pounds right; acceleration ≈ 2.5 ft/s²","Net 50 pounds right; no acceleration because friction balances it"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Net force = 50 - 30 = 20 pounds to the right. Mass in slugs = weight / g = 120 / 32 = 3.75 slugs. Acceleration = F_net / m = 20 / 3.75 = 5.33 ft/s^2 to the right. Choice B (80 pounds; 21 ft/s^2) adds the two forces instead of subtracting them. Choice C (20 pounds; 2.5 ft/s^2) uses weight (120 lb) directly as mass instead of dividing by g, doubling the apparent mass. Choice D (50 pounds; no acceleration) misreads the surface as having friction; with no friction, the only horizontal forces are the two applied pushes.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 4, 'A 500-Newton engine rests on a steel workbench. The coefficient of static friction between the engine and bench is 0.3. A horizontal force of 160 N is applied to the engine. Does the engine move, and what is the maximum static friction force?', '["Yes, the engine moves; maximum static friction was 150 N, which 160 N exceeds","Yes, the engine moves; maximum static friction was 160 N, which the applied force just equals","No, the engine stays put; maximum static friction was 150 N, but it grows to match the 160 N applied","No, the engine stays put; maximum static friction was 160 N opposing the applied force"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Compute the static-friction ceiling: f_s,max = μ_s × N = 0.3 × 500 = 150 N. The applied force of 160 N exceeds that ceiling, so the engine begins to slide. Choice B (150 vs 160 is mistakenly read as equal) ignores the 10 N gap that triggers motion. Choice C is the most common misconception: students think static friction always rises to match whatever force is applied, but it actually caps at μ_s × N. Choice D treats kinetic friction as the answer at rest and uses the wrong number entirely; static friction never exceeds its ceiling.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 4, 'A block slides down a ramp at a constant speed. At constant speed, which of the following must be true?', '["There is no friction force on the block","The component of gravity along the ramp exactly equals the kinetic friction force","The normal force equals the gravitational force","The coefficient of kinetic friction is zero"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Constant velocity means zero acceleration, so the net force along the ramp is zero. The component of gravity pulling the block down the ramp (W sin theta) must be exactly canceled by kinetic friction (mu_k x N) acting up the ramp. Choice A (no friction) would leave gravity unopposed and the block would accelerate, not move at constant speed. Choice C (normal equals gravity) is true only on a flat surface; on a ramp, normal force equals W cos theta, less than full weight. Choice D (mu_k = 0) is equivalent to choice A and contradicts the constant-speed observation.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 4, 'A 40-kg box sits on a horizontal floor. Coefficient of static friction = 0.5, kinetic friction = 0.35. A horizontal force of 180 N is applied. What is the friction force and does the box move? (g = 10 m/s²)', '["Friction = 200 N, box does not move","Friction = 180 N, box does not move","Maximum static friction = 200 N; 180 N < 200 N so box stays; friction = 180 N","Box moves; kinetic friction = 140 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Normal force = mg = 40 × 10 = 400 N. Maximum static friction = 0.5 × 400 = 200 N. Applied force = 180 N < 200 N, so the box does NOT move. When stationary, static friction equals the applied force: 180 N. Kinetic friction (140 N) is only relevant if the box were sliding.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 5, 'A crate is being pushed across a rough floor at constant velocity with a horizontal force of 80 N. If the floor surface is then treated to reduce the coefficient of kinetic friction by half, and the same 80-N force is maintained, what happens to the crate?', '["It continues at the same constant velocity","It decelerates and stops","It accelerates because the applied force now exceeds the reduced friction","It reverses direction"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Originally, applied force (80 N) balanced friction (80 N) for constant velocity. Halving the coefficient of kinetic friction halves the friction force to 40 N while the applied force stays at 80 N. Net force = 80 - 40 = 40 N in the direction of motion. By Newton''s Second Law, a = F_net / m > 0, so the crate accelerates. Choice A (same velocity) ignores the new force imbalance. Choice B (decelerates) reverses the direction of the net force; less friction means less resistance, not more. Choice D (reverses direction) would require a net force opposite to motion, which is not the case here.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 5, 'A 10-kg block rests on a 25-degree incline. The coefficient of static friction is 0.5. Will the block slide? (Use g = 10 m/s², sin 25° ≈ 0.42, cos 25° ≈ 0.91)', '["Yes, because gravity down the ramp exceeds maximum static friction","No, because maximum static friction exceeds gravity''s ramp component","It will slide at exactly constant velocity","Insufficient information without knowing the block''s surface material"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gravity along ramp = mg sin 25° = 10 × 10 × 0.42 = 42 N. Normal force = mg cos 25° = 10 × 10 × 0.91 = 91 N. Maximum static friction = 0.5 × 91 = 45.5 N. Since 45.5 N > 42 N, static friction can fully oppose the sliding tendency. The block does not slide.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'A screw is a simple machine based on which other simple machine?', '["Lever","Wheel and axle","Inclined plane wrapped in a helix","Pulley"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A screw is geometrically an inclined plane wrapped helically around a cylinder. The pitch (distance between threads) is the height of the inclined plane, and the circumference traveled per rotation is its length. Choice A (lever) is unrelated; a screw does not rotate around a fixed fulcrum like a lever. Choice B (wheel and axle) is the closest second answer because screws are turned by a wheel-like head, but the underlying geometry that creates the linear advance is the spiral ramp itself, not a wheel-axle radius ratio. Choice D (pulley) does not match; pulleys use ropes and grooves, not threaded inclines.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'Pascal''s principle states that pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is:', '["absorbed by the fluid and converted to heat","transmitted equally in all directions throughout the fluid","reduced in proportion to the depth of the fluid","only transmitted upward in the fluid"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pascal''s principle states that pressure applied to an enclosed, incompressible fluid is transmitted equally in all directions and to every surface bounding the fluid. This is the foundation of hydraulic systems, brakes, and lifts. Choice A (absorbed and converted to heat) describes friction or compression losses, not the transmission of pressure. Choice C (reduced by depth) is true for static fluid pressure due to gravity but is not Pascal''s principle; Pascal''s law concerns the added pressure from external force. Choice D (only upward) is geometrically wrong; fluids transmit applied pressure in every direction at once.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'A frictionless ramp is 12 feet long and rises 3 feet vertically. What is its mechanical advantage?', '["3","4","9","36"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mechanical advantage of an inclined plane = length of slope / vertical height = 12 / 3 = 4. A longer ramp (relative to height) requires less force but the load must travel a greater distance. MA = 4 means you need 1/4 of the load''s weight as effort force.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'A hydraulic system input piston has an area of 5 in² and the output piston has an area of 25 in². If the input force is 100 pounds, what force does the output piston exert?', '["20 pounds","100 pounds","500 pounds","2,500 pounds"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Hydraulic force multiplication: F_out = F_in x (A_out / A_in) = 100 x (25 / 5) = 100 x 5 = 500 pounds. Choice A (20 pounds) inverts the area ratio and divides force by 5 instead of multiplying. Choice B (100 pounds) ignores the area difference entirely. Choice D (2,500 pounds) multiplies force by the output area alone (100 x 25), ignoring the input area in the denominator. Hydraulics multiply force by the ratio of areas; the input piston moves a longer distance with less force, the output piston moves a shorter distance with more force, conserving work.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 3, 'A ramp 20 feet long rises 5 feet. A 240-pound load is pushed up the ramp. What effort force is required (frictionless)?', '["12 pounds","40 pounds","48 pounds","60 pounds"]'::jsonb, 3, 'MA = ramp length / height = 20 / 5 = 4. Effort = Load / MA = 240 / 4 = 60 pounds. A trap answer of 48 pounds corresponds to 240 / 5 (dividing by height instead of MA).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 3, 'A hydraulic brake system has an input piston area of 1 in² and the brake caliper piston area is 3 in². A driver applies 30 pounds of force at the brake pedal, which the booster amplifies by a factor of 4 before reaching the master cylinder. How much clamping force does the caliper exert?', '["30 pounds","90 pounds","120 pounds","360 pounds"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Two stages of multiplication apply in series. Booster: 30 x 4 = 120 pounds at the master cylinder. Hydraulic area ratio: 120 x (3/1) = 360 pounds at the caliper. Choice A (30 pounds) ignores both stages. Choice B (90 pounds) applies only the hydraulic ratio to the bare pedal force (30 x 3 = 90), skipping the booster. Choice C (120 pounds) stops after the booster and ignores the hydraulic stage. When mechanical and hydraulic advantages chain together, you multiply their factors: total MA = 4 x 3 = 12, and final force = 30 x 12 = 360 pounds.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 3, 'A wedge has a length of 10 inches and a thickness (wide end) of 2 inches. You drive it under a 600-pound rock. How much driving force is needed to generate the lifting force (assuming MA fully transfers)?', '["60 pounds","120 pounds","300 pounds","600 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Wedge MA = length / thickness = 10 / 2 = 5. Driving force = Load / MA = 600 / 5 = 120 pounds. Choice A (60 pounds) doubles the wedge MA to 10, perhaps using length / (thickness/2). Choice C (300 pounds) halves the load and ignores the MA, treating the wedge like a simple lever with MA = 2. Choice D (600 pounds) skips the wedge entirely and uses the load weight as the required force. A wedge converts a small driving force along its length into a much larger splitting force perpendicular to its motion, just like an inclined plane in mirror image.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 4, 'In a hydraulic system, the input piston moves down 10 inches with an area of 2 in². The output piston has an area of 8 in². How far does the output piston move upward?', '["1.25 inches","2.5 inches","5 inches","40 inches"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Fluid volume is conserved: Volume in = Volume out. Input volume = 2 in² × 10 in = 20 in³. Output: 20 in³ = 8 in² × d. d = 20 / 8 = 2.5 inches. The output piston moves a shorter distance but with proportionally more force — the same trade-off as any mechanical advantage system.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 4, 'A loading ramp is 18 feet long and rises 6 feet. An 800-pound engine is pushed up the ramp with a steady force. How much work is done on the engine as it is raised the full 6 feet vertically? (Work = Force × Distance traveled; use the vertical height.)', '["800 foot-pounds","2,400 foot-pounds","4,800 foot-pounds","14,400 foot-pounds"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Work done against gravity = weight × vertical height = 800 × 6 = 4,800 foot-pounds. The ramp''s MA (18/6 = 3) reduces the effort force to 800/3 ≈ 267 pounds, but you push over 18 feet of ramp: 267 × 18 = 4,800 ft-lb — the same result, confirming conservation of energy. Work done on the load always equals weight × height, regardless of the path.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 4, 'A hydraulic press has an input cylinder of area 3 cm² and an output cylinder of area 75 cm². A technician pushes the input piston down 50 cm. What is the output force if the input force is 60 N?', '["60 N","300 N","1,500 N","3,750 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area ratio = 75 / 3 = 25. Output force = 60 × 25 = 1,500 N. The output piston moves 50 × (3/75) = 2 cm — short distance but large force. Output piston travel is inversely proportional to the area ratio, confirming energy conservation.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 5, 'An engine hoist uses a compound system: a 3:1 lever feeds into a 4-rope pulley block-and-tackle. An engine weighs 600 pounds. What is the minimum effort force required at the lever input to lift the engine?', '["50 pounds","200 pounds","400 pounds","600 pounds"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When simple machines are combined in series, their mechanical advantages multiply: Total MA = 3 x 4 = 12. Effort = Load / Total MA = 600 / 12 = 50 pounds. Choice B (200 pounds) uses only the pulley MA of 3, ignoring the lever. Choice C (400 pounds) reduces the load by only 1.5, perhaps averaging the MAs (3+4)/2 instead of multiplying. Choice D (600 pounds) ignores both stages and uses the full engine weight. Compound machines trade input force for input distance: you pull through 12 times the distance the engine rises.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 5, 'A hydraulic system output piston has an area of 50 in². The system pressure is 200 psi. What force does the output piston exert?', '["4 pounds","250 pounds","10,000 pounds","1,000,000 pounds"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Force = Pressure × Area = 200 psi × 50 in² = 10,000 pounds. This is the fundamental hydraulic force formula. The trap answer 250 pounds comes from adding (200 + 50) rather than multiplying, and 4 pounds comes from dividing (200 / 50).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'Newton''s Second Law of Motion states that force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). If a 2-kg object has an acceleration of 10 m/s², what is the net force on it?', '["5 N","12 N","20 N","0.2 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Newton''s Second Law: F = m x a = 2 kg x 10 m/s^2 = 20 N. Choice A (5 N) divides incorrectly (a / m / 2). Choice B (12 N) adds mass and acceleration (2 + 10), mixing incompatible units. Choice D (0.2 N) inverts the formula and divides mass by acceleration (2 / 10). Force is proportional to both mass and acceleration; the units (N = kg m/s^2) confirm the multiplicative relationship. Heavier objects need more force for the same acceleration; lighter objects accelerate more under the same force.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'A ball is thrown horizontally from a building ledge. At the instant it leaves the thrower''s hand, which direction does gravity act on it?', '["Horizontally, in the direction of throw","Upward, opposing the throw","Vertically downward, regardless of horizontal motion","At a 45-degree angle combining horizontal and vertical"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Near Earth''s surface, gravity acts vertically downward at 9.8 m/s^2 regardless of horizontal motion. The instant the ball leaves the hand, the only force on it (ignoring air resistance) is the downward pull of gravity. Choice A (horizontal in direction of throw) confuses initial velocity with the gravitational force; the throw gives velocity, not a continued force. Choice B (upward) reverses gravity''s direction. Choice D (45 degrees) adds a horizontal component to gravity that does not exist; horizontal and vertical motions are independent in projectile motion, with gravity acting only on the vertical component.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'What is the momentum of a 4-kg object moving at 15 m/s?', '["3.75 kg·m/s","11 kg·m/s","60 kg·m/s","225 kg·m/s"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Momentum p = mass × velocity = 4 kg × 15 m/s = 60 kg·m/s. Dividing instead of multiplying (4/15 ≈ 0.27 or 15/4 = 3.75) inverts the formula. Momentum is a vector quantity with units of kg·m/s.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 5, 'In a perfectly inelastic collision, two objects stick together after impact. What is conserved in this type of collision?', '["Kinetic energy only","Momentum only","Both kinetic energy and momentum","Neither momentum nor kinetic energy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In any collision (elastic or inelastic), total momentum is conserved. In a perfectly inelastic collision, kinetic energy is NOT conserved — some is converted to heat, sound, and deformation. Elastic collisions conserve both momentum and kinetic energy.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'A rocket in space fires its engines and accelerates. Newton''s Third Law explains this by stating that:', '["Objects in space have no inertia and respond to any force","The exhaust gases are pushed backward, and the rocket is pushed forward by an equal and opposite reaction force","The rocket''s mass decreases as fuel is burned, increasing speed automatically","Gravity pulls the rocket forward in the direction of acceleration"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Newton''s Third Law: for every action force there is an equal and opposite reaction force. The rocket pushes exhaust gases backward (action); the gases push the rocket forward with an equal force (reaction). Because the action-reaction pair acts on the rocket and the gases (not on the surrounding air), thrust works in a vacuum. Choice A (no inertia in space) is wrong; objects retain their mass and inertia everywhere. Choice C (mass loss alone causes speed) ignores that a force is needed to accelerate the remaining mass. Choice D (gravity pulls forward) misidentifies the force; gravity pulls toward planetary masses, not in the direction of acceleration.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 3, 'A 3-kg object moving east at 8 m/s collides with a 3-kg object at rest. They stick together. What is the velocity of the combined mass immediately after the collision?', '["8 m/s east","4 m/s east","0 m/s","2 m/s east"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Conservation of momentum: p_before = (3 × 8) + (3 × 0) = 24 kg·m/s. Combined mass = 6 kg. v_after = 24 / 6 = 4 m/s east. The combined mass is twice the original, so velocity is halved. This is a perfectly inelastic collision — kinetic energy is not conserved but momentum is.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 3, 'A ball is thrown upward and reaches its highest point. At that exact moment, what is the ball''s velocity and what is its acceleration?', '["Velocity = 0 m/s; acceleration = 0 m/s² (weightless at peak)","Velocity = 0 m/s; acceleration = 9.8 m/s² downward","Velocity = peak speed; acceleration = 9.8 m/s² upward","Velocity = 0 m/s; acceleration is upward until it reverses"]'::jsonb, 1, 'At the highest point, vertical velocity is momentarily zero (the ball is neither moving up nor down). However, gravity still acts downward at 9.8 m/s² continuously — acceleration due to gravity never stops, regardless of the object''s velocity. This is a common misconception: zero velocity does not mean zero acceleration.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 3, 'Two balls are dropped simultaneously from the same height: Ball A has a mass of 1 kg, Ball B has a mass of 5 kg. Ignoring air resistance, which hits the ground first?', '["Ball A, because it is lighter and falls more easily","Ball B, because gravity exerts more force on it","They hit at the same time","It depends on the shape of the balls"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Galileo''s principle: in the absence of air resistance, all objects fall with the same gravitational acceleration (g ≈ 9.8 m/s²) regardless of mass. Although gravity exerts more force on Ball B, Ball B also has more inertia (F = ma → a = F/m, and F and m both scale with mass, so a = g for all). Both hit simultaneously.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 4, 'A stationary 8-kg bowling ball is struck by a 0.5-kg cue ball moving at 20 m/s. After the collision, the cue ball bounces straight back at 10 m/s. Using conservation of momentum, what is the approximate velocity of the bowling ball after the collision?', '["0.94 m/s in the original direction of the cue ball","1.875 m/s in the original direction","20 m/s in the original direction","10 m/s backward"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Taking the cue ball''s initial direction as positive: p_before = 0.5 × 20 + 8 × 0 = 10 kg·m/s. p_after = 0.5 × (−10) + 8 × v_bowling. 10 = −5 + 8v → 8v = 15 → v = 1.875 m/s in the original forward direction. The cue ball reverses direction (negative), transferring most of its momentum to the heavier ball.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-1', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Three pieces are given: Piece A is a large right triangle with a right angle at the bottom-left corner. Piece B is a small right triangle with the right angle at the top-right corner. Piece C is a rectangle. When pieces A, B, and C are assembled together, which figure results?', '["A large rectangle whose width equals the base of piece A","A square with side length equal to the height of piece A","A large right triangle with no interior gaps","An L-shaped piece with a notch on one side"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Piece A (large right triangle) and piece B (small right triangle) share matching hypotenuse angles. Placing B against A along the hypotenuse fills the diagonal strip and produces a rectangle whose width equals A''s base. Piece C (rectangle) then extends the figure in the same width direction, completing a larger rectangle. ''A large right triangle with no interior gaps'' cannot form, because adding a rectangle (piece C) to a triangle straightens one side and disqualifies the triangle outline. ''A square'' would require both dimensions to match, which the pieces'' proportions do not guarantee. ''An L-shape'' requires a notch that the rectangle C is specifically filling.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Two pieces are shown: Piece A is a medium square with a dot in its center. Piece B is an identical medium square with no markings. When placed side by side along their right and left edges respectively, what shape results?', '["A large square","A tall thin rectangle","A wide rectangle with the dot on the left half","A wide rectangle with the dot on the right half"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two identical squares placed edge to edge span twice the width and the same height, producing a 2:1 wide rectangle. Piece A (with the dot) is on the left, so the dot sits in the left half. ''A large square'' would require placing the squares to also double the height, which side-by-side placement does not do. ''A tall thin rectangle'' confuses the long axis: the squares meet horizontally, so the result is wide. ''Wide rectangle with the dot on the right half'' reverses the placement of piece A.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Four small right triangles, each identical and each with a right angle at the bottom-left, are shown. When all four are assembled by rotating pairs to face each other and joining along their hypotenuses, what shape do they form?', '["A large right triangle","A rectangle","A parallelogram","An irregular pentagon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Two right triangles joined along their hypotenuses (one rotated 180 degrees relative to the other) form a rectangle, since the right-angle corners are now diagonally opposite and the legs line up edge to edge. Doing this with all four triangles produces two such rectangles, which then sit side by side to make one larger rectangle. ''A large right triangle'' would require pairing along legs, not hypotenuses, and would leave a triangular outline rather than a four-sided one. ''A parallelogram'' would result from sliding rather than reflecting the pieces. ''An irregular pentagon'' requires five sides, but the four-triangle hypotenuse pairing has exactly four straight edges.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Three pieces are given: Piece A is a large equilateral triangle marked with an arrow pointing up. Piece B is an identical equilateral triangle with no marking. Piece C is a small equilateral triangle. Pieces A and B are joined along one edge with B flipped (pointing down). Where should piece C be placed to complete a larger equilateral triangle?', '["Along the left edge of piece A","In the gap at the upper-right where the two piece edges don''t meet","In the corner gap at the bottom where the combined A-B shape has an open notch","On top of piece A to extend it upward"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Joining two equilateral triangles along a shared edge with opposite orientations (one apex up, one apex down) creates a rhombus shape, not a complete equilateral triangle. A small equilateral triangle is needed to fill the bottom-corner notch where the combined shape sweeps inward, completing the larger equilateral triangle outline. ''Along the left edge'' would extend the figure sideways rather than fill any gap. ''In the upper-right gap'' does not match the bottom-pointing geometry of the joined pair. ''On top of piece A'' would simply double-cover existing area rather than complete a new shape.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Four pieces are shown: Piece A is a large square. Piece B is a right triangle whose legs are each half the side length of piece A. Piece C is an identical triangle to B. Piece D is an identical triangle to B. When B, C, and D are assembled and attached to piece A, which shape results?', '["A larger square","A regular hexagon","A square with one corner cut off","A pentagon with one right angle"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The geometry depends on whether the triangles attach inside or outside the square. Pressed against three corners of the square externally, with the right angle of each triangle matching a corner, each triangle extends one side of the square outward. The combined boundary becomes a five-sided figure where one corner retains the original 90 degree angle of the square. ''A regular hexagon'' would require equal angles and sides, which extending three corners cannot produce. ''A larger square'' would require four matching extensions, not three. ''A square with one corner cut off'' is the inverse arrangement (subtracting rather than adding).', false, 'draft'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Two pieces are given: Piece A is an L-shaped piece (a 3×2 rectangle with a 1×1 square removed from one corner). Piece B is a small 1×1 square. When piece B is placed in the missing corner of piece A, what shape results?', '["A 3×2 rectangle","A 2×3 rectangle (same thing, different orientation)","A T-shape","A 4×1 strip"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Piece A is a 3 by 2 rectangle with a 1 by 1 corner removed, leaving an L-shape. Piece B is exactly the 1 by 1 square that was removed. Placing B back into the missing corner restores the original 3 by 2 rectangle. The 2 by 3 rectangle option is the same shape with axes swapped, but the puzzle specifies a 3 by 2 orientation. ''A T-shape'' would form only if B were attached to the outside of the L, extending a leg. ''A 4 by 1 strip'' would require breaking apart and re-arranging the L, which the problem does not allow.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Three pieces are given: Piece A is a medium isosceles right triangle with the right angle at top. Piece B is an identical triangle. Piece C is a small square whose side equals the leg length of pieces A and B. When A and B are placed with their hypotenuses together, then C is attached to one open side, which figure results?', '["A larger isosceles right triangle","A square","A rectangle that is twice as wide as it is tall","A rectangle with a triangular bump on one end"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two isosceles right triangles joined along their hypotenuses form a square whose side equals the triangles'' leg length. Adding piece C, a square of the same side length, along one open edge of that square extends it horizontally into a rectangle measuring 2 leg-lengths wide and 1 leg-length tall, a 2:1 ratio. ''A larger isosceles right triangle'' would require placing the triangles'' legs together instead of hypotenuses. ''A square'' covers only the first step (triangles alone) before C is added. ''A rectangle with a triangular bump'' would result only if C were attached at an angle or off-center, not flush along an edge.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Five pieces are labeled A–E. Piece A is a large square. Pieces B and C are identical right triangles each with legs equal to half the side of A. Piece D is a small square with side equal to one-quarter the side of A. Piece E is a thin rectangle. When all five pieces are assembled without gaps or overlaps, which overall shape results?', '["A large right triangle","A large square larger than piece A","A large rectangle that is twice as long as it is wide","A T-shape"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The pieces include a large square A, two triangles with legs equal to half of A''s side, a small square equal to one-quarter of A''s side, and a thin rectangle. Combined areas can in principle tile a square whose side is 1.5 times piece A. The triangles fill two corner gaps, the small square fills a quarter-corner gap, and the rectangle bridges the remaining strip. ''A large right triangle'' has the wrong outline (3 sides instead of 4). ''A 2:1 rectangle'' would leave gaps that the given piece set cannot fill. ''A T-shape'' has notches that an enclosed tiling does not produce.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Piece A is a large right triangle with the right angle at the lower-left, the vertical leg on the left, and the horizontal leg on the bottom. Piece B is a smaller right triangle that is congruent to the upper-left half of piece A when it is cut along its median. Piece C is the remaining lower-right portion of that median cut. When B and C are reassembled, which shape do they form?', '["A square","A shape identical to piece A","A rectangle","A parallelogram"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pieces B and C are described as the two halves of piece A cut along its median to the hypotenuse. Reuniting them along that cut line restores piece A exactly. The result is geometrically identical to the original triangle. ''A square'' would require the cut to produce four equal corners, which a single median cut cannot do. ''A rectangle'' would require the cut piece pair to share a right angle on every corner, which a triangle''s halves do not. ''A parallelogram'' would require sliding rather than re-attaching B and C, separating them rather than re-joining them.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Four pieces: Piece A is a large square with a diagonal line drawn from the top-left to the bottom-right corner. Pieces B, C, D are right triangles of equal size. When B, C, and D are placed against piece A so that each triangle''s hypotenuse aligns with an outer edge of A, which overall assembled figure results?', '["A regular octagon","A larger square rotated 45°","A plus sign (cross shape)","A star shape"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Adding isosceles right triangles to the outside of a square with their hypotenuses flush along three sides extends three of the square''s edges outward into points. Depending on the proportions of the triangles, the assembled outline forms a larger square oriented at 45 degrees relative to the original. ''A regular octagon'' would require eight equal sides and angles, which only emerges from a more symmetric cut. ''A plus sign'' results from placing the triangles on the inside or from using rectangles instead. ''A star shape'' requires triangles on every side with notches between them, not flush hypotenuses.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Three pieces: Piece A is a large rectangle (3 units wide, 2 units tall). Piece B is a right triangle with legs 2 units and 1 unit. Piece C is a right triangle identical to B. B and C are mirror images of each other. When B is placed against the right side of A (hypotenuse facing A''s right edge), and C is placed against the left side (mirrored), which shape results?', '["A regular hexagon","A parallelogram","A hexagon with two right angles","A parallelogram with clipped corners"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Placing two opposite-facing right triangles on the short ends of a rectangle, each angled in the same slant direction (mirror images that nonetheless lean the same way along the long axis), converts the rectangle into a parallelogram. The triangles shift each short side into a slanted edge while preserving the top and bottom horizontal edges. ''A regular hexagon'' has six sides with equal lengths and angles, neither of which the rectangle plus triangle pair produces. ''A hexagon with two right angles'' would require the original short sides of the rectangle to survive as vertical edges, but the triangles replace them. ''A parallelogram with clipped corners'' would require additional cuts.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Six pieces labeled A–F. Piece A is a medium square. Piece B is a medium square of identical size. Piece C is a right triangle with legs equal to the side of A. Piece D is an identical triangle to C. Piece E is a small rectangle 1×2 units. Piece F is a 1×1 square. All pieces assembled without gaps or overlap: which overall shape is formed?', '["A square whose side equals twice the side of piece A","A rectangle twice as long as it is wide","An irregular pentagon","A large right triangle"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Two squares of side s (A and B) form a 2s by s rectangle when joined edge to edge. The two right triangles with legs s each fill the two open corners above (or below), extending the figure into a 2s by 2s square. The thin rectangle E and the small square F fit into the remaining interior gaps to complete the tiling. The result is a square whose side equals 2s, twice piece A. ''A 2:1 rectangle'' covers only the first step. ''An irregular pentagon'' has five sides, which an enclosed tiling does not produce. ''A large right triangle'' has the wrong outline entirely.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Piece A is a large isosceles trapezoid with a long base of 4 units, a short top of 2 units, and height 2 units. Piece B is a right triangle with legs 2 units each. Piece C is an identical right triangle to B. When B is placed against trapezoid A''s left slanted edge and C is placed against the right slanted edge, what overall shape is formed?', '["A large rectangle 4 units wide and 2 units tall","A large square 4 units on each side","A regular hexagon","A parallelogram"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The trapezoid has a long base of 4 and short top of 2, leaving a horizontal offset of 1 unit on each slanted side. Each right triangle placed against a slanted edge fills the gap between that slant and a vertical line, extending the trapezoid into a rectangle with width matching the long base and height matching the trapezoid''s height. The result is a 4 by 2 rectangle. ''A 4 by 4 square'' would require doubling the height. ''A regular hexagon'' needs six equal sides, not four. ''A parallelogram'' would result if both triangles slanted in the same direction, but mirrored triangles square off both ends.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-14', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Piece A is a large square. A smaller square piece B (half the side of A) is cut from the center-right of A, leaving an L-shape. Piece C is that same smaller square. Piece D is a right triangle with legs equal to half the side of A. When pieces A (L-shape), C, and D are assembled in a flat arrangement without overlap, what results?', '["A shape identical to the original large square A","A right triangle larger than piece D","A rectangle that is 1.5 times as long as it is wide","A pentagon"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Re-attaching the missing square (piece C) to the L-shaped remainder restores the original large square. Adding the right triangle D, which has legs equal to half the side of A, along one outer edge extends the figure by a triangular bump. With the right proportion choice, that bump completes the shape into a rectangle 1.5 times longer than it is wide. ''A shape identical to the original square'' ignores piece D. ''A right triangle'' would require the square to fold into a triangle, which it cannot. ''A pentagon'' would result from triangle D being attached at an angle or only partially.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-15', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Pieces A, B, C, D are four congruent parallelograms, each with a horizontal top edge and slanted sides leaning to the right. When the four pieces are arranged in a 2×2 grid with alternating orientations (every other piece flipped upside down), what overall shape is formed?', '["A large parallelogram","A large rectangle","A rhombus","An irregular hexagon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each parallelogram leans the same direction on its own, but flipping every other parallelogram in a 2 by 2 grid reverses its slant. When laid out, the slanted edges of adjacent flipped and unflipped pieces meet to form straight vertical edges along the left and right of the grid, while the top and bottom remain horizontal. The combined boundary is a rectangle. ''A large parallelogram'' would result from placing all four in the same orientation, not alternating. ''A rhombus'' has four equal slanted sides, which alternating parallelograms cancel out. ''An irregular hexagon'' would require six sides, but the alternation produces exactly four straight edges.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-16', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Seven pieces: Piece A is a regular hexagon with a dot at its center. Pieces B through G are six equilateral triangles, each with one side equal to the side length of hexagon A. When all six triangles (B–G) are placed against each outer edge of hexagon A, what shape results?', '["A larger regular hexagon","A 12-pointed star","A regular 12-sided polygon (dodecagon)","A six-pointed Star of David shape"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A regular hexagon has 120 degree interior angles. At every hexagon vertex, two adjacent triangles meet, each contributing one 60 degree base angle. That leaves 360 minus 120 minus 60 minus 60 equals 120 degrees of empty space outside the hexagon at each vertex, which is a concave inward notch. The six triangle apexes form the convex outward points, and the six concave notches sit between them, producing a six-pointed Star of David shape (hexagram). ''A larger regular hexagon'' is the trap of assuming adjacent triangle edges line up, but they meet at a 120 degree concave angle, not 180. A ''dodecagon'' would need equal convex angles, not alternating tips and notches. A ''12-pointed star'' would need 12 tips, but the figure has only 6.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-17', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Three pieces: Piece A is a right triangle with legs 3 and 4 units. Piece B is a right triangle with legs 3 and 4 units (identical to A). Piece C is a 3 by 4 rectangle. When A and B are joined along their hypotenuses to form a rectangle, and C is placed along the 4-unit side of that combined rectangle, what shape is formed?', '["A square with side 5 units","A rectangle 4 units wide and 6 units tall","A rectangle 3 units wide and 8 units tall","A 3 by 4 rectangle"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Two right triangles with legs 3 and 4 joined along their hypotenuses reconstitute a 3 by 4 rectangle (area 12), because cutting a rectangle along its diagonal gives exactly those two triangles. Placing the second 3 by 4 rectangle C against the 4-unit side stacks the two rectangles into a 4 wide by 6 tall figure (total area 24). ''A 5 by 5 square'' has area 25 and does not match the combined area. ''A 3 by 8 rectangle'' would require joining the rectangles along their 3-unit sides, not the 4-unit sides specified in the stem. ''A 3 by 4 rectangle'' counts only the first step of assembly.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Pieces A–D are four identical right trapezoids, each with a long parallel side of 4 units, a short parallel side of 2 units, and height 2 units. The slanted leg rises from the right end of the long base. When the four trapezoids are arranged so that each slanted leg fits flush against the next piece''s slanted leg (alternating flip), what overall shape results?', '["A large square","A large regular octagon","A large rectangle 8 units wide and 4 units tall","A large parallelogram"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Each pair of mirrored trapezoids (normal + flipped) forms a rectangle 6 units wide and 2 units tall. Two such pairs stacked vertically give a rectangle 6×4 — but joining all four end-to-end yields 8 units wide × 2 units tall when laid flat. Accounting for all edges correctly: four trapezoids in alternating-flip row produce an 8×2 rectangle; two rows give 8×4.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-19', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Three pieces: Piece A is a medium square (side = 2 units) with a diagonal arrow pointing from the bottom-left to the top-right corner. Piece B is a right triangle with legs 2 and 2 units (the lower-left half of a same-sized square). Piece C is a right triangle with legs 2 and 2 units (the upper-right half). When A, B, and C are assembled flat without overlap, what shape results?', '["A 2×4 rectangle","A large right triangle with legs 4 units each","A large square with side 2√2","A 2×2 square with two triangular ears on the sides"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Piece A is a 2 by 2 square (area 4). Pieces B and C are right triangles with legs 2 and 2 (area 2 each). Total area = 8, matching a right triangle with legs 4 and 4. The square fits one corner of that larger triangle and the two right triangles fill the other two corner regions. ''A 2 by 4 rectangle'' has area 8 too, but its four-right-angle outline does not match the L-shaped reassembly. ''A square with side 2 times sqrt 2'' has area 8 but requires a rotated arrangement. ''A 2 by 2 square with triangular ears'' leaves protrusions rather than enclosing a clean shape.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-20', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Five pieces are shown. Piece A is a large equilateral triangle (side 4 units). Pieces B, C, D are small equilateral triangles (side 2 units). Piece E is a rhombus made from two small equilateral triangles joined at one edge. When A, B, C, D, and E are assembled, which shape results?', '["A regular hexagon with side 2 units","A larger equilateral triangle with side 6 units","A trapezoid","A regular hexagon with side 4 units"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Measure everything in units of small triangles (side 2 each). Large triangle A (side 4) holds 4 small-triangle areas. The three small triangles add 3. The rhombus E (two joined) adds 2. Total = 9, exactly the area of an equilateral triangle with side 6. They tile that triangle with A at one corner, the rhombus filling an adjacent strip, and the small triangles completing the outer edge. ''A hexagon side 2'' has area 6 small-triangle units, too small. ''A trapezoid'' has the wrong outline. ''A hexagon side 4'' has area 24, far too large.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-1', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A rectangular prism (box) is sitting with its longest dimension running left to right. If you rotate it 90° by tipping it backward (the top face tilts away from you, rotating around the back-bottom edge), which face is now on top?', '["The original top face","The original bottom face","The original back face","The original front face"]'::jsonb, 3, 'When the prism tips backward around its back-bottom edge, that edge stays fixed and the cube falls onto its back face. The original top rotates away to become the new back, the original front swings upward to occupy the top position, and the original bottom moves to face the viewer as the new front. So the new top is the original front face. ''The original top face'' would only stay on top if no rotation occurred. ''The original bottom face'' would require a 180 degree rotation. ''The original back face'' rotates downward to the bottom, not upward.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A cube has colored stickers: top = orange, bottom = purple, front = red, back = blue, left = green, right = white. The cube is picked up and turned upside-down (rotated 180° around a horizontal front-to-back axis). What color is now on top?', '["Orange","Purple","Red","Blue"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Flipping the cube 180 degrees around the horizontal front-to-back axis spins it like a wheel through the front and back faces, swapping top with bottom and left with right while front and back remain fixed. The original bottom (purple) ends up on top. ''Orange'' would only stay on top if no rotation had occurred. ''Red'' and ''Blue'' label the front and back faces, which the axis preserves rather than moves to the top.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'You are looking directly at the front face of a rectangular prism. It is then rotated 90 degrees around its vertical axis so that the left side swings toward you. Which face is now facing you?', '["The original front face","The original right face","The original back face","The original left face"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The stem tells you directly which face moves where: the left side swings toward you, so the new front is the original left face. After this quarter turn, the original front has rotated to become the new right side, the original right has rotated to the new back, and the original back has rotated to the new left. Choice B confuses the rotation direction (right swinging forward would be a rotation in the opposite sense). Choice A would require no rotation at all. Choice C would require a 180 degree spin, not 90.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cube: top = silver, bottom = gold, front = red, back = blue, left = green, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90° to the right around the vertical axis (the right face swings to the front). Then rotate 90° forward — tilting the new top toward you, pivoting around the new front-bottom edge. What color is now on top after both rotations?', '["Yellow","Silver","Red","Blue"]'::jsonb, 0, 'After rotation 1 (90° right around vertical axis): the right face (yellow) moves to front, the front (red) moves to left, the left (green) moves to back, the back (blue) moves to right; top stays silver. After rotation 2 (90° forward, pivoting around the front-bottom edge): the new front face (yellow) swings up to become the new top. Final top = yellow (index 0).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A rectangular prism is 2 units wide, 3 units tall, and 4 units deep. You view it from directly in front. If you then view it from directly above (bird''s-eye view), what shape do you see?', '["A 2×3 rectangle","A 2×4 rectangle","A 3×4 rectangle","A 4×4 square"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The bird''s-eye view from directly above shows the prism''s top face, which is bounded by width and depth: 2 by 4. Height drops out of the view because the eye looks straight down along that axis. ''2 by 3'' is the front view (width by height). ''3 by 4'' is the side view (height by depth). ''4 by 4'' has no matching face on the prism. Each viewpoint projects out the dimension along its sight line, so identifying which dimension disappears (height for the top view) gives the answer directly.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A cube has colored faces: top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate 90° to the left around its vertical axis, then rotate 90° backward (top tilts away from you, pivoting around the back-bottom edge). What color is now facing you (front) after both rotations?', '["Blue","White","Black","Yellow"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rotation 1 (90° left, vertical): left (blue) → back, back (green) → right, right (yellow) → front, front (red) → left. Top = white, bottom = black. Rotation 2 (90° backward, around back-bottom edge): new top = original back = green; new front = original top = white; new bottom = original front = yellow; new back = original bottom = black. Front face = white.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A solid triangular prism rests with one rectangular face flat on a table. You view it from the front and see a rectangle. What shape do you see when you view it from the left end?', '["A rectangle","A triangle","A square","A trapezoid"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A triangular prism has two triangular end faces and three rectangular side faces connecting them. The front view (a rectangular face) shows a rectangle. Looking at the left end reveals the triangular cross-section at that end. ''A rectangle'' would result from any side-face view but not an end-face view. ''A square'' would require equal-sided rectangles, which the problem does not guarantee. ''A trapezoid'' results from cutting a prism obliquely, not from looking at its standard end face.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A cube is placed with face 1 on top. It is then rotated 90° forward twice in a row (each time the top tilts toward you, pivoting around the front-bottom edge). After both rotations, which original face is now on top?', '["The original top face (face 1)","The original front face","The original bottom face (face opposite face 1)","The original back face"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Each 90 degree forward rotation cycles the faces so that the face at the back rotates up to become the new top, the original top moves forward to become the new front, the original front rotates down to the bottom, and the original bottom rotates back to the rear. After one rotation, the original back is on top. After two rotations, the face that was at back-after-the-first rotation (which is the original bottom) is now on top. ''The original top'' would only return after four rotations. ''The original front'' is on top after three rotations, not two. ''The original back'' is on top after one rotation only.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A cube has faces numbered 1 (top), 2 (bottom), 3 (front), 4 (back), 5 (left), 6 (right). It is rotated 90° to the right (around vertical axis), then 90° to the right again, then 90° forward (around front-bottom edge). What number is on top?', '["1","3","4","2"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Starting state: top=1, bottom=2, front=3, back=4, left=5, right=6. Right rotation 1 (vertical axis): right→front, old front→left, old left→back, old back→right; top and bottom unchanged. After rot1: front=6, left=3, back=5, right=4; top=1, bottom=2. Right rotation 2: front=4, left=6, back=3, right=5; top=1, bottom=2. Forward rotation 3 (top toward you, front-bottom pivot): top→front, front→bottom, bottom→back, back→top. New top = old back = 3. Answer = 3, choice b, index 1.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A rectangular prism has dimensions 1×2×4 (height × width × depth). If you slice it with a horizontal plane halfway up its height, what shape is the cross-section?', '["A 1×2 rectangle","A 2×4 rectangle","A 1×4 rectangle","A square"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A horizontal slice through the rectangular prism, taken at any height, exposes a face parallel to the top and bottom. Its dimensions are width by depth, which the problem states as 2 by 4. The vertical height of 1 unit does not appear in the cross-section because the cut is perpendicular to that axis. ''1 by 2'' uses height and width but omits depth. ''1 by 4'' uses height and depth but omits width. ''A square'' would require width equal to depth, which is not the case here.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90 degrees to the right around its vertical axis (the right face swings toward you to become the new front). What color is now on the left side?', '["Blue","Red","Green","Yellow"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The stem specifies the direction: the right face swings forward to become the new front. The same quarter turn rotates the original front to the left, the original left to the back, and the original back to the right. Top and bottom sit on the rotation axis and do not move. The new left face shows the original front color, red. ''Blue'' was the original left and has rotated to the back. ''Green'' was the original back and now sits on the right. ''Yellow'' was the original right and is now on the front.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 5, 'A regular tetrahedron (4 identical equilateral-triangle faces) rests on one face. You rotate it 120° around the vertical axis passing through the top vertex. How many faces look identical in position to where they started?', '["0","1","2","4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The top vertex stays fixed during a vertical-axis rotation. The face on the bottom (the base) stays in the same horizontal plane. 120° is exactly one-third of a full rotation, which is a symmetry of the triangular base — the base face maps to itself. The three side faces cycle among themselves. So exactly 1 face (the bottom) is in the same position.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 5, 'A cube is sliced by a plane that passes through the midpoints of four parallel edges — specifically the four edges running left-to-right on the front and back faces (two on the front face, two on the back). What is the shape of the cross-section?', '["A square","A rectangle that is not a square","A rhombus","A trapezoid"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The four edges referenced are the top-front, bottom-front, top-back, and bottom-back edges. Their midpoints sit at the cube''s horizontal middle and form the four corners of a square in the vertical plane running front-to-back through the center. The cross-section is a square. ''A rectangle that is not a square'' would require two distinct edge lengths, but the midpoints are equidistant. ''A rhombus'' has equal sides, but the 90 degree angles here make it specifically a square. ''A trapezoid'' has only one pair of parallel sides, while this cross-section has two pairs.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-14', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 5, 'A solid cylinder is cut by a plane that passes through the cylinder at an angle of 45° to the cylinder''s base (the plane intersects both the top and bottom circles). What shape is the cross-section?', '["A circle","A rectangle","An ellipse","A parabola"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Any plane that cuts a circular cylinder at an angle other than perpendicular (but not parallel to the axis) produces an elliptical cross-section. A perpendicular cut gives a circle; a cut parallel to the axis gives a rectangle.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-15', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90 degrees backward (the top tilts away, pivoting around the back-bottom edge), then 90 degrees to the left around the vertical axis. What color is on the bottom after both rotations?', '["Red","White","Green","Black"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Track the rotation as a die rolling. Rotation 1 tips the top away from the viewer over the back-bottom edge: the original top swings backward and down to become the new back (so white moves to back), the original back swings down to become the new bottom (green to bottom), the original bottom swings forward and up to become the new front (black to front), and the original front swings up to become the new top (red to top). Left and right are unchanged. Rotation 2 spins the cube about a vertical axis, which never changes top or bottom. The bottom remains green. Choice A (red) traces the rotation in the wrong direction (toward the viewer instead of away). Choice B (white) confuses the new back with the new bottom. Choice D (black) assumes the bottom stays put, ignoring rotation 1 entirely.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-16', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90 degrees forward (top tilts toward you, pivoting around the front-bottom edge). What color is now on the back face?', '["White","Green","Red","Black"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A 90 degree forward roll cycles four faces around the cube: top moves to front, front moves to bottom, bottom moves to back, back moves to top. So the original bottom (black) is now on the back. The original top (white) became the new front, not the back, so choice A is the trap of stopping the trace one step early. Choice B (green) confuses the new top with the new back, because the original back face did move during the rotation. Choice C (red) is the trap of keeping the original front in place, but a forward rotation rolls every vertical face by one position.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A net consists of six squares arranged as follows: a row of four squares (labeled 1–4, left to right), square 5 attached to the top edge of square 2, and square 6 attached to the bottom edge of square 3. When this net is folded, what 3D object is formed?', '["An open-top box","A cube","A rectangular prism that is not a cube","A triangular prism"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use square 2 as the base. Square 1 folds up as the left wall, square 3 folds up as the right wall, square 4 (attached to square 3) folds inward from the right wall to form the back wall, square 5 (atop square 2) folds up as the front wall, and square 6 (below square 3) folds inward to cap the top. All six equal squares enclose the volume, forming a cube. ''An open-top box'' covers only 5 squares with no lid. ''A rectangular prism that is not a cube'' would require unequal squares. ''A triangular prism'' requires triangular end faces, which the all-square net cannot produce.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A flat net has the shape of a cross: one square in the center, one square above, one below, one to the left, one to the right, and one more square attached to the right edge of the rightmost square (6 squares total, forming a plus sign with an extra square on one arm). When folded, which face is opposite the center square?', '["The extra square on the extended arm","The square directly above the center","The square directly below the center","The square to the left of the center"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Label: center=C, top=T, bottom=B, left=L, right=R, extra=E (right of R). Fold: C is the base. T, B, L, R fold up to become four side walls. E, which is two squares away from center in the right direction, folds over to become the top (opposite C). T and B are adjacent to C, so they fold to be front/back walls — not opposite C.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A net consists of a column of four squares numbered 1–4 (top to bottom). Square 5 is attached to the right edge of square 1, and square 6 is attached to the right edge of square 4. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square 2?', '["Square 4","Square 5","Square 6","Square 3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Assign square 2 as the base. Square 1 (above 2) folds to become the back wall. Square 3 (below 2) folds to become the front wall. Square 4 (below 3): when 3 is the front wall, 4 folds over it to become the top. Square 5 (right of square 1): when 1 is the back wall, 5 folds along with it to become the right wall. Square 6 (right of square 4): when 4 is the top, 6 folds down to become the left wall. Opposite the base (square 2) is the top = square 4. Answer: square 4, choice a, index 0.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A net for a cube is laid out as follows: a row of three squares (A, B, C) from left to right. Square D is above square B. Square E is below square B. Square F is to the right of square C. When folded, which square is opposite square A?', '["Square C","Square F","Square D","Square E"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Assign B as the base. A (left of B) folds up to become the left wall. C (right of B) folds up to become the right wall. F (right of C): when C is the right wall, F continues to become the top. D (above B) folds to become the front wall. E (below B) folds to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=B, top=F, left=A, right=C, front=D, back=E. Opposite A (left) = C (right) = choice a, index 0.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A net consists of a column of four squares (1 at top, 2, 3, 4 at bottom). Square 5 is attached to the left edge of square 2. Square 6 is attached to the right edge of square 3. When folded into a cube, which two squares are opposite each other?', '["Square 1 and square 4","Square 2 and square 4","Square 5 and square 6","Square 1 and square 3"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Fold step by step with square 2 as base. Square 1 (above 2) folds up → back wall. Square 3 (below 2) folds up → front wall. Square 4 (below 3) continues: it folds over the front wall to become the top (opposite base=2). Square 5 (left of 2): folds up → left wall. Square 6 (right of 3): when square 3 becomes the front wall, square 6 (on its right edge) folds to become the right wall. Opposites: bottom(2) ↔ top(4); back(1) ↔ front(3); left(5) ↔ right(6). Therefore squares 5 and 6 are opposite.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A net consists of a row of four squares (W, X, Y, Z from left to right). Square V is attached to the top edge of square X, and square U is attached to the bottom edge of square Y. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square Z?', '["Square W","Square V","Square U","Square X"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Assign X as the base. W (left of X) folds up to become the left wall. Y (right of X) folds up to become the right wall. Z (right of Y): when Y is the right wall, Z folds over to become the top. V (above X) folds to become the front wall. U (below Y): when Y is the right wall, U is on Y''s bottom edge, folding to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=X, top=Z, left=W, right=Y, front=V, back=U. Opposite Z (top) = X (bottom) = choice d, index 3.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A T-shaped net of 6 squares: a row of three squares (P, Q, R) forms the top of the T. Square S is below Q. Square T is below S. Square U is below T. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square P?', '["Square R","Square T","Square U","Square S"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Assign Q as the base. P (left of Q) folds up to become the left wall. R (right of Q) folds up to become the right wall. S (below Q) folds up to become the front wall. T (below S): when S is the front wall, T folds over it to become the top. U (below T): when T is the top, U folds to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=Q, top=T, left=P, right=R, front=S, back=U. Opposite P (left) = R (right) = choice a, index 0.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A net of 6 squares arranged as: Row 1 has squares A and B (A left, B right). Row 2 has squares C and D (C below A, D below B). Row 3 has squares E and F (E below C, F below D). When folded into a rectangular prism (all squares are the same size, so it is a cube), which square is opposite square B?', '["Square A","Square C","Square E","Square F"]'::jsonb, 2, 'This 2×3 grid net folds as follows: let D be the base. C (left of D) folds up → left wall. B (above D, in row 1) folds up → back wall. A (above C, in row 1) is attached to C; it folds to become the top. E (below C, in row 3) folds up → front wall. F (below D, in row 3) folds up → right wall. Faces: bottom=D, top=A, left=C, right=F, back=B, front=E. Opposite B (back) = E (front) = choice c (index 2).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A net consists of: a central square M, square N attached to M''s top edge, square O attached to N''s top edge, square P attached to M''s right edge, square Q attached to M''s bottom edge, and square R attached to Q''s bottom edge. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square O?', '["Square Q","Square M","Square R","Square N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Assign M as the base. N (above M) folds to become the back wall. O (above N): when N is the back wall, O folds over it to become the top. P (right of M) folds to become the right wall. Q (below M) folds to become the front wall. R (below Q): when Q is the front wall, R folds over it to become the bottom — but since M is the base, R becomes the additional face; the six faces are M(bottom), O(top), N(back), Q(front), P(right), R(left). Opposite O (top) = M (bottom)? No: each square is a distinct face. The face chain from O downward: O→N→M→Q→R. O and R are two squares apart through the spine, making them opposites. Opposite O = R = choice c, index 2.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A cross-shaped net of 5 squares: square 1 in center, squares 2–5 attached to each of its four sides (top, bottom, left, right). A sixth square (6) is attached to the top edge of square 2 (which is above square 1). When folded, which square is opposite square 1 (the center)?', '["Square 2","Square 6","Square 3","Square 4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Let square 1 = base. Square 3 (bottom of 1) → front wall. Square 4 (right of 1) → right wall. Square 5 (left of 1) → left wall. Square 2 (top of 1) → back wall. Square 6 (top of 2): when 2 is the back wall, 6 is on 2''s top edge — it folds over to become the top (opposite base 1). Opposite square 1 = square 6.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A net of 6 squares: square A is the base of a column. Above A are squares B, C (in order from bottom to top). Square D is attached to the right edge of A. Square E is attached to the right edge of B. Square F is attached to the left edge of C. When this net is folded into a cube, which square is opposite square F?', '["Square D","Square A","Square E","Square B"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Assign B as the base. A (below B) folds up to become the front wall. C (above B) folds up to become the back wall. E (right of B) folds to become the right wall. D (right of A): when A is the front wall, D is on A''s right edge and folds to become the bottom. F (left of C): when C is the back wall, F is on C''s left edge and folds to become the left wall. Face assignments: top=B, front=A, back=C, right=E, bottom=D, left=F. Opposite F (left) = E (right) = choice c, index 2.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A square sheet is folded once by bringing the left edge to meet the right edge (a vertical fold, creating a rectangle half the original width). A hole is then punched through all layers at the center of the folded rectangle. When the sheet is unfolded, how many holes are there, and where?', '["One hole in the exact center of the original sheet","Two holes symmetrically placed left and right of center, each at the vertical midpoint","Four holes at the four quadrant centers","Two holes — one in the center of each half — stacked vertically"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single vertical fold halves the sheet''s width and stacks two layers along the fold. The punch goes through both layers at the center of the folded rectangle. When unfolded, the two punch holes appear mirrored across the vertical fold line, both at the same vertical height (the midpoint). ''One hole in the exact center'' would result only if the punch were on the fold line itself. ''Four holes at quadrant centers'' requires two perpendicular folds, not one. ''Two holes stacked vertically'' would result from a horizontal fold, not vertical.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-17', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 5, 'A cube net is arranged as follows: a zigzag row of four squares — square 1, then square 2 to the right of 1, then square 3 above 2, then square 4 to the right of 3. Square 5 is below square 2. Square 6 is to the right of square 4. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square 1?', '["Square 3","Square 4","Square 6","Square 5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Assign square 2 as the base. Square 1 (left of 2) folds up to become the left wall. Square 5 (below 2) folds up to become the front wall. Square 3 (above 2) folds up to become the back wall. Square 4 (right of 3): when 3 is the back wall, square 4 is on 3''s right edge and folds to become the right wall. Square 6 (right of 4): when 4 is the right wall, square 6 folds to become the top. Face assignments: bottom=2, top=6, left=1, right=4, front=5, back=3. Opposite left (1) = right (4) = choice b, index 1.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-1', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A staircase of cubes is built against a wall: the first column from the left is 1 cube tall, the second is 2 cubes tall, and the third is 3 cubes tall. Each column is 1 cube wide and 1 cube deep. How many total cubes are in the staircase?', '["5","6","7","9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each column contains as many cubes as its height: 1 + 2 + 3 = 6 cubes. The staircase formula n(n+1)/2 with n = 3 confirms 3 times 4 divided by 2 = 6. ''5'' undercounts, perhaps missing the top cube of the tallest column. ''7'' overcounts by 1. ''9'' applies the formula for a 3 by 3 grid (9 cubes), which is the bounding box rather than the actual staircase shape.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A rectangular arrangement of cubes is 4 cubes long, 2 cubes wide, and 1 cube tall (a single flat layer). How many cubes are in the arrangement?', '["6","7","8","10"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the three dimensions: 4 long times 2 wide times 1 tall = 8 cubes. ''6'' undercounts, possibly by adding instead of multiplying (4 + 2 = 6). ''7'' has no clear derivation. ''10'' overcounts, possibly by adding the dimensions and an extra 4 (4 + 2 + 4 = 10). The volume formula L times W times H gives 8 directly.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A 2×2×2 cube structure is built from unit cubes. How many unit cubes are used in total?', '["4","6","8","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A 2 by 2 by 2 cube structure contains 2 times 2 times 2 = 8 unit cubes. ''4'' is the count of cubes in a single 2 by 2 layer, missing the second layer above. ''6'' is the count of faces on a cube, not unit cubes inside. ''12'' is the count of edges on a cube, also not the unit count. The volume formula resolves directly to 8.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A structure has a base layer of 3×3 cubes (9 cubes) and a top layer of only the four corner positions of that 3×3 grid (4 cubes at the corners). How many total cubes are in the structure?', '["9","11","13","16"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Bottom layer is 3 by 3 = 9 cubes. Top layer has only the four corner positions = 4 cubes. Total = 9 + 4 = 13. ''9'' counts only the bottom and forgets the corners on top. ''11'' miscounts the corner additions (perhaps using 2 instead of 4). ''16'' would result from a fully filled second layer (also 3 by 3), but the problem specifies only the corners.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A 3×3×3 large cube is assembled from unit cubes. How many unit cubes have exactly two painted faces if only the outside surface of the large cube is painted?', '["8","12","16","24"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unit cubes with exactly 2 painted faces sit on the edges of the large cube but not at the corners. A 3×3×3 cube has 12 edges, each with 1 non-corner edge cube. So: 12 × 1 = 12 edge cubes have exactly 2 painted faces.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'Looking at a structure from directly above, you see a 3×3 grid with a hole in the center (the center position is empty). All visible squares are exactly 1 cube tall. How many total unit cubes are in the structure?', '["7","8","9","12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The 3 by 3 footprint has 9 positions. The center position is empty, so 9 minus 1 = 8 cubes remain. Each cube is 1 unit tall, so there is no additional vertical multiplication. ''7'' undercounts by 1, perhaps removing two positions instead of one. ''9'' ignores the hole. ''12'' overcounts, possibly by treating the structure as having a second layer.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'A 3×3×3 large cube is built from unit cubes. All six outer faces are painted red. How many unit cubes have exactly three painted faces?', '["4","6","8","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Three-face cubes sit at the corners of the large painted cube, since each corner sits at the intersection of three outer faces. Any cube has exactly 8 corners, so 8 unit cubes have three painted faces, regardless of the cube''s overall size (as long as it is at least 2 units per side). ''4'' confuses corners with face count of a tetrahedron or a different solid. ''6'' is the count of face centers (one-face cubes). ''12'' is the count of edges (two-face cubes for a 3 by 3 by 3 cube).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'A 5×5×5 large cube is assembled from unit cubes. How many unit cubes are completely hidden (touch no outer face)?', '["9","16","27","64"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Peel off the painted outer shell, one cube thick, on every side. The hidden interior of a 5 by 5 by 5 cube measures (5 minus 2) cubed = 3 cubed = 27 unit cubes. ''9'' uses 3 squared instead of 3 cubed, dropping a dimension. ''16'' uses 4 squared, mixing up the formula. ''64'' uses 4 cubed, which is the surface cube count rather than the hidden interior. The (n minus 2) cubed rule applies to any cube with n at least 3.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'A 4×4×4 large cube is built from unit cubes and all six outer faces are painted. How many unit cubes have exactly one painted face?', '["16","24","36","48"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unit cubes with exactly one painted face are in the center of each face (not on any edge). Each face of a 4×4×4 cube has (4−2)² = 4 such cubes. Six faces × 4 = 24 cubes with exactly one painted face.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'A tower is built: bottom layer is 4×4 (16 cubes), next layer is 3×3 (9 cubes) centered on the first, next is 2×2 (4 cubes), then 1×1 (1 cube). How many unit cubes are in the tower?', '["25","28","30","32"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the cubes per layer: 16 + 9 + 4 + 1 = 30. The pyramid follows the sequence of perfect squares from 1 to n squared, summed: in this case 4 squared plus 3 squared plus 2 squared plus 1 squared. ''25'' uses only 16 + 9, omitting the upper two layers. ''28'' undercounts by 2. ''32'' overcounts, possibly adding an extra layer. The straightforward sum of squares from 1 to 4 gives 30.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'A 3×3×3 cube has all six faces painted blue. It is then cut into 27 unit cubes. How many unit cubes have NO painted faces at all?', '["0","1","6","8"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Zero-paint cubes have no exposed face. For a 3 by 3 by 3 cube, peel off the outer shell on every side: the hidden interior is (3 minus 2) cubed = 1 cubed = 1 unit cube, the single cube at the very center. ''0'' would be correct only for cubes 2 by 2 by 2 or smaller, where every unit cube touches an outer face. ''6'' is the count of face-center cubes (one-face cubes), each of which has one painted side. ''8'' is the corner count (three-face cubes).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'An L-shaped structure is built on a table: one arm is 4 cubes long, 1 cube wide, and 1 cube tall. The other arm is 3 cubes long, 1 cube wide, and 2 cubes tall. The two arms share 1 corner cube. How many total cubes are in the structure?', '["9","10","11","13"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Count each arm separately, then subtract the shared cube to avoid double-counting. Arm 1 has 4 times 1 times 1 = 4 cubes. Arm 2 has 3 times 1 times 2 = 6 cubes. The two arms share 1 corner cube at their junction. Total = 4 + 6 minus 1 = 9. ''10'' forgets to subtract the shared cube. ''11'' overcounts further. ''13'' adds two extra cubes, possibly from miscounting arm 2. The inclusion-exclusion adjustment (subtract the overlap) is essential.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'A 4×4×4 large cube is built from unit cubes and all six outer faces are painted. How many unit cubes have exactly two painted faces?', '["12","24","36","48"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unit cubes with exactly two painted faces lie on the edges of the large cube but not at corners. A cube has 12 edges; each edge of a 4×4×4 cube has (4−2) = 2 non-corner cubes. Total: 12 × 2 = 24 cubes with exactly two painted faces.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-14', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'From the front, a structure appears as: 3 cubes across on the bottom row, 2 cubes in the middle row (centered), 1 cube on top (centered). Each stack is 1 cube deep. How many total cubes are in this pyramid viewed from the side?', '["4","5","6","9"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the rows: 3 + 2 + 1 = 6 cubes. Each row is 1 cube deep, so the depth dimension does not multiply the count. ''4'' undercounts by 2, perhaps missing rows. ''5'' undercounts by 1. ''9'' would result from a 3 by 3 grid in every row instead of a stepped pyramid. The triangular pattern n + (n-1) + ... + 1 gives 6 for n = 3.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-1', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, 'A contractor charges a flat fee of $120 plus $45 per hour. A second contractor charges $60 per hour with no flat fee. For what number of hours will both contractors charge the same total amount?', '["4 hours","6 hours","8 hours","10 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set 120 + 45h = 60h, so 120 = 15h and h = 8 hours, where the per-hour gap of $15 closes the $120 flat fee. Choice 4 hours divides $120 by $30, mixing the rate difference with the wrong spread. Choice 6 hours divides $120 by $20, miscomputing the per-hour differential. Choice 10 hours divides $120 by $12, treating the gap as smaller than the actual $15 per hour.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-2', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 5, 'A gear with 18 teeth meshes with a gear with 45 teeth. If the smaller gear rotates at 250 rpm, how fast does the larger gear rotate?', '["80 rpm","100 rpm","125 rpm","150 rpm"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Speeds are inversely proportional to teeth, so larger gear rpm = 250 × (18/45) = 250 × 0.4 = 100 rpm. Choice 80 rpm uses about 18/56, miscounting the larger gear''s teeth. Choice 125 rpm halves the input speed, treating the ratio as 1:2 instead of 18:45. Choice 150 rpm multiplies by 18/30, undercounting the larger gear''s tooth count by 15 teeth.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-3', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 5, 'A soldier''s test score was reduced by 12% due to a grading error. After the error was corrected, the score was increased by 20% of the reduced score. The original score was 250. What is the final corrected score?', '["250.0","264.0","247.2","270.0"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Reduced = 250 × 0.88 = 220, then final = 220 × 1.20 = 264. Choice 250.0 assumes −12% then +20% nets back to the original because the rates cancel, but each percentage applies to a different base. Choice 247.2 multiplies 220 × 1.12, using a 12% increase instead of 20%. Choice 270.0 applies the 20% increase to the original 250 (giving 300) minus the 12% reduction, mixing the order of operations.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-4', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'Two soldiers start at the same point and walk in the same direction. Soldier A walks at 4 mph; Soldier B walks at 6 mph. Soldier B starts 30 minutes after Soldier A. How long after B starts does B catch up with A?', '["45 minutes","1 hour","1 hour 15 minutes","1 hour 30 minutes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A''s head start = 4 × 0.5 = 2 miles, closing rate = 6 − 4 = 2 mph, so catch-up time = 2 ÷ 2 = 1 hour after B starts. Choice 45 minutes uses a 3 mph closing rate, adding instead of subtracting somewhere in the setup. Choice 1 hour 15 minutes uses a slower closing rate near 1.6 mph. Choice 1 hour 30 minutes reports the head-start time (30 min) plus another hour, mixing the two clocks.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-5', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 5, 'A barrel holds 84 gallons. A pump fills it at 7 gallons per minute, but a leak drains it at 1.75 gallons per minute. Starting empty, how many minutes does it take to fill the barrel?', '["12 minutes","14 minutes","16 minutes","18 minutes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Net fill rate = 7 − 1.75 = 5.25 gal/min, so time = 84 ÷ 5.25 = 16 minutes. Choice 12 minutes divides 84 by 7, ignoring the leak entirely. Choice 14 minutes uses about 6 gal/min net, rounding the leak down to 1 gal/min. Choice 18 minutes uses a net rate near 4.67 gal/min, rounding the leak up to about 2.33 and inflating its effect.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-6', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, 'Three workers can paint a room in 6 hours. Two of the workers leave after 2 hours. The remaining worker finishes alone. How many total hours does the job take?', '["12 hours","14 hours","16 hours","18 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total job = 3 × 6 = 18 worker-hours. In the first 2 hours, 3 workers complete 6 worker-hours, leaving 12. One worker alone needs 12 hours for the remainder, so total elapsed time = 2 + 12 = 14 hours. Choice 12 hours forgets the first 2 hours of work and reports just the solo finish. Choice 16 hours uses 14 wh remaining, miscounting the work done in the first phase. Choice 18 hours reports the full worker-hours total.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-7', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'A boat travels 48 miles upstream in 4 hours and the same distance downstream in 3 hours. What is the speed of the current?', '["2 mph","3 mph","4 mph","5 mph"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Upstream speed = 48/4 = 12 mph (boat − current); downstream = 48/3 = 16 mph (boat + current); current = (16 − 12) / 2 = 2 mph. Choice 3 mph averages the trip times incorrectly. Choice 4 mph uses the full 16 − 12 = 4 spread without halving it, the most common upstream/downstream trap. Choice 5 mph splits 14 mph and rounds the boat-in-still-water speed up to a friendlier 15.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-8', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 5, 'If 5 machines produce 300 widgets in 4 hours, how many machines are needed to produce 540 widgets in 3 hours?', '["9","10","12","15"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Per-machine rate = 300 / (5 × 4) = 15 widgets per machine-hour; in 3 hours, one machine makes 45 widgets, so machines needed = 540 ÷ 45 = 12. Choice 9 uses 540/60, treating per-machine output as 60 widgets/hr (mixing the time and output). Choice 10 uses 540 / (5 × 11), miscomputing the per-machine 3-hour output. Choice 15 scales 540/300 = 1.8 and multiplies by 5, ignoring the time change from 4 hours to 3 hours.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-2', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 5, 'INVETERATE most nearly means:', '["Recently reformed","Deeply experienced","Long-established and unlikely to change","Violently opposed"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Inveterate means firmly established by long habit, as in ''an inveterate smoker who has lit up daily for forty years.'' From Latin inveteratus, made old. Recently reformed is the direct antonym, naming change from a long habit. Deeply experienced is the most dangerous false friend: experienced people have done something for a long time, but inveterate emphasizes that the habit is ingrained and unlikely to change, while experienced is neutral about flexibility. Violently opposed is a register trap drawing on the harsh sound, but inveterate is about permanence, not hostility. Only Long-established and unlikely to change fits.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-3', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 5, 'In the sentence ''The diplomat''s ANODYNE speech avoided any statement that might offend either side, leaving the audience with nothing to applaud or protest,'' the word ANODYNE most nearly means:', '["Highly persuasive","Inoffensive to the point of being dull","Deeply critical of both parties","Remarkably brief"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A speech that left ''nothing to applaud or protest'' pins the meaning to deliberate avoidance of any reaction. Anodyne specifically labels content drained of anything that could offend or excite. ''Highly persuasive'' is the opposite of evoking no response. ''Deeply critical of both parties'' would have produced protest, ruling it out. ''Remarkably brief'' addresses length, which the sentence never raises. Only Inoffensive to the point of being dull matches the deliberate blandness the clue describes, including the negative connotation of dullness.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-4', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 5, 'The word PUSILLANIMOUS contains the Latin root ANIM (spirit/soul) and the prefix PUSILL- (very small). PUSILLANIMOUS most nearly means:', '["Extremely generous of spirit","Showing a lack of courage; cowardly","Spiritually enlightened","Overly animated or energetic"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PUSILLANIMOUS breaks down as PUSILL- (very small, from Latin pusillus) plus ANIM- (spirit, soul) plus -OUS (adjective-forming), literally ''small-souled.'' A small spirit shrinks from danger, so the word means cowardly. ''Extremely generous of spirit'' is the direct opposite (that would be magnanimous, great-souled). ''Spiritually enlightened'' reads ANIM- correctly but misses PUSILL-, treating ''small'' as humility rather than deficiency. ''Overly animated or energetic'' confuses ANIM- (soul) with animated (lively), a common error since animation and animal share the same root in surface meaning only. Only Showing a lack of courage fits.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-5', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 5, 'The root PATER (father) appears in PATERNALISTIC. A PATERNALISTIC policy is one that:', '["Grants full autonomy to individuals","Restricts freedom supposedly for people''s own good, like a father deciding for a child","Applies equally to all family members","Traces authority through the maternal line"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The root PATER comes from Latin meaning father. Cognates include paternal (fatherly), patriarch (a father-ruler), patron (a protector who acts like a father), paternity (fatherhood), and expatriate (one who has left the fatherland). A paternalistic policy treats adults like children under a father''s authority, restricting choices supposedly for their good. ''Grants full autonomy'' is the opposite. ''Applies equally to all family members'' confuses PATER with FAMIL- (family), which is broader. ''Traces authority through the maternal line'' would require MATER- (mother), the opposite root. Only Restricts freedom supposedly for people''s own good fits PATER plus the over-control connotation.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-6', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 5, 'SANGUINE most nearly means:', '["Pessimistic about the future","Optimistic and positive","Relating to blood or violence","Slow and deliberate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sanguine means optimistic, especially in a difficult situation. Although it derives from the Latin word for blood (a sanguine complexion was historically linked to a cheerful temperament), in modern usage it consistently means having a positive outlook. ''Relating to blood'' is the etymological trap.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-1', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'Passage: ''The town council voted unanimously to fund the new water treatment plant, citing both aging infrastructure and rising contaminant levels. However, the project manager noted that costs had already exceeded projections by 40%, and the mayor quietly asked engineers to explore a scaled-back alternative.'' What can most reasonably be inferred from this passage?', '["The council regrets its decision to fund the project","The mayor supports the original project without reservation","Concerns about cost may lead to a modified or reduced project scope","Rising contaminant levels have been resolved by the council vote"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The mayor''s request to ''explore a scaled-back alternative'' combined with costs 40% over budget strongly implies the original plan may be modified. The council vote shows approval in principle, not necessarily for the original scope. Contaminants are not yet resolved — the plant is only approved, not built.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-2', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Passage: ''Proponents claim the new regulation will protect consumers, but a closer examination reveals that its provisions were drafted almost entirely by the industries it purports to regulate. The oversight committee, composed largely of former industry executives, approved it in a single closed session. Whether this constitutes governance or theater is left as an exercise for the reader.'' What is the author''s tone?', '["Optimistic and encouraging","Objective and purely informational","Sardonic and skeptical","Alarmed and urgent"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The phrase ''left as an exercise for the reader'' is an ironic rhetorical device implying the answer is obvious without stating it. Combined with ''theater'' and the point about industry drafting its own regulations, the tone is sardonic skepticism, not neutral reporting or alarm.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-3', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Passage: ''Urban heat islands form when dense concentrations of pavement, buildings, and human activity replace natural land cover. Cities can be up to 7°F warmer than surrounding rural areas. While tree-planting campaigns are popular, researchers find that highly reflective roof coatings — though less photogenic — reduce surface temperatures more efficiently per dollar invested. Policy makers who overlook this evidence in favor of visible green initiatives may be choosing optics over outcomes.'' What is the main idea?', '["Urban heat islands are caused primarily by industrial pollution","Tree-planting is the most cost-effective solution to urban overheating","Reflective roof coatings are more cost-efficient than tree planting at reducing urban heat, but are less politically appealing","Policy makers should avoid all green initiatives until more research is available"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage contrasts the popularity of tree planting with the superior cost-efficiency of reflective coatings, and explicitly criticizes policy makers who prioritize visible green projects. The main idea is that reflective roofs outperform trees economically but lose on optics.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-4', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'Passage: ''The permafrost beneath Siberian tundra holds an estimated 1.5 trillion tons of organic carbon — roughly twice the amount currently in the atmosphere. As average temperatures rise, permafrost thaws and the organic material decomposes, releasing carbon dioxide and methane. Methane is approximately 86 times more potent than CO₂ as a greenhouse gas over a 20-year period, though its atmospheric lifetime is shorter. Scientists warn this feedback loop could accelerate warming in ways that current climate models may underestimate.'' According to the passage, how much more potent is methane than CO₂ as a greenhouse gas over 20 years?', '["20 times","50 times","86 times","100 times"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage gives the figure directly: methane is "approximately 86 times more potent than CO₂ as a greenhouse gas over a 20-year period." Choice C matches that number. Choice A picks up the "20-year period" detail and recycles the 20 as the potency multiplier, which is the classic number-swap trap on detail-recall items. Choice B is a plausible-looking distractor that does not appear anywhere in the passage. Choice D rounds 86 up to a familiar round number that the text does not state. Only C reflects the figure the passage actually provides.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-5', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'Passage: ''The pharmaceutical company released its Phase 2 trial results, showing a 34% reduction in symptom severity versus placebo. Analysts noted, however, that the trial enrolled only 80 participants and excluded patients over 65 and those with common comorbidities. The FDA typically requires Phase 3 trials of 300–3,000 participants before approval.'' What can be most reasonably inferred?', '["The drug will likely receive FDA approval within one year","The Phase 2 results are fraudulent","The drug''s effectiveness in the broader population remains uncertain, and further trials are required","Excluding older patients proves the drug is ineffective for them"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage stacks three constraints: a small 80-person trial, exclusion of older and comorbid patients, and an FDA standard of "Phase 3 trials of 300–3,000 participants before approval." Together those facts point to uncertainty about the broader population and a clear next step. Choice C captures both. Choice A overreaches with a specific approval timeline the passage does not support. Choice B overreaches by leaping from limitations to fraud. Choice D overreaches in the opposite direction, treating exclusion (a study design choice) as proof of ineffectiveness. Only C stays within the evidence.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-6', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Passage: ''Advocates of universal basic income point to pilot programs in Finland and Kenya as proof of concept. Critics counter that these experiments are too small, too short, and too generously funded to scale globally. Both sides marshal the same limited data to opposite conclusions, a reminder that in policy debates, the evidence rarely speaks for itself.'' What is the author''s primary purpose?', '["To advocate for universal basic income","To discredit the critics of universal basic income","To highlight that the same evidence supports opposing conclusions, illustrating limits of policy data","To explain why pilot programs in Finland and Kenya succeeded"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The author lays out both sides, then states the takeaway: "in policy debates, the evidence rarely speaks for itself." That meta-point about contested evidence is the actual purpose. Choice C captures it. Choice A misreads the balanced framing as advocacy for one position. Choice B does the same in reverse. Choice D assumes the pilot programs succeeded, when the passage frames their value as contested rather than settled. The author is not picking a side or evaluating outcomes; the author is commenting on how the same data fuels opposite arguments.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-7', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Passage: ''Sleep deprivation does not merely cause fatigue. Research links chronic short sleep to increased risk of cardiovascular disease, metabolic disorders, and impaired immune response. Cognitive effects include reduced working memory, slower reaction time, and impaired judgment — the last of which may be the most dangerous because sleep-deprived individuals consistently underestimate their own impairment. A person who has slept 6 hours may feel alert while performing at the level of someone legally drunk.'' What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Six hours of sleep is sufficient for most adults","Sleep deprivation causes serious physical and cognitive harm, made worse by impaired self-awareness of that harm","Fatigue is the primary danger of insufficient sleep","Legal intoxication limits should apply to sleep-deprived drivers"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage opens by saying sleep deprivation "does not merely cause fatigue," then catalogs physical harms (cardiovascular, metabolic, immune), cognitive harms (memory, reaction time, judgment), and the self-concealing twist that sufferers underestimate their own impairment. Choice B blends all three pieces. Choice A contradicts the passage, which frames six hours as dangerously impaired. Choice C names the harm the author explicitly rejects as the main point. Choice D invents a policy prescription about legal intoxication limits that the passage never proposes. Only B captures the full structure of harms plus hidden impairment.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-1', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'A soldier has twice as many push-ups completed as sit-ups. If he does 12 more sit-ups, both totals will be equal. How many push-ups did he complete originally?', '["12","18","24","36"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let sit-ups = s and push-ups = 2s. After 12 more sit-ups: s + 12 = 2s, so s = 12. Original push-ups = 2(12) = 24. The choice 12 returns the sit-up count rather than the push-up count. The choice 18 comes from treating the relation as 2s = s + 6 (halving the 12) or splitting the difference. The choice 36 comes from using 3s instead of 2s for push-ups, treating "twice as many" as "three times as many."', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-2', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'A right triangle has legs of 5 cm and 12 cm. A square is constructed on the hypotenuse. What is the area of that square?', '["60 cm²","119 cm²","144 cm²","169 cm²"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Pythagorean theorem gives the hypotenuse: c = √(5² + 12²) = √(25 + 144) = √169 = 13 cm. The 5-12-13 triple shows up often. Square on the hypotenuse: 13² = 169 cm². The choice 60 cm² is the triangle''s area (1/2 × 5 × 12), not the square. The choice 119 cm² comes from c² = 144 − 25 (subtracting instead of adding the leg-squares). The choice 144 cm² squares only the longer leg (12²), forgetting the 5² contribution.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-3', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Simplify: (2x²y)³ ÷ (4x³y²)', '["2x³y","2x²y","x³y","2xy³"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Cube the numerator: (2x²y)³ = 2³ · x⁶ · y³ = 8x⁶y³. Divide by 4x³y²: 8/4 = 2, x^(6−3) = x³, y^(3−2) = y. Result: 2x³y. The choice 2x²y subtracts exponents before cubing the numerator. The choice x³y forgets to divide the coefficients (leaves 8/4 unsimplified or treats it as 1). The choice 2xy³ swaps the surviving x and y exponents, putting the cube on the wrong variable.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-4', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'A tank is 3/8 full. After adding 45 gallons it is 5/8 full. What is the total capacity of the tank?', '["120 gallons","150 gallons","180 gallons","210 gallons"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The 45 gallons raised the level from 3/8 to 5/8, a change of 2/8 = 1/4 of the tank. So 1/4 of capacity = 45 gallons, and capacity = 45 × 4 = 180 gallons. The choice 120 gallons comes from using 3/8 of capacity = 45 (the starting fraction, not the change). The choice 150 gallons comes from 45 ÷ 0.3 or another wrong fraction of capacity. The choice 210 gallons comes from adding the 45 gallons to the wrong base, or using 5/8 of capacity = 45.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-5', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 5, 'The sum of three consecutive odd integers is 111. What is the largest of the three integers?', '["35","37","39","41"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let the integers be n, n + 2, n + 4. Sum: 3n + 6 = 111, so 3n = 105 and n = 35. Largest = n + 4 = 39. Check: 35 + 37 + 39 = 111. The choice 35 returns the smallest of the three. The choice 37 returns the middle integer. The choice 41 comes from using n + 6 as the largest (treating four integers instead of three).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-6', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'If 2/3 of a number equals 4/5 of another number, and the first number is 60, what is the second number?', '["40","48","50","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Compute 2/3 of the first number: 2/3 × 60 = 40. Set 4/5 of the second number equal to 40: (4/5)n = 40, so n = 40 × 5/4 = 50. The choice 40 returns the shared value, stopping one step too early. The choice 48 comes from multiplying 40 by 6/5 instead of 5/4. The choice 72 comes from multiplying 60 by 6/5 (using the wrong fraction relationship entirely).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-7', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'A rectangular room is 15 feet long and 10 feet wide. A diagonal brace runs from one corner to the opposite corner. What is the length of the brace, to the nearest whole foot?', '["16 feet","17 feet","18 feet","19 feet"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The diagonal of a rectangle uses the Pythagorean theorem on the length and width. d = √(15² + 10²) = √(225 + 100) = √325 ≈ 18.03 feet, which rounds to 18 feet. The choice 16 feet comes from √(225 + 25) or another arithmetic slip. The choice 17 feet comes from √289 = 17, using 15² + 8² by misreading the width. The choice 19 feet comes from √(225 + 144) and a width-misread to 12.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A square sheet of paper has its four corners labeled A (top-left), B (top-right), C (bottom-right), and D (bottom-left). The sheet is folded by bringing corner B down to meet corner D (a diagonal fold along the line from A to C). Which shape does the folded paper form?', '["A smaller square","A right triangle with the right angle at corner A","A right triangle with vertices at A, the merged B-D point, and C","A rectangle"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Folding B onto D means the fold line is the perpendicular bisector of segment BD, which is the diagonal AC. Half of the square reflects across AC. Corners B and D merge to a single point, while A and C stay in place. The visible boundary has vertices at A, C, and the merged B-D point. ''A right triangle with the right angle at corner A'' misplaces the right angle: after folding, the right angle sits at the merged point, not at A. ''A smaller square'' would require a midline fold, not a diagonal one. ''A rectangle'' likewise requires a midline fold rather than a diagonal one.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-19', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 5, 'Six squares form a cube net in this arrangement: square 1 is in the top-left position. Square 2 is to the right of square 1. Square 6 is to the right of square 2. Square 3 is below square 2. Square 4 is to the right of square 3. Square 5 is above square 4 (same column as 4, sharing square 4''s top edge). When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square 1?', '["Square 4","Square 5","Square 6","Square 3"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Assign square 2 as the base. Square 1 (left of 2) folds up to become the left wall. Square 6 (right of 2) folds up to become the right wall. Square 3 (below 2) folds up to become the front wall. Square 4 (right of 3): when 3 is the front wall, square 4 is on 3''s right edge and folds to become the top. Square 5 (above 4): when 4 is the top, square 5 folds to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=2, top=4, left=1, right=6, front=3, back=5. Opposite left (1) = right (6) = choice c, index 2.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-20', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 5, 'A rectangular sheet (2 units wide, 4 units tall) is folded in half by bringing the top edge to the bottom edge (horizontal fold → 2×2 square). Then folded again bringing the top edge to the bottom edge (another horizontal fold → 2×1 rectangle, four layers). A hole is punched at the center of this 2×1 rectangle through all layers. When fully unfolded, how many holes appear and how are they arranged?', '["One hole in the center of the sheet","Two holes side by side across the middle of the sheet","Four holes in a vertical column at the sheet''s horizontal center","Four holes in a 2×2 grid"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The first fold (top to bottom) creates 2 layers stacked vertically. The second fold (top to bottom again) creates 4 layers stacked vertically. Each fold halves the vertical extent and doubles the layers along the vertical axis, leaving the horizontal axis untouched. Punching the center of the 4-layer rectangle puts 4 punch points along the vertical axis at the horizontal center when unfolded, each at a different vertical position spaced by the fold intervals. ''One hole'' covers only a single layer. ''Two holes side by side'' would require a vertical fold, not horizontal. ''Four holes in a 2 by 2 grid'' requires perpendicular folds rather than two parallel folds.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 5, 'A 5×5×5 large cube is painted on all outer faces and then cut into 125 unit cubes. How many unit cubes have exactly one painted face?', '["36","48","54","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Unit cubes with exactly one painted face sit at the center of each outer face (not on any edge). Each face of a 5×5×5 cube has (5−2)² = 9 such cubes. Six faces × 9 = 54 unit cubes with exactly one painted face.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-19', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 5, 'A hollow open-top box is built from unit cubes: outer dimensions are 4 wide × 4 deep × 3 tall, with walls and bottom exactly 1 unit thick and no top face. How many unit cubes make up this box?', '["28","36","40","48"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Build the count layer by layer. The bottom layer is a solid 4 by 4 = 16 cubes (the floor). Each of the 2 upper layers is the wall only: outer 4 by 4 = 16 positions minus the inner hollow 2 by 2 = 4 positions, leaving 12 wall cubes per upper layer. Two upper layers contribute 12 times 2 = 24. Total = 16 + 24 = 40. ''28'' undercounts, possibly with one upper layer only. ''36'' undercounts by 4, possibly missing the floor''s interior or one wall layer. ''48'' overcounts, possibly treating the upper layers as solid 4 by 4 = 16 each.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-20', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 5, 'A 4×4×4 large cube painted on all six outer faces is cut into 64 unit cubes. How many unit cubes have zero painted faces?', '["0","4","8","16"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Hidden interior cubes do not touch any outer face. The hidden core of a 4 by 4 by 4 cube measures (4 minus 2) cubed = 2 cubed = 8 unit cubes. ''0'' would apply only for cubes 2 by 2 by 2 or smaller. ''4'' undercounts the interior. ''16'' overcounts, possibly by squaring 4 (the surface count of one face) instead of cubing 2. The (n minus 2) cubed rule works for any cube with n at least 3.', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cube: top = silver, bottom = gold, front = red, back = blue, left = green, right = white. The cube is rotated 180° around the vertical axis (spinning a half-turn so the front face goes all the way to the back). What color is now facing you (front)?', '["Red","Blue","Green","White"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A 180 degree rotation around the vertical axis spins the cube halfway, so the original front swings all the way around to the back, and the original back rotates to the front. Top and bottom sit on the rotation axis and stay fixed. The original back (blue) becomes the new front. ''Red'' was the original front and is now on the back. ''Green'' and ''White'' are the left and right faces, which a vertical-axis rotation swaps with each other but does not move to the front (after a full 180 degree turn, left and right have also swapped, but neither ends up at the front).', true, 'trusted'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A warehouse stores 24 boxes. Each box holds 12 items. How many items are in the warehouse?', '["36","252","288","296"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the count of boxes by items per box: 24 x 12. Break it down: 24 x 10 = 240, then 24 x 2 = 48, and 240 + 48 = 288. Choice 36 adds 24 + 12 instead of multiplying. Choice 252 reflects a mis-carried digit in the 24 x 12 column (treating 2 x 24 as 28). Choice 296 adds 8 too many, likely from carrying twice. The correct total is 288 items.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A truck began the day with 156 packages. The driver delivered 89. How many packages remain on the truck?', '["57","67","77","245"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract delivered packages from the starting count: 156 - 89. Stack the numbers and borrow from the tens column: 16 - 9 = 7 in the ones place, then 14 - 8 = 6 after borrowing in the tens place, giving 67. Verify by adding back: 89 + 67 = 156. Choice 245 adds the two numbers, inverting the operation entirely. Choice 77 forgets to subtract 1 from the tens column after borrowing, leaving 5 instead of 4. Choice 57 reflects subtracting 99 instead of 89, a misread digit. The driver has 67 packages left on the truck.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A bakery splits 144 cookies evenly into 12 boxes. How many cookies go in each box?', '["11","12","13","132"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide total cookies by number of boxes to find the size of each share: 144 / 12. Recall the multiplication fact 12 x 12 = 144, so the quotient is 12. Verify by multiplying back: 12 cookies per box x 12 boxes = 144 cookies total, matching the starting number. Choice 132 subtracts 12 from 144, treating the problem as removal rather than even partition into groups. Choice 11 reflects an off-by-one slip, perhaps recalling 11 x 12 = 132. Choice 13 over-shoots, since 13 x 12 = 156, which exceeds the actual total. Each box contains exactly 12 cookies.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A clerk buys 6 notebooks at $3.25 each. What is the total cost?', '["$9.25","$18.50","$19.50","$19.75"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply quantity by unit price: 6 x $3.25. Split the price into whole dollars and cents to simplify. The dollar portion gives 6 x $3 = $18.00, and the cents portion gives 6 x $0.25 = $1.50. Add the parts: $18.00 + $1.50 = $19.50. Choice $9.25 adds 6 + 3.25, inverting the operation by using addition instead of multiplication. Choice $18.50 forgets the carry from the cents multiplication, treating 6 x $0.25 as $0.50 rather than $1.50. Choice $19.75 adds an extra quarter from a miscounted carry in the cents column. The total cost is $19.50.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A depot starts with 1,247 rounds. A shipment adds 968, and a training event uses 415. How many rounds remain?', '["1,690","1,800","2,215","2,630"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Work through the two operations in order: first add the shipment, then subtract the training expenditure. Step one: 1,247 + 968 = 2,215. Step two: 2,215 - 415 = 1,800. Choice 2,215 stops after the addition step, reporting the intermediate sum as the final answer without subtracting the training rounds. Choice 2,630 adds all three numbers together, ignoring that the training event removes rounds rather than adds them. Choice 1,690 reflects subtracting 525 instead of 415, a digit misread that swaps the 1 in the tens place for a 2. The depot has 1,800 rounds remaining.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A coach divides 84 athletes into 4 equal squads, then adds 15 reserves to one squad. How many athletes are in that enlarged squad?', '["21","27","36","51"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two operations are needed in a specific order: divide the athletes into equal squads first, then add reserves to the one enlarged squad. Step one: 84 / 4 = 21 athletes per squad. Step two: 21 + 15 = 36 athletes in the enlarged squad. Choice 21 reports the squad size before reserves arrive, stopping at the intermediate value and ignoring the second step. Choice 51 adds the reserves twice, computing 21 + 15 + 15 by double-counting the addition step. Choice 27 reflects a miscount in the addition step, perhaps adding 6 instead of 15. The enlarged squad has 36 athletes.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A field has 80 trees. A storm destroys 0.75 of them. How many trees were destroyed?', '["20","60","75","40"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Multiply the total count by the decimal fraction to find the affected portion: 0.75 x 80. Convert 0.75 into the equivalent fraction three-quarters, then take three-quarters of 80. One-quarter of 80 is 20, so three-quarters is 3 x 20 = 60. Verify with direct multiplication: 0.75 x 80 = 60. Choice 20 reports the trees that survived the storm (80 - 60), answering the opposite question from what was asked. Choice 75 treats 0.75 as a count of 75 trees directly, ignoring the multiplication. Choice 40 misreads 0.75 as one-half and computes 0.5 x 80. The storm destroyed 60 trees.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A shopper buys 3 pounds of beef at $4.80 per pound and 2 packs of buns at $3.25 each. She pays with a $30 bill. How much change does she receive?', '["$8.10","$9.10","$9.20","$20.90"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Three steps are required: compute each item subtotal, sum the subtotals to get the bill, then subtract from the amount tendered. Beef subtotal: 3 x $4.80 = $14.40. Bun subtotal: 2 x $3.25 = $6.50. Bill total: $14.40 + $6.50 = $20.90. Change owed: $30.00 - $20.90 = $9.10. Choice $20.90 reports the bill total itself, stopping at the intermediate value before the change calculation. Choice $9.20 reflects a ten-cent rounding error during the addition of subtotals. Choice $8.10 subtracts a miscomputed bill of $21.90. She receives $9.10 in change.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A driver travels at 60 miles per hour for 2 hours and 45 minutes. How many miles does he cover?', '["120","145","165","180"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert the minutes into a decimal fraction of an hour, then multiply by speed. 45 minutes equals 45/60 = 0.75 hour, so total time is 2.75 hours. Distance equals rate times time: 60 x 2.75 = 165 miles. Split the multiplication for clarity: 60 x 2 = 120, and 60 x 0.75 = 45, then 120 + 45 = 165. Choice 120 uses only the two whole hours, dropping the 45-minute portion. Choice 180 rounds the time up to 3 full hours before multiplying. Choice 145 treats 45 minutes as 0.45 hour, a unit-conversion error. The driver covers 165 miles.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A teacher needs 3 pencils for each of her 18 students. Pencils are sold only in boxes of 12. What is the minimum number of boxes she must buy?', '["4","5","6","54"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Three steps: find total pencils needed, divide by box size to get boxes, then round up because partial boxes cannot be purchased. Pencils needed: 18 students x 3 pencils each = 54 pencils. Boxes required: 54 / 12 = 4.5 boxes. Since stores sell only whole boxes, round up to 5 so the class has enough. Buying only 4 boxes provides 48 pencils, leaving the class 6 short. Choice 4 rounds down and leaves the class short. Choice 54 reports the total pencil count rather than the number of boxes. Choice 6 over-rounds by one box, buying more than necessary. She must buy 5 boxes.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A 5-gallon bucket of paint covers 1,750 square feet. How many gallons are needed to cover 4,200 square feet?', '["8","10","12","14"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up a unit-rate problem in two steps: find coverage per gallon, then divide the target area by that rate to find gallons needed. Coverage per gallon: 1,750 / 5 = 350 square feet per gallon. Gallons needed for 4,200 square feet: 4,200 / 350 = 12 gallons. Verify by multiplying back: 12 x 350 = 4,200, which matches the target area exactly. Choice 10 reflects dividing 4,200 by an incorrect per-gallon rate of 420. Choice 14 doubles the original five-gallon bucket without checking the proportion of areas. Choice 8 results from a miscomputed per-gallon rate near 525. The job requires 12 gallons of paint.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A worker earns $18 per hour for regular time and 1.5 times that for any hours over 40 in a week. She works 46 hours. What is her total pay?', '["$828","$882","$900","$1,242"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Split the 46 hours into regular and overtime portions, compute each pay segment, then add. Regular hours: 40 at $18 each = $720. Overtime hours: 46 - 40 = 6 hours. Overtime rate: 1.5 x $18 = $27 per hour. Overtime pay: 6 x $27 = $162. Total: $720 + $162 = $882. Choice $828 pays all 46 hours at the regular $18 rate (46 x $18 = $828), ignoring the overtime premium. Choice $1,242 applies the 1.5x multiplier to every hour worked rather than only hours above 40. Choice $900 rounds the overtime pay to a clean number. Her total pay is $882.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'A truck has a maximum load of 2,000 pounds. Equipment weighing 380 pounds is already on board. How many 45-pound crates can be added without exceeding the limit?', '["32","35","36","44"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two steps: find remaining weight capacity after the existing load, then divide by crate weight. Remaining capacity: 2,000 - 380 = 1,620 pounds available. Crates that fit: 1,620 / 45 = 36 exactly, with no remainder. Verify: 36 x 45 = 1,620, exactly filling the remaining capacity. Choice 44 divides the full 2,000 by 45, ignoring the 380 pounds of equipment already on board. Choice 35 rounds the answer down by one, even though 36 crates fit perfectly. Choice 32 reflects dividing by 50 instead of 45, a misread weight. The truck can carry 36 more crates.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'Two vehicles start 270 miles apart and drive toward each other. One travels at 55 mph and the other at 35 mph. How many hours until they meet?', '["2.7","3","4","5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When two objects move toward each other, the gap between them shrinks at a rate equal to the sum of their speeds. Add the speeds first, then divide the starting distance by that combined rate. Combined closing speed: 55 + 35 = 90 mph. Time to meet: 270 / 90 = 3 hours. Verify: in 3 hours the first car covers 55 x 3 = 165 miles and the second covers 35 x 3 = 105 miles, totaling 270. Choice 2.7 divides 270 by 100, a slipped digit. Choice 4 divides by the slower speed only. Choice 5 uses the faster speed alone. They meet in 3 hours.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-15', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'A tank holds 240 gallons when full. Water flows in at 8 gallons per minute while a drain removes 3 gallons per minute. Starting empty, how many minutes does it take to fill the tank?', '["30","48","53","80"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Two opposing rates are at work, so find the net fill rate, then divide tank volume by that rate. Net rate: 8 gallons in minus 3 gallons out = 5 gallons per minute of actual filling. Time to fill: 240 / 5 = 48 minutes. Verify: in 48 minutes, 8 x 48 = 384 gallons flow in while 3 x 48 = 144 drain out, leaving 240 in the tank, matching its capacity. Choice 30 uses only the 8-gallon inflow, ignoring the drain. Choice 80 uses only the drain rate, inverting the problem. Choice 53 reflects a miscomputed net rate near 4.5. The tank fills in 48 minutes.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-16', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A student earns scores of 78, 85, and 92 on three tests. After a fourth test, her average across all four is exactly 84. What did she score on the fourth test?', '["79","81","82","84"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use the average formula: total points equals average times count. Required total: 84 x 4 = 336. Sum of first three: 78 + 85 + 92 = 255. Fourth score: 336 - 255 = 81. Choice 84 assumes the fourth score must equal the average, which only holds when the prior scores already average to 84. Choice 82 reflects an arithmetic slip in summing 78 + 85 + 92 as 254. Choice 79 subtracts in the wrong direction. She scored 81.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-17', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'What is the sum of all whole numbers from 1 to 50, inclusive?', '["1,225","1,275","1,325","2,550"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use the arithmetic series formula: sum equals n times (n + 1) divided by 2, where n is the largest number. Here n = 50, so sum = 50 x 51 / 2 = 2,550 / 2 = 1,275. Choice 2,550 forgets to divide by 2, reporting n times (n + 1) directly. Choice 1,225 uses n = 49 by accident, summing 1 to 49. Choice 1,325 adds 50 to 1,275 a second time. The correct sum is 1,275.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'What is 25% of 60?', '["12","15","18","20"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent of an amount uses the formula (percent/100) x amount. Plug in: 0.25 x 60 = 15. Choice 12 comes from using 20% instead of 25%, reading the percent loosely. Choice 18 comes from using 30% instead of 25%, also a misread. Choice 20 results from dividing 60 by 3, which would be one-third, not one-quarter. Reading 25% as one-quarter is a useful shortcut: 60 divided by 4 equals 15. Either method, formula or fraction conversion, lands on 15 cleanly.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, '30 is what percent of 150?', '["15%","20%","25%","30%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent-of-total uses the formula (part/whole) x 100. Plug in: (30/150) x 100 = 20%. A quick check: 150 divided by 5 equals 30, so 30 is one-fifth of 150, and one-fifth is 20%. Choice 15% halves the part incorrectly. Choice 25% comes from dividing 30 by 120 instead of 150, a wrong-base error that ignores the stated total. Choice 30% mistakes the part value for the answer, ignoring that the question asks for a ratio. The whole always goes in the denominator.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'What is 15% of 80?', '["8","10","12","16"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Percent of an amount uses (percent/100) x amount. Plug in: 0.15 x 80 = 12. A fast method splits 15% into 10% plus 5%: 10% of 80 is 8, 5% of 80 is 4, and the sum is 12. Choice 8 stops at 10% and forgets the extra 5%. Choice 10 comes from rough rounding between the two pieces. Choice 16 doubles to 20% by mistake, treating 15% as if it were closer to one-fifth. The 10%-plus-5% trick handles most tip-style and sales-tax calculations quickly without a calculator.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'A recruit answered 18 questions correctly out of 20. What percent did the recruit get right?', '["80%","85%","90%","95%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Percent correct uses (correct/total) x 100. Plug in: (18/20) x 100 = 90%. Choice 80% comes from miscounting 4 missed instead of 2, since 16/20 = 80%, or from doubling the number wrong before converting. Choice 85% splits the difference without computing. Choice 95% comes from treating 1 missed question as 5% instead of 2 missed as 10%. The shortcut: each missed question out of 20 is worth 5 percentage points, so 2 missed equals 10 points off 100%.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A $50 shirt is on sale for 30% off. What is the sale price?', '["$15","$20","$30","$35"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Sale price after a percent discount uses original x (1 - discount). Plug in: 50 x 0.70 = $35. Choice $15 confuses percent off with percent paid: 30% of 50 is the discount amount, not the price paid. Choice $20 comes from subtracting 30 directly from 50, treating the percent as a dollar amount. Choice $30 comes from using 40% off instead of 30%. The customer always pays (100 - discount)% of the original, which here is 70% of $50.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A dinner bill is $80. With an 18% tip, what is the total amount paid?', '["$14.40","$80.18","$94.40","$98.00"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total with tip uses bill x (1 + tip rate). Plug in: 80 x 1.18 = $94.40. The tip alone is 0.18 x 80 = $14.40, which appears as choice $14.40 but represents only the tip, not the total. Choice $80.18 treats 18% as 18 cents, a decimal-place error. Choice $98.00 uses 22.5% rounding or adds $18 flat instead of 18%. The question asks for the total paid, so the tip must be added to the original bill.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A recruit increased pushup reps from 100 to 125. What is the percent increase?', '["20%","25%","30%","125%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent increase uses (new - old)/old x 100. Plug in: (125 - 100)/100 x 100 = 25 / 100 x 100 = 25%. Choice 20% uses the new value 125 as the denominator (25/125), a wrong-base error common in percent-change problems. Choice 30% comes from rough estimation between 25 and 33. Choice 125% treats the new total as the percent change instead of computing the change relative to the starting value. The original value always goes in the denominator for percent change, because the question asks how much the count grew compared with where it started.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A $200 item has an 8% sales tax. What is the total cost?', '["$208","$212","$216","$280"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total with tax uses price x (1 + tax rate). Plug in: 200 x 1.08 = $216. Tax alone is 0.08 x 200 = $16, then add to the price: 200 + 16 = $216. Choice $208 treats 8% as 8 dollars flat. Choice $212 uses 6% by mistake (0.06 x 200 = $12, plus $200 = $212). Choice $280 confuses 8% with 40% or treats tax as a much larger rate. A shortcut for 8% of a round number: take 10% and subtract one-fifth of it. 10% of 200 is 20, one-fifth of 20 is 4, so 8% is 16.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A practice score rose from 40 to 52. What is the percent increase?', '["12%","23%","30%","52%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Percent increase uses (new - old)/old x 100. Plug in: (52 - 40)/40 x 100 = 12/40 x 100 = 30%. Choice 23% divides by the new value 52 instead of the original 40, the classic wrong-base error. Choice 12% reports the raw point gain as a percent, ignoring the formula. Choice 52% mistakes the new score for the answer. The original value is always the denominator in percent change problems, because the question asks how much it grew relative to where it started.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A $500 loan charges 6% simple interest per year. How much interest accrues over 2 years?', '["$30","$50","$60","$66"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Simple interest uses I = principal x rate x time. Plug in: 500 x 0.06 x 2 = $60. Choice $30 forgets the time factor and computes only one year of interest. Choice $50 misreads the rate as 5% and computes 500 x 0.05 x 2 = $50. Choice $66 reflects compound interest applied incorrectly (500 x 1.06 x 1.06 minus 500 rounds near 61.80, then bumped). Simple interest never compounds: each year adds the same fixed dollar amount, calculated from the original principal only.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A mile time dropped from 8:00 minutes to 6:00 minutes. What is the percent decrease?', '["20%","25%","33%","75%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent decrease uses (old - new)/old x 100. Plug in: (8 - 6)/8 x 100 = 2/8 x 100 = 25%. Choice 20% comes from dividing by 10 or a similar wrong-base slip. Choice 33% divides by the new value 6 instead of the original 8, a wrong-base error that inflates the answer. Choice 75% reports the ratio of new to old (6/8) as if it were the decrease, confusing percent remaining with percent change. Faster runs mean a decrease in time, but the formula stays the same.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 4, 'A jacket costs $80. It is marked down 25%, then 8% sales tax is added to the sale price. What is the final price?', '["$60.00","$62.40","$64.80","$67.00"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Sequential percent changes apply one at a time. Step 1: 80 x 0.75 = $60 sale price. Step 2: 60 x 1.08 = $64.80 final. Choice $60.00 stops after the discount and forgets to add tax. Choice $62.40 applies tax to the original $80 instead of the discounted $60, then subtracts the discount, an order error. Choice $67.00 combines 25% off and 8% tax into a single 17% net change, but sequential percentages on different bases do not add directly. The base for tax is the sale price, not the sticker price.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 4, 'After a 20% discount, a backpack costs $48. What was the original price?', '["$57.60","$60.00","$68.00","$76.80"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Working backward from a discounted price uses original = sale/(1 - discount). Plug in: 48/0.80 = $60. Choice $57.60 multiplies $48 by 1.20, treating the discount as if it added back as a percent increase on the sale price, but 20% of $48 is not the same as 20% of the original. Choice $68 adds a flat $20 to the sale price. Choice $76.80 divides by 0.625 or applies the wrong adjustment. The sale price represents 80% of the original, so dividing by 0.80 recovers 100%.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 5, 'A stock rises 20% one month, then falls 20% the next month. What is the net percent change from the starting price?', '["0% (no change)","4% decrease","4% increase","20% decrease"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Chained percent changes apply to different bases. Start with 1.00, multiply by 1.20 for the rise: 1.20. Then multiply by 0.80 for the fall: 1.20 x 0.80 = 0.96, which is a 4% decrease from the start. Choice 0% adds the percentages directly (+20 - 20 = 0), the classic trap, but the 20% drop applies to a larger base than the 20% gain did. Choice 4% increase reverses the direction. Choice 20% decrease ignores the first rise entirely. Equal-percent up-then-down sequences always net to a small loss.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A car travels at a steady 55 mph for 4 hours. How far does it go?', '["13.75 miles","59 miles","220 miles","275 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 55 mph times 4 hours, which is 220 miles. The choice 13.75 reverses the operation and divides 55 by 4. The choice 59 adds rate and time instead of multiplying. The choice 275 uses 5 hours instead of 4, a common slip when rereading the problem. Always identify which quantity is missing and pick the matching form of the formula before plugging in numbers.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A cyclist rides 36 miles at 12 mph. How long does the ride take?', '["2 hours","3 hours","4 hours","24 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use T = D / R. Time equals 36 miles divided by 12 mph, which is 3 hours. The choice 2 divides 36 by 18 by mistake. The choice 4 divides 36 by 9, often from misreading the rate. The choice 24 multiplies distance by 2 instead of dividing, the classic operation-flip trap. When you want time, isolate it on one side of the formula first so the arithmetic step is clear.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A runner averages 8 mph for 2 hours. How far does she run?', '["4 miles","10 miles","16 miles","82 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 8 mph times 2 hours, which is 16 miles. The choice 4 divides 8 by 2, reversing the operation. The choice 10 adds the rate and time. The choice 82 concatenates the digits, a sign of skipping the formula entirely. Even with friendly numbers, write D = R x T before computing so the operation is locked in.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A train moves at 75 mph for 6 hours. How many miles does it cover?', '["12.5 miles","81 miles","450 miles","475 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 75 mph times 6 hours, which is 450 miles. The choice 12.5 divides 75 by 6. The choice 81 adds the two numbers. The choice 475 comes from a multiplication slip where 75 x 6 is read as 75 x 6 + 25. Multiply column by column on scratch paper if the product is not automatic, and always pair the unit of the answer (miles) with the formula.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A car drives at 65 mph for 2.5 hours. How far does it travel?', '["26 miles","130 miles","162.5 miles","195 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 65 mph times 2.5 hours, which is 162.5 miles. Compute 65 x 2 = 130, then add half of 65, which is 32.5, for 162.5. The choice 26 divides 65 by 2.5. The choice 130 ignores the half hour. The choice 195 uses 3 hours instead of 2.5. With decimal time, split the hours into whole and fractional parts and multiply each before adding.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A bus drives at 40 mph for 45 minutes. How far does it go?', '["18 miles","30 miles","45 miles","1,800 miles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert minutes to hours first. 45 minutes equals 0.75 hour. Then D = R x T = 40 x 0.75 = 30 miles. The choice 18 uses 0.45 hour, a unit-conversion error treating minutes as a decimal. The choice 45 simply restates the time number with the wrong unit. The choice 1,800 multiplies 40 by 45 without converting minutes. Always convert mixed time units to hours before applying the formula.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A delivery van covers 240 miles at an average speed of 48 mph. How long does the trip take?', '["4 hours","5 hours","6 hours","192 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use T = D / R. Time equals 240 miles divided by 48 mph. 48 times 5 is 240, so the trip takes 5 hours. The choice 4 divides 240 by 60 by mistake. The choice 6 divides 240 by 40. The choice 192 subtracts 48 from 240, the wrong operation entirely. When the rate is close to a round number, test the round number first as a sanity check before doing long division.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A jogger runs for 1 hour 30 minutes at 22 mph on a bike-jog trail. How far does she go?', '["11 miles","23.5 miles","33 miles","44 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert 1 hour 30 minutes to 1.5 hours. Then D = R x T = 22 x 1.5 = 33 miles. Compute 22 x 1 = 22 and add half of 22, which is 11, for 33. The choice 11 reports only the half-hour portion. The choice 23.5 adds 22 and 1.5. The choice 44 uses 2 hours instead of 1.5. Mixed time formats are the most common error source, so always rewrite them as a single decimal or fraction of an hour first.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A truck covers 90 miles in 1.5 hours. What is its average speed?', '["45 mph","60 mph","75 mph","135 mph"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use R = D / T. Speed equals 90 miles divided by 1.5 hours, which is 60 mph. Multiply numerator and denominator by 2 to clear the decimal: 180 / 3 = 60. The choice 45 divides 90 by 2 instead of 1.5. The choice 75 splits the difference between 90 and 60 in a guessing pattern. The choice 135 multiplies 90 by 1.5 instead of dividing, the classic operation flip when solving for rate.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'A driver covers the first 120 miles at 60 mph and the next 180 miles at 45 mph. What is the average speed for the entire trip?', '["50 mph","52.5 mph","54 mph","55 mph"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Average speed equals total distance divided by total time, not the average of the two rates. Time for leg one is 120 / 60 = 2 hours. Time for leg two is 180 / 45 = 4 hours. Total distance is 300 miles in 6 hours, so the average is 50 mph. The choice 52.5 is the arithmetic mean of 60 and 45, the classic trap. The choices 54 and 55 weight the legs incorrectly. When segments differ in length and rate, always sum the actual times.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'Two cars leave the same point heading the same direction. Car A travels at 50 mph and Car B travels at 65 mph. How far apart are they after 3 hours?', '["15 miles","45 miles","150 miles","345 miles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Same direction, so use the rate difference. The gap grows at 65 - 50 = 15 mph. After 3 hours the gap is 15 x 3 = 45 miles. The choice 15 reports only the rate difference and forgets the time. The choice 150 uses the sum of the rates, which would apply only if the cars were heading opposite directions. The choice 345 adds the two distances they traveled. For chase problems, work with the difference of the rates from the start.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'A hiker walks 3 miles at 4 mph, then 5 miles at 5 mph. How long does the full hike take?', '["1 hour","1.5 hours","1.75 hours","2 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Compute each leg separately, then add. Leg one takes 3 / 4 = 0.75 hour. Leg two takes 5 / 5 = 1 hour. Total time is 0.75 + 1 = 1.75 hours. The choice 1 reports only the second leg. The choice 1.5 averages the two legs incorrectly. The choice 2 rounds 1.75 up to a tidier number. Resist the urge to average times or rates across legs of different lengths. Sum the actual minutes each piece takes.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 4, 'A car leaves a rest stop at 60 mph. One hour later, a second car leaves the same rest stop on the same road at 75 mph. How far from the rest stop does the second car catch the first?', '["240 miles","270 miles","300 miles","375 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When the second car starts, the first car has a 60-mile head start. The closing speed is 75 - 60 = 15 mph. Catch-up time is 60 / 15 = 4 hours. Distance from the rest stop is 75 x 4 = 300 miles. The choice 240 uses the slower car''s distance at 4 hours, which is the same point but computed inconsistently in a way that often misfires. The choice 270 averages the two cars. The choice 375 uses 5 hours by mistake. Track who starts when and which rate is the gap closer.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 4, 'Two trains start 360 miles apart and head toward each other on parallel tracks. One travels at 55 mph and the other at 65 mph. How long until they meet?', '["2 hours","3 hours","3.6 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When two objects move toward each other, add the rates to get the closing speed. 55 + 65 = 120 mph. Time to meet is 360 / 120 = 3 hours. The choice 2 uses only one rate. The choice 3.6 divides 360 by 100, a common slip when adding rates carelessly. The choice 6 uses the difference of the rates instead of the sum, which applies to same-direction chase problems. Sum for converging motion, subtract for catch-up.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-15', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'A boat moves at 15 mph in still water. On a river with a 3 mph current, the boat travels 36 miles downstream and then 36 miles back upstream. How long does the round trip take?', '["4 hours","4.8 hours","5 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Downstream the current adds to the boat speed, so the effective rate is 15 + 3 = 18 mph. Upstream the current subtracts, giving 15 - 3 = 12 mph. Downstream time is 36 / 18 = 2 hours. Upstream time is 36 / 12 = 3 hours. Total is 5 hours. The choice 4 averages the two leg times. The choice 4.8 divides total distance 72 by 15, ignoring the current. The choice 6 divides 72 by 12, using only the slower leg''s rate. Compute each leg with its own effective rate.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-16', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'A plane flies 600 miles with a 40 mph tailwind, then returns the same 600 miles against a 40 mph headwind. Its airspeed in still air is 200 mph. What is the total flight time for the round trip?', '["5 hours","6 hours","6.25 hours","7.5 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ground speed outbound is 200 + 40 = 240 mph. Ground speed returning is 200 - 40 = 160 mph. Outbound time is 600 / 240 = 2.5 hours. Return time is 600 / 160 = 3.75 hours. Total is 6.25 hours. The choice 5 ignores the wind and uses 1,200 / 240. The choice 6 averages the two leg times. The choice 7.5 doubles 3.75, treating both legs as the slow leg. The arithmetic mean of two rates never gives the right round-trip time when distances are equal but rates differ.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'A pancake recipe uses flour and sugar in a 2:1 ratio. If a baker uses 4 cups of flour, how much sugar is needed?', '["2 cups","3 cups","6 cups","8 cups"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Set up the proportion flour/sugar = 2/1 = 4/x. Cross-multiply: 2x = 4, so x = 2 cups. The choice 8 cups multiplies 4 by 2 instead of dividing, treating flour as the smaller part. The choice 6 cups adds the parts (4 + 2) instead of scaling. The choice 3 cups subtracts 1 from 4 instead of applying the ratio. Sugar is the smaller quantity here, so it must be less than the flour amount.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'Concrete is mixed with cement and sand in a 1:3 ratio. If 5 bags of cement are used, how many bags of sand are needed?', '["8","12","15","20"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up cement/sand = 1/3 = 5/x. Cross-multiply: x = 15 bags. The choice 8 adds the parts (5 + 3) instead of scaling. The choice 20 multiplies 5 by 4 (the total ratio parts) instead of by 3. The choice 12 subtracts 3 from a wrong total. Sand needs three times the cement, so each cement bag pairs with three sand bags, giving 5 times 3.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'In a classroom the ratio of boys to girls is 3:4. If there are 9 boys, how many girls are in the class?', '["10","12","13","16"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Set up boys/girls = 3/4 = 9/x. Cross-multiply: 3x = 36, so x = 12 girls. The choice 13 adds 4 to 9 instead of scaling proportionally. The choice 16 applies the scale factor 4 to the wrong number (4 times 4). The choice 10 mixes addition and the ratio incorrectly. Scaling the 3 up to 9 means multiplying by 3, so the 4 also scales by 3 to reach 12.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'A paint mix uses red and white in a 1:2 ratio. If 3 quarts of red are used, how much white is needed?', '["1.5 quarts","5 quarts","6 quarts","9 quarts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up red/white = 1/2 = 3/x. Cross-multiply: x = 6 quarts. The choice 1.5 quarts flips the ratio and divides instead of multiplying. The choice 5 quarts adds the parts (3 + 2) instead of scaling. The choice 9 quarts multiplies 3 by 3 (the total parts) instead of by 2. White is twice the red, so 3 quarts of red pairs with 6 quarts of white.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'On a map, 1 inch represents 25 miles. Two towns are 6.5 inches apart on the map. How far apart are they in reality?', '["31.5 miles","150 miles","162.5 miles","175 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up inches/miles = 1/25 = 6.5/x. Cross-multiply: x = 162.5 miles. The choice 31.5 adds 25 and 6.5 instead of multiplying. The choice 150 drops the 0.5 inch from the calculation. The choice 175 rounds 6.5 up to 7 before multiplying. Each inch on the map equals 25 actual miles, so 6.5 inches scales directly to 6.5 times 25.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'A cookie recipe uses 3 cups of flour to make 8 cookies. How many cups of flour are needed to make 60 cookies?', '["20 cups","22.5 cups","24 cups","65 cups"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Set up flour/cookies = 3/8 = x/60. Cross-multiply: 8x = 180, so x = 22.5 cups. The choice 20 cups multiplies 60 by 1/3 instead of 3/8. The choice 24 cups uses the wrong ratio of 60 divided by something close. The choice 65 cups adds 60 and 5 with no proportional logic. Each cookie needs 3/8 cup of flour, so 60 cookies need 60 times 3/8.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'A server tips at a rate of $4 for every $25 of bill. If the bill is $87.50, what tip should be left at this rate?', '["$12.50","$14.00","$17.50","$21.88"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Set up tip/bill = 4/25 = x/87.50. Cross-multiply: 25x = 350, so x = $14.00. The choice $12.50 applies a flat 1/7 ratio incorrectly. The choice $17.50 uses a 20 percent tip rate, not the 16 percent given. The choice $21.88 uses a 25 percent rate from confusing the 25 in the ratio. The given ratio is 4 out of 25, which is 16 percent, so 87.50 times 0.16 gives 14.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'On a map, 2 centimeters represents 15 kilometers. If two cities are 9 centimeters apart on the map, how far apart are they?', '["22 km","45 km","67.5 km","135 km"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up cm/km = 2/15 = 9/x. Cross-multiply: 2x = 135, so x = 67.5 km. The choice 135 km forgets to divide by 2 after multiplying 9 by 15. The choice 45 km uses 1 cm per 5 km, the wrong scale. The choice 22 km adds 15 and 9 minus 2. Each centimeter equals 7.5 km, so 9 centimeters equals 67.5 km.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'In a class the ratio of boys to girls is 3:5. If the class has 32 students total, how many are boys?', '["8","12","19","20"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The ratio 3:5 means 3 + 5 = 8 total parts. Boys are 3/8 of the total: 32 times 3/8 = 12 boys. The choice 19 treats the part-to-part ratio as part-to-whole, computing 32 times 3/5. The choice 20 makes the same error in the other direction (32 times 5/8). The choice 8 just reports the total parts. Always add the ratio parts before splitting a known total.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'Concrete is mixed with cement, sand, and gravel in a 1:2:4 ratio. A batch contains 35 cubic feet of concrete total. How much gravel is in the batch?', '["5 cubic feet","10 cubic feet","20 cubic feet","28 cubic feet"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the parts: 1 + 2 + 4 = 7 total parts. Gravel is 4/7 of the total: 35 times 4/7 = 20 cubic feet. The choice 28 cubic feet treats 4/5 as the gravel share, forgetting to include cement in the sum. The choice 10 cubic feet uses 4/14, dividing by twice the correct total. The choice 5 cubic feet divides 35 by 7 without scaling up. Add all three parts of the ratio before taking the gravel fraction.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'A paint blend uses red, yellow, and blue in a 4:3:2 ratio. If the blend contains 18 ounces of blue, how many ounces is the entire blend?', '["54 oz","63 oz","72 oz","81 oz"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Blue is 2 parts. Each part equals 18 divided by 2, or 9 ounces. Add the parts: 4 + 3 + 2 = 9 total parts. Total blend = 9 parts times 9 ounces = 81 ounces. The choice 54 oz multiplies 18 by 3, treating yellow''s ratio number as the scale factor. The choice 72 oz uses 8 parts, forgetting blue itself. The choice 63 oz uses 7 parts, dropping blue. Find the per-part value first, then multiply by total parts.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 4, 'A bag contains red, blue, and green marbles in a 2:3:5 ratio. The bag has 24 red marbles. How many green marbles are in the bag?', '["36","48","60","96"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Red is 2 parts and equals 24 marbles, so each part equals 12 marbles. Green is 5 parts: 5 times 12 = 60 green marbles. The choice 36 multiplies 12 by 3, giving the blue count instead of green. The choice 48 treats green as 4 parts (12 times 4) by miscounting the ratio. The choice 96 reports blue plus green combined (3 + 5 = 8 parts at 12 each), answering for the non-red total rather than green alone. Find the value of one part by dividing the known quantity by its ratio number, then multiply by the target ratio number.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 4, 'A salad dressing mixes oil, vinegar, and water in a 1:2:5 ratio. If the recipe uses 30 ounces of water, how many ounces of dressing does it make total?', '["36 oz","42 oz","48 oz","75 oz"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Water is 5 parts and equals 30 ounces, so each part equals 6 ounces. Add the parts: 1 + 2 + 5 = 8 total parts. Total dressing = 8 times 6 = 48 ounces. The choice 36 oz misadds the ratio as 1 + 2 + 3 = 6 total parts and multiplies 6 by 6. The choice 42 oz uses 7 parts, dropping one of the smaller components. The choice 75 oz multiplies 30 by 2.5, treating the ratio additively. Find the per-part value, add all parts, then multiply.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'Six workers can paint a house in 10 days. Working at the same rate, how many days will 4 workers need to paint the same house?', '["6.67 days","8 days","12 days","15 days"]'::jsonb, 3, 'This is inverse proportion: fewer workers means more days. Total work equals 6 times 10 = 60 worker-days. With 4 workers, days = 60 divided by 4 = 15 days. The choice 6.67 days applies direct proportion (10 times 4/6), shrinking the time as workers shrink. The choice 12 days subtracts 2 workers and adds 2 days. The choice 8 days reduces time even more, the opposite of what should happen. When one quantity decreases, the other increases by the inverse factor.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A paperback book costs $12. How much do 5 of these books cost?', '["$17","$55","$60","$65"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the unit price by the quantity: 12 x 5 = 60, so 5 books cost $60. Choice $17 adds 12 and 5 instead of multiplying, a slip that happens when small numbers nudge the brain toward addition. Choice $55 misreads the price as $11 and computes 11 x 5, or drops a dollar when carrying. Choice $65 adds an extra $5, a common slip from rounding 12 up to 13 before multiplying. The structure is a single-step unit-cost problem, and the only operation needed is one multiplication.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A teacher splits 24 students into 4 equal groups. How many students are in each group?', '["5","6","8","20"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide the total by the number of groups: 24 / 4 = 6 students per group. Choice A comes from dividing 24 by 5 by accident, then rounding to a nearby whole number. Choice C results from dividing 24 by 3, a common error when a student confuses the number of groups with the number of dividers needed between groups. Choice D comes from subtracting 4 from 24 instead of dividing, a misread of the cue phrase ''split into.'' One operation, equal-share division, is all this question asks for, and the keyword ''equal groups'' is the signal to divide.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A train travels at a constant 60 miles per hour. How far does it travel in 3 hours?', '["20 miles","63 miles","120 miles","180 miles"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Distance equals rate times time: 60 x 3 = 180 miles. Choice A inverts the formula and divides 60 by 3 instead of multiplying, which would give a speed-per-hour fraction rather than a distance. Choice B adds 60 and 3 instead of multiplying, a classic operator swap when the rate and time numbers look small. Choice C uses 2 hours instead of 3, an off-by-one read on the time value. Distance-rate-time is one of the most common word-problem setups, and at this difficulty only a single product is required to reach the answer.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A bakery starts the day with 48 muffins. By noon, 19 muffins have been sold. How many muffins remain?', '["29","31","39","67"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract the amount sold from the starting count: 48 - 19 = 29 muffins remain. Choice B comes from subtracting 17 instead of 19, a digit misread on the ones place. Choice C results from subtracting only the 9 in 19 and ignoring the tens digit, leaving 39 muffins. Choice D adds the two numbers instead of subtracting, which is the operator-flip trap when the word ''sold'' is glossed over and the stem is read as a combine-totals problem. A single subtraction handles the whole problem, and careful alignment of place values prevents the digit-slip distractors.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A shirt is marked $25, and a store offers 20% off. What is the sale price?', '["$5","$20","$24.50","$30"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find 20% of $25 (which is $5), then subtract from the original: 25 - 5 = $20. Choice A reports only the discount amount and forgets to subtract from the price, a stopping-too-early mistake. Choice C treats 20% as 2%, taking $0.50 off instead of $5, a decimal-place slip. Choice D adds the discount to the price rather than subtracting it, the operator-flip error when the cue word ''off'' is missed. Percent-off problems are two-step: compute the discount amount, then apply it in the correct direction to reach the sale price.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'Marcus earns $14 per hour. He works 6 hours on Monday and 4 hours on Tuesday. How much does he earn in total for both days?', '["$56","$84","$140","$1,400"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the hours first, then multiply by the rate: 6 + 4 = 10 hours, and 10 x 14 = $140. Choice A multiplies only Tuesday''s 4 hours by 14, dropping Monday entirely. Choice B multiplies only Monday''s 6 hours by 14, dropping Tuesday entirely. Choice D misplaces the decimal, sliding a zero so the hourly rate is treated as $140 instead of $14, a place-value slip. Two-day pay problems need both days summed before the wage rate is applied, and the order of operations matters when the same wage covers both shifts.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'Three pizzas are each cut into 8 slices. If 4 friends share all the slices equally, how many slices does each friend get?', '["3","6","8","12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find the total slices first: 3 x 8 = 24, then divide among 4 people: 24 / 4 = 6 slices each. Choice A divides 12 by 4, using only one pizza. Choice C reports the slices per pizza, skipping the share step. Choice D divides 24 by 2 instead of 4, halving the friends. The two operations have to happen in order, multiply then divide, and missing either step lands on a wrong choice.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A car travels 240 miles using 8 gallons of gas. What is the car''s mileage in miles per gallon?', '["30 mpg","32 mpg","248 mpg","1,920 mpg"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Miles per gallon equals miles divided by gallons: 240 / 8 = 30 mpg. Choice B comes from dividing 256 by 8, a digit slip that reads the miles value wrong. Choice C adds 240 and 8 instead of dividing, an operator-swap error that ignores the per-unit cue in the question. Choice D multiplies 240 by 8, which would give total miles if you drove 8 full tanks, not a rate per gallon. The phrase ''per gallon'' signals division, with miles as the numerator and gallons as the denominator, and getting the order right matters since flipping it produces gallons per mile.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A bag contains 60 marbles. One-fourth are red, one-third are blue, and the rest are green. How many marbles are green?', '["15","20","25","35"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Red: 60 x 1/4 = 15. Blue: 60 x 1/3 = 20. Green: 60 - 15 - 20 = 25. Choice A reports the red count only. Choice B reports the blue count only. Choice D adds the red and blue counts instead of subtracting them from 60, taking the wrong complement. Fraction-of-total problems often hide the answer in the last step, so the leftover quantity, not either named fraction, is what the stem asks for.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'Jordan saved $150. He spent 40% of his savings on a bike, then spent 25% of the remaining money on a helmet. How much money does Jordan have left?', '["$30.00","$52.50","$67.50","$90.00"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Bike cost: 150 x 0.40 = $60, leaving 150 - 60 = $90. Helmet: 90 x 0.25 = $22.50, leaving 90 - 22.50 = $67.50. Choice $30.00 subtracts the bike cost twice, computing 90 - 60 by mistake. Choice $52.50 adds the two percentages (65%) and takes that off $150 directly: 150 - 97.50 = $52.50. Choice $90.00 stops after the bike purchase and forgets the helmet. The key move is using the post-bike balance as the new base for the 25%.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'A pancake recipe uses 2 cups of flour to serve 4 people. How many cups of flour are needed to serve 10 people using the same recipe?', '["2.5 cups","4 cups","5 cups","8 cups"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up a proportion: 2 cups / 4 people = x / 10 people, so x = (2 x 10) / 4 = 5 cups. Choice A reverses the ratio and divides 10 by 4. Choice B doubles the recipe to serve 8 people instead of 10, an undershoot. Choice D multiplies 2 by 4 instead of by 10/4, applying the wrong scaling factor. Proportion problems require keeping the same quantity (flour or people) in the same position on both sides of the equation.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'A student''s five test scores are 78, 85, 92, 89, and 76. What is the average of these scores?', '["82","84","85","88"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the scores: 78 + 85 + 92 + 89 + 76 = 420. Divide by 5: 420 / 5 = 84. Choice A undercounts the sum by 10 (likely reading 78 as 68). Choice C reports the median (the middle score when sorted: 76, 78, 85, 89, 92) instead of the mean. Choice D divides 440 by 5, an addition error in the sum. Averages have two stages, and a single arithmetic slip in the sum is the most common way to miss this kind of item.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'A worker assembles 12 widgets in 45 minutes. Working at the same rate, how many widgets can the worker assemble in 3 hours?', '["32","36","48","60"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert 3 hours to 180 minutes, then scale: 180 / 45 = 4, and 4 x 12 = 48 widgets. Choice A multiplies 12 by 3 hours without converting units, treating hours and 45-minute blocks as equal. Choice B uses 135 minutes (2.25 hours) instead of 180. Choice D multiplies 12 by 5, assuming five 45-minute blocks fit in 3 hours rather than four. The unit conversion from hours to minutes (or to 45-minute blocks) is the trip-up step.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 4, 'Two trains leave the same station at the same time, traveling in opposite directions. One train moves at 55 mph and the other at 65 mph. After how many hours are the trains 360 miles apart?', '["1.5 hours","3 hours","4.5 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When objects move in opposite directions, their separation rate is the sum of their speeds: 55 + 65 = 120 mph. Time = distance / rate = 360 / 120 = 3 hours. Choice 1.5 hours doubles the combined rate to 240 mph (perhaps by also doubling each speed) and computes 360 / 240. Choice 4.5 hours misreads 65 as 25 (digit slip), uses 80 mph as the combined rate, and computes 360 / 80. Choice 6 hours averages the two speeds to get 60 mph instead of summing, then divides 360 / 60. The combined-rate setup is the load-bearing step.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-15', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 4, 'An inlet pipe can fill a tank in 6 hours. A drain pipe can empty the full tank in 9 hours. If both pipes are open and the tank starts empty, how long will it take to fill the tank?', '["3 hours","7.5 hours","15 hours","18 hours"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Add the rates with the drain as negative: 1/6 - 1/9 = 3/18 - 2/18 = 1/18 tank per hour. Time to fill one tank = 18 hours. Choice A subtracts 6 from 9 and reports the difference. Choice B averages 6 and 9 to get 7.5, ignoring that the pipes work against each other. Choice C adds the two times (6 + 9) instead of combining rates. Work-rate problems require rates, not times, to be combined, with the sign matching whether each pipe fills or drains.', false, 'draft'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-16', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, '$1,000 is deposited in an account earning 5% interest compounded annually. How much interest is earned after 2 years?', '["$100.00","$102.50","$105.00","$110.25"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Compound balance after 2 years: 1000 x (1.05)^2 = 1000 x 1.1025 = $1,102.50. Interest earned is 1102.50 - 1000 = $102.50. Choice A applies simple interest (1000 x 0.05 x 2), missing the compounding bump. Choice C reports only the first year''s interest (1000 x 0.05). Choice D reports the multiplier 1.1025 scaled to $110.25, mistakenly using a $1,000 principal at 10.25% per year for one year, or forgetting to subtract the original principal from a slightly mis-scaled balance. Compound interest answers are always slightly above the simple-interest figure for the same period.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If x + 7 = 15, what is the value of x?', '["7","8","22","9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Isolate x by subtracting 7 from both sides: x + 7 - 7 = 15 - 7, which gives x = 8. Choice 22 is the sign-error trap that comes from adding 7 to 15 instead of subtracting. Choice 7 is the constant on the left side rather than the variable''s value. Choice 9 results from subtracting 6 instead of 7. The inverse operation of addition is subtraction, so a positive constant added to x must be subtracted to undo it.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If x - 9 = 4, what is x?', '["-5","5","13","36"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add 9 to both sides to isolate x: x - 9 + 9 = 4 + 9, which gives x = 13. Choice -5 is the sign-error trap from subtracting 9 from 4 instead of adding. Choice 5 reverses the direction by computing 9 - 4. Choice 36 comes from multiplying 9 and 4 instead of using inverse operations. Subtraction of a positive constant is undone by addition of that same constant on both sides.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If 6x = 42, what is x?', '["6","7","8","36"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide both sides by 6 to isolate x: 6x / 6 = 42 / 6, which gives x = 7. Choice 6 is the coefficient itself, not the solution value of the variable. Choice 8 results from a division error treating 42 as 48 in the head. Choice 36 comes from subtracting 6 from 42 instead of dividing, an inverted-operation trap. Multiplication of x by a coefficient is undone by dividing both sides by that coefficient, not by subtracting it from both sides.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If 4x + 3 = 19, what is x?', '["4","5.5","16","22"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 3 from both sides to clear the constant: 4x + 3 - 3 = 19 - 3, which gives 4x = 16. Then divide both sides by 4: x = 4. Choice 16 is the intermediate value of 4x reported instead of x. Choice 22 adds 3 to 19 instead of subtracting, a sign-error on transposition. Choice 5.5 comes from dividing 22 by 4 after that same transposition error. The order matters: undo addition first, then undo multiplication, because the coefficient binds tighter to the variable.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If 5x - 2 = 23, what is x?', '["4.2","5","21","25"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add 2 to both sides: 5x = 25. Then divide by 5: x = 5. Choice 25 is the intermediate value of 5x reported as the answer instead of x. Choice 21 comes from subtracting 2 from 23 instead of adding, a sign-error trap. Choice 4.2 results from dividing 21 by 5 after the same transposition error. A negative constant on the variable side must be added to both sides, then the coefficient must be divided out.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If x/3 + 4 = 9, what is x?', '["5","13","15","39"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Subtract 4 from both sides: x/3 = 5. Then multiply both sides by 3: x = 15. Choice 5 is the intermediate value of x/3 reported instead of x. Choice 13 comes from adding 4 to 9 instead of subtracting, a sign-error on transposition. Choice 39 results from multiplying 13 by 3 after the same transposition error. Division by a constant is undone by multiplying both sides by that constant after the addition is cleared.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 3(x - 2) = 18, what is x?', '["4","6","8","20"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Distribute the 3: 3x - 6 = 18. Add 6 to both sides: 3x = 24. Divide by 3: x = 8. Choice 4 comes from subtracting 6 from both sides instead of adding, yielding 3x = 12 and then x = 4. Choice 6 drops the constant entirely after distributing and divides 18 by 3, ignoring the -6 term. Choice 20 reports the value of 3x - 4 by skipping the divide step (3x = 24, then 24 - 4). Both terms inside the parentheses must be multiplied by the factor outside, and the -6 must be moved to the right side by adding.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If -2x + 9 = 1, what is x?', '["-4","4","5","-5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 9 from both sides: -2x = -8. Divide by -2: x = 4. Choice -4 is the sign-error trap from dividing -8 by 2 instead of -2, or from forgetting that negative divided by negative is positive. Choice 5 comes from adding 9 to 1 instead of subtracting and then dividing by 2. Choice -5 compounds both errors. When the variable has a negative coefficient, the final division by that negative must flip the sign of the result.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 4(2x + 1) = 28, what is x?', '["3","3.375","13.5","27"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Distribute the 4: 8x + 4 = 28. Subtract 4 from both sides: 8x = 24. Divide by 8: x = 3. Choice 13.5 comes from dropping the 4 entirely on the left side (writing 2x + 1 = 28), then solving 2x = 27 to get x = 13.5. Choice 3.375 results from 8x + 1 = 28: the student multiplies 2x by 4 but leaves the 1 unmultiplied, then solves 8x = 27 to get x = 3.375. Choice 27 is the intermediate value 28 - 1, reported before dividing. The factor outside the parentheses must hit every term inside.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 5 - 3x = -7, what is x?', '["-4","4","-2/3","2/3"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 5 from both sides: -3x = -12. Divide by -3: x = 4. Choice -4 is the sign-error trap from dividing -12 by 3 instead of -3, ignoring that a negative divided by a negative yields positive. Choice -2/3 comes from adding 5 to -7 to get -2 then dividing by 3, a transposition error. Choice 2/3 compounds the same transposition with the sign-flip. Negative coefficients on the variable demand careful tracking of signs through the final division.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If 7x - 4 = 3x + 12, what is x?', '["2","4","8","16"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 3x from both sides: 4x - 4 = 12. Add 4 to both sides: 4x = 16. Divide by 4: x = 4. Choice 16 is the intermediate value of 4x reported instead of x. Choice 2 comes from a sign-error of subtracting 4 from 12 instead of adding, giving 4x = 8. Choice 8 results from 7x + 3x = 10x and then 10x = 16 with arithmetic slips on combining variable terms. Move variable terms to one side and constants to the other before isolating.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If 2x + 5 = 17, what is the value of x² - x?', '["6","12","30","42"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Solve for x first: 2x + 5 = 17, so 2x = 12 and x = 6. Substitute into x² - x: 6² - 6 = 36 - 6 = 30. Choice 6 stops at x without computing the expression, a common premature-stop trap. Choice 12 is the intermediate value of 2x from the first equation. Choice 42 comes from x² + x = 36 + 6, a sign-error on the second term. Always read what the question asks for after solving for the variable, not just the variable''s value.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If 5x + 8 = 2x - 7, what is x?', '["-5","5","-1/3","1/3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 2x from both sides: 3x + 8 = -7. Subtract 8 from both sides: 3x = -15. Divide by 3: x = -5. Choice 5 is the sign-error trap from dropping the negative on the final division. Choice -1/3 comes from adding 8 to -7 to get 1 instead of subtracting, then dividing by 3 with a sign flip. Choice 1/3 compounds both arithmetic and sign errors. Negative results are common when variable coefficients on the left exceed those on the right but the constants pull the answer below zero.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If x + y = 10 and x - y = 4, what is x?', '["3","6","7","14"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the two equations: (x + y) + (x - y) = 10 + 4, which gives 2x = 14, so x = 7. Choice 14 is the intermediate value of 2x reported instead of x. Choice 3 is the value of y, not x: substituting x = 7 into x + y = 10 gives y = 3. Choice 6 comes from averaging the right-hand sides incorrectly. Adding the two equations cancels the y terms because their coefficients are opposites, leaving a single-variable equation in x.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'If -3x > 12, which describes x?', '["x > 4","x > -4","x < 4","x < -4"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Divide both sides by -3. Dividing or multiplying an inequality by a negative number flips the direction of the inequality: x < -4. Choice x > -4 is the trap of dividing without flipping the sign, the most common inequality error. Choice x > 4 also fails to flip the sign and additionally drops the negative on -4. Choice x < 4 flips the sign but drops the negative result. Two operations must happen together when dividing an inequality by a negative: compute the numeric result and reverse the inequality symbol.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'If 2x + y = 11 and x + y = 7, what is y?', '["3","4","7","11"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract the second equation from the first: (2x + y) - (x + y) = 11 - 7, which gives x = 4. Substitute x = 4 into x + y = 7: 4 + y = 7, so y = 3. Choice 4 is the value of x, not y, a common premature-stop trap when the question asks for the other variable. Choice 7 is the right-hand side of the second equation, not y. Choice 11 is the right-hand side of the first equation. Subtracting one equation from another with matching y coefficients eliminates y, but here it isolates x.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Evaluate 3⁴.', '["12","27","64","81"]'::jsonb, 3, 'An exponent means repeated multiplication of the base. 3⁴ equals 3 · 3 · 3 · 3, which equals 81. Choice 12 multiplies the base and exponent (3 × 4), a common shortcut error. Choice 27 stops one step early at 3³. Choice 64 confuses the base and exponent and computes 4³ instead. Only the full product 3 · 3 · 3 · 3 = 81 applies the definition of an exponent correctly.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Simplify x³ · x⁴.', '["x⁷","x¹²","x","2x⁷"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When multiplying powers with the same base, add the exponents. x³ · x⁴ becomes x^(3+4), which equals x⁷. Choice x¹² multiplies the exponents instead of adding them, which is the rule for a power raised to a power, not multiplication. Choice x subtracts the exponents as if dividing. Choice 2x⁷ incorrectly doubles the coefficient; the bases each have an implied coefficient of 1, and 1 · 1 stays 1.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Evaluate 2⁵.', '["10","16","25","32"]'::jsonb, 3, '2⁵ means multiply 2 by itself five times: 2 · 2 · 2 · 2 · 2, which equals 32. Choice 10 multiplies the base by the exponent (2 × 5), which ignores the meaning of exponents. Choice 16 stops one factor short at 2⁴. Choice 25 swaps the base and exponent and computes 5². Working through each doubling, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, confirms 32 is correct.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify x⁸ / x³.', '["x¹¹","x²⁴","x⁵","x⁵/³"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When dividing powers with the same base, subtract the exponents. x⁸ / x³ becomes x^(8-3), which equals x⁵. Choice x¹¹ adds the exponents, which is the rule for multiplication, not division. Choice x²⁴ multiplies the exponents, which applies to a power of a power. Choice x⁵/³ treats the exponents as a fraction left over after subtraction, mixing rules. Subtracting exponents during same-base division produces x⁵.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify (x³)⁴.', '["x⁷","x¹²","x⁸¹","x⁶⁴"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When raising a power to a power, multiply the exponents. (x³)⁴ becomes x^(3·4), which equals x¹². Choice x⁷ adds the exponents, which is the rule for multiplying same-base expressions, not nesting. Choice x⁸¹ raises 3 to the fourth power and treats that as the exponent. Choice x⁶⁴ raises 4 to the third power. Multiplying the two exponents directly gives x¹².', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Rewrite x⁻³ with a positive exponent.', '["1/x³","-x³","-3x","1/(-x³)"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A negative exponent means take the reciprocal of the base with a positive exponent. x⁻³ equals 1/x³. Choice -x³ treats the negative exponent as a negative sign on the result, which confuses two different operations. Choice -3x multiplies the base by the exponent. Choice 1/(-x³) puts the negative on the base itself, which would only happen if the base were written as (-x). The rule converts the negative exponent into a positive exponent in the denominator.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify (y²)⁵.', '["y⁷","y¹⁰","y²⁵","y³²"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When raising a power to a power, multiply the exponents. (y²)⁵ becomes y^(2·5), which equals y¹⁰. Choice y⁷ adds the exponents, which is the rule for multiplying same-base terms, not nesting. Choice y²⁵ squares the outer exponent and uses that as the result. Choice y³² evaluates 2⁵ and treats that as the exponent. The correct move is to multiply 2 and 5 to get y¹⁰.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify (2x³)².', '["2x⁶","4x⁵","4x⁶","4x⁹"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When an exponent applies to a product, distribute it to each factor. (2x³)² becomes 2² · (x³)², which equals 4 · x⁶, or 4x⁶. Choice 2x⁶ squares the variable part but forgets to square the coefficient. Choice 4x⁵ squares the coefficient but adds exponents instead of multiplying them. Choice 4x⁹ raises the inside exponent to the outside power instead of multiplying. The product 4x⁶ applies both the coefficient and exponent rules.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Expand (x + 3)(x + 4).', '["x² + 12","2x + 7","x² + 7x + 7","x² + 7x + 12"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Use FOIL to expand: first x · x = x², outer x · 4 = 4x, inner 3 · x = 3x, last 3 · 4 = 12. Combine like terms 4x + 3x to get 7x. The product is x² + 7x + 12. Choice x² + 12 multiplies only the first and last terms and skips the middle. Choice 2x + 7 adds the binomials instead of multiplying. Choice x² + 7x + 7 forgets to multiply the constants and uses 3 + 4 instead of 3 · 4.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify (xy²)³.', '["xy⁶","x³y⁵","x³y⁶","x³y⁸"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Distribute the exponent across each factor in the product, multiplying exponents when raising a power to a power. (xy²)³ becomes x³ · (y²)³, which equals x³y⁶. Choice xy⁶ raises only y to the third power and leaves x with exponent 1. Choice x³y⁵ adds exponents 2 and 3 instead of multiplying. Choice x³y⁸ raises 2 to the third power and treats that as the exponent of y. The product rule cubes each factor.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify x⁵ · x⁻².', '["x⁷","x³","x⁻¹⁰","1/x³"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When multiplying powers with the same base, add the exponents, including negatives. x⁵ · x⁻² becomes x^(5 + (-2)), which equals x³. Choice x⁷ adds 5 and 2 as if both were positive, ignoring the negative sign. Choice x⁻¹⁰ multiplies the exponents instead of adding them. Choice 1/x³ flips the result to the denominator, which would apply only if the final exponent were negative. The sum 5 + (-2) = 3 keeps the answer in the numerator.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Expand (x - 2)(x + 5).', '["x² - 10","x² - 3x - 10","x² + 3x + 10","x² + 3x - 10"]'::jsonb, 3, 'FOIL: first x · x = x², outer x · 5 = 5x, inner -2 · x = -2x, last -2 · 5 = -10. Combine 5x and -2x to get 3x. The result is x² + 3x - 10. Choice x² - 10 skips the middle terms. Choice x² - 3x - 10 reverses the sign on the middle term, a common error from subtracting instead of adding 5x and -2x. Choice x² + 3x + 10 keeps the constant positive, forgetting that a positive times a negative is negative.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Factor x² + 7x + 10.', '["(x + 1)(x + 10)","(x + 2)(x + 5)","(x + 3)(x + 4)","(x - 2)(x - 5)"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find two numbers that multiply to 10 and add to 7. The pair 2 and 5 works because 2 · 5 = 10 and 2 + 5 = 7, so the factors are (x + 2)(x + 5). Choice (x + 1)(x + 10) multiplies to 10 but adds to 11. Choice (x + 3)(x + 4) adds to 7 but multiplies to 12. Choice (x - 2)(x - 5) multiplies to 10 but adds to -7, flipping the sign on the middle term.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Factor x² - x - 12.', '["(x - 4)(x + 3)","(x + 4)(x - 3)","(x - 4)(x - 3)","(x + 6)(x - 2)"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Find two numbers that multiply to -12 and add to -1. The pair -4 and 3 works because -4 · 3 = -12 and -4 + 3 = -1, so the factors are (x - 4)(x + 3). Choice (x + 4)(x - 3) multiplies to -12 but adds to 1, the wrong sign on the middle term. Choice (x - 4)(x - 3) multiplies to 12, not -12. Choice (x + 6)(x - 2) multiplies to -12 but adds to 4. Sign placement matters because the constant is negative.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Simplify ((x²)³)².', '["x⁷","x⁸","x¹²","x⁶⁴"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Apply the power of a power rule from the inside out, multiplying exponents at each step. (x²)³ becomes x⁶. Then (x⁶)² becomes x^(6·2), which equals x¹². Choice x⁷ adds the three exponents 2 + 3 + 2 instead of multiplying. Choice x⁸ multiplies 2 · 4, treating the outer 2 as applying to the inner 2. Choice x⁶⁴ evaluates 2⁶ and treats that as the exponent. Multiplying 2 · 3 · 2 gives 12.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Factor x² + 10x + 25.', '["(x + 5)²","(x - 5)²","(x + 5)(x - 5)","(x + 25)(x + 1)"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Look for two numbers that multiply to 25 and add to 10. The pair 5 and 5 works, so the factors are (x + 5)(x + 5), which equals (x + 5)². This is a perfect square trinomial. Choice (x - 5)² expands to x² - 10x + 25, with the wrong sign on the middle term. Choice (x + 5)(x - 5) is the difference of squares, which would produce x² - 25 and no middle term. Choice (x + 25)(x + 1) multiplies to 25 but adds to 26.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-17', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Evaluate 7⁰.', '["0","1","7","undefined"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Any nonzero number raised to the zero power equals 1, so 7⁰ equals 1. The rule follows from the division pattern: 7^n / 7^n equals 1, but using the exponent rule it also equals 7^(n-n), which equals 7⁰. Choice 0 confuses the exponent with the result. Choice 7 keeps the base when the exponent is zero, mixing it up with the rule for an exponent of 1. Choice undefined applies only to 0⁰, not to a nonzero base.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-18', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Factor x² - 49.', '["(x - 7)²","(x + 7)²","(x + 7)(x - 7)","(x - 49)(x + 1)"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The expression is a difference of squares because 49 equals 7² and there is no middle term. The pattern a² - b² factors as (a + b)(a - b), so x² - 49 becomes (x + 7)(x - 7). Choice (x - 7)² expands to x² - 14x + 49, which has a middle term and the wrong constant sign. Choice (x + 7)² expands to x² + 14x + 49. Choice (x - 49)(x + 1) multiplies to -49 but produces x² - 48x - 49, not a clean difference of squares.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-19', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Which expression equals x^(1/2)?', '["x/2","√x","1/x²","2/x"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A fractional exponent of 1/2 means take the square root of the base, so x^(1/2) equals √x. The general rule states x^(1/n) equals the nth root of x. Choice x/2 divides the base by 2, treating the exponent as a regular fraction multiplier. Choice 1/x² applies the negative-exponent rule and squares the base, mixing two unrelated operations. Choice 2/x flips the fraction and uses the base as a denominator. Only the square root matches the fractional exponent definition.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-20', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Evaluate 25^(1/2).', '["5","12.5","50","625"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A fractional exponent of 1/2 means take the square root of the base, so 25^(1/2) equals √25, which equals 5. Choice 12.5 multiplies 25 by 1/2, treating the exponent as a regular multiplier instead of a root. Choice 50 multiplies 25 by 2, applying the reciprocal of the exponent as a multiplier. Choice 625 squares 25, which would happen with an exponent of 2 rather than 1/2. The square root, not multiplication, defines a 1/2 power.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, '1/2 + 1/4 = ?', '["2/6","3/4","1/6","2/4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rewrite 1/2 with a denominator of 4 so both fractions share a common base: 1/2 equals 2/4. Now add the numerators while holding the denominator fixed: 2/4 plus 1/4 equals 3/4. The result is already in lowest terms because 3 and 4 share no common factor. The choice 2/6 comes from adding numerators and denominators separately, which is not how fraction addition works. The choice 2/4 is the converted form of 1/2 alone, with no addition performed. The choice 1/6 reflects a similar add-everything error applied with the wrong sign.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, '0.3 + 0.4 = ?', '["0.07","0.7","0.34","7"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Line up the decimal points and add tenths to tenths. Three tenths plus four tenths equals seven tenths, written 0.7. Since each addend has only one digit after the decimal point, the sum also has one digit after the decimal point. The choice 0.07 places the sum two decimal places to the right, treating 0.3 and 0.4 as hundredths rather than tenths. The choice 0.34 concatenates the digits without performing any addition. The choice 7 drops the decimal point entirely and gives a whole number. Only 0.7 preserves the place value of the original addends.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, 'What is 1/2 of 0.5?', '["0.25","1.0","0.5","0.1"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Taking half of a number means multiplying by 1/2, which equals 0.5. Compute 0.5 times 0.5: multiply 5 by 5 to get 25, then place two decimal places in the product because each factor has one decimal place. The result is 0.25. As a fraction, 1/2 times 1/2 equals 1/4, which converts to 0.25 and confirms the answer. The choice 1.0 results from adding 0.5 to itself instead of halving. The choice 0.5 leaves the value unchanged, ignoring the halving step. The choice 0.1 misplaces the decimal point.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, '1/3 + 1/4 = ?', '["2/7","7/12","1/7","2/12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The denominators 3 and 4 share no common factors, so the least common denominator is their product, 12. Convert each fraction: 1/3 becomes 4/12 because 1 times 4 is 4 and 3 times 4 is 12, while 1/4 becomes 3/12 because 1 times 3 is 3 and 4 times 3 is 12. Add the numerators: 4 plus 3 equals 7. The sum is 7/12, already in lowest terms since 7 is prime. The choice 2/7 comes from adding numerators and denominators directly. The choice 1/7 reflects a similar error with a subtraction step. The choice 2/12 ignores the conversion step.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, '2/3 × 3/5 = ? (lowest terms)', '["6/15","5/8","2/5","1/5"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply numerators across and denominators across without finding a common denominator, since this is multiplication. 2 times 3 is 6, and 3 times 5 is 15, giving 6/15. Reduce by dividing both by their greatest common factor, 3: 6 divided by 3 is 2, and 15 divided by 3 is 5. The result is 2/5. The choice 6/15 is the unsimplified product, which fails the lowest-terms requirement stated in the stem. The choice 5/8 comes from adding numerators and denominators instead of multiplying. The choice 1/5 reflects an over-reduction error that drops too much from the numerator.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, 'Write 0.6 as a fraction in lowest terms.', '["6/10","3/5","2/3","6/100"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The decimal 0.6 means six tenths, written as the fraction 6/10. To put this in lowest terms, find the greatest common factor of 6 and 10, which is 2. Divide both top and bottom by 2: 6 over 10 becomes 3 over 5. Since 3 and 5 share no common factor, 3/5 is fully reduced. The choice 6/10 is correct in value but not in lowest terms, so it fails the stated requirement. The choice 2/3 is close in decimal value, 0.666..., but not equal to 0.6 exactly. The choice 6/100 misreads the place value, treating 0.6 as six hundredths.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, '5/8 − 1/4 = ?', '["4/4","3/8","1/2","4/8"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find a common denominator before subtracting. The denominators 8 and 4 share 4 as a factor, and 8 is a multiple of 4, so use 8 as the common denominator. Convert 1/4 to eighths by multiplying top and bottom by 2: 1/4 equals 2/8. Subtract: 5/8 minus 2/8 equals 3/8. Since 3 and 8 share no common factor, 3/8 is already in lowest terms. The choice 4/4 comes from subtracting numerators and denominators separately. The choice 1/2 reflects a guess at a familiar fraction near the answer. The choice 4/8 forgets the conversion and subtracts 1 from 5 directly.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, '2 1/3 + 1 1/4 = ?', '["3 2/7","3 7/12","3 1/12","4 7/12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add whole parts first: 2 plus 1 equals 3. For the fractional parts, use the common denominator 12: 1/3 becomes 4/12, and 1/4 becomes 3/12. Add 4/12 plus 3/12 to get 7/12. Combine the whole part with the fractional part: 3 and 7/12. The choice 3 2/7 adds numerators and denominators of the fractional parts. The choice 3 1/12 subtracts instead of adds. The choice 4 7/12 adds an extra whole unit that does not arise here.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, 'Express 1/3 as a decimal.', '["0.3","0.33","0.333...","0.13"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Perform long division of 1 by 3. The first digit after the decimal point is 3, with remainder 1. The next digit is again 3, with remainder 1, and the pattern continues forever. The result is 0.333..., a repeating decimal, often written with a bar over the 3. The choice 0.3 truncates after one place and loses accuracy. The choice 0.33 truncates after two places and is still short of the exact value, falling between 0.33 and 0.34. The choice 0.13 misorders the digits and gives a much smaller number. Only 0.333... captures the full repeating pattern.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, 'Which fraction is largest: 3/5, 5/8, 7/12, 2/3?', '["3/5","5/8","7/12","2/3"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Convert each to a decimal for direct comparison, rounded to three places. 3 divided by 5 equals 0.600 exactly. 5 divided by 8 equals 0.625 exactly. 7 divided by 12 equals 0.583 with a 3 repeating. 2 divided by 3 equals 0.666 with a 6 repeating. Even without exact decimals, the comparison is clear: 0.666... is larger than 0.625, which is larger than 0.600, which is larger than 0.583. So 2/3 is the largest fraction. Comparing numerators or denominators alone fails because both differ across the four fractions. Decimal conversion gives a single common scale that makes the ordering immediate.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, '3 1/2 − 1 3/4 = ?', '["2 1/4","1 3/4","1 1/4","2 3/4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert both to improper fractions to avoid borrowing errors. 3 1/2 becomes 7/2, which equals 14/4. 1 3/4 stays as 7/4. Subtract: 14/4 minus 7/4 equals 7/4. Convert back to a mixed number: 7 divided by 4 is 1 with remainder 3, giving 1 3/4. The choice 2 1/4 results from subtracting whole parts and fractional parts separately without borrowing. The choice 1 1/4 drops half a unit somewhere in the borrow. The choice 2 3/4 reverses the operation.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, '(3/4) ÷ (2/3) = ?', '["1/2","6/12","1 1/8","2/4"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Dividing by a fraction means multiplying by its reciprocal, the flip-and-multiply rule. Flip the divisor 2/3 to 3/2, then multiply: 3/4 times 3/2. Multiply numerators across to get 9, and multiply denominators across to get 8, giving 9/8. Convert 9/8 to a mixed number: 9 divided by 8 is 1 with remainder 1, so the result is 1 1/8. The choice 1/2 comes from multiplying 3/4 by 2/3 without flipping. The choice 6/12 also reflects multiplying instead of dividing. The choice 2/4 simplifies the same multiplication error. Only flipping and multiplying gives 1 1/8.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, 'What is 1/2 of 3/4 of 8?', '["3","6","4","12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Work from the inside out. Three-fourths of 8 is 6, since 8 divided by 4 is 2 and 2 times 3 is 6. Then one-half of 6 is 3. Equivalently, multiply across: 1/2 times 3/4 times 8 equals 24/8 equals 3. The choice 6 stops after the first step and forgets to take half. The choice 4 reflects taking half of 8 first and ignoring the 3/4. The choice 12 adds the steps instead of multiplying them.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, '(1/2 + 1/3) ÷ (1/6) = ?', '["5/36","5","1/5","6/5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add inside the parentheses first using a common denominator of 6, since 6 is the least common multiple of 2 and 3. Convert: 1/2 becomes 3/6, and 1/3 becomes 2/6. Add the numerators to get 5/6. Now divide by 1/6 by flipping the divisor and multiplying: 5/6 times 6/1 equals 30/6, which simplifies to 5. The choice 5/36 multiplies by 1/6 instead of dividing. The choice 1/5 reverses the final operation entirely. The choice 6/5 inverts the answer. Only flipping the divisor and multiplying delivers 5.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, '(2/5) ÷ (4/15) = ? Express as a mixed number in lowest terms.', '["8/75","1 1/2","4/3","2/3"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Invert the divisor and multiply: 2/5 times 15/4 equals 30/20. Reduce by dividing top and bottom by 10: 30 over 20 becomes 3 over 2. Convert to a mixed number as the stem requests: 3/2 equals 1 1/2. The choice 8/75 multiplies the original fractions without flipping the divisor. The choice 4/3 comes from inverting the wrong fraction, flipping 2/5 to 5/2 and then misreducing. The choice 2/3 inverts the final answer. Only 1 1/2 is the simplified quotient in the requested mixed-number form.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'Which fraction equals 0.1818... (the 18 repeats)?', '["18/100","9/50","2/11","1/9"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use the standard rule for repeating decimals: a two-digit repeating block becomes that block over 99. So 0.1818... equals 18/99. Reduce by dividing top and bottom by the greatest common factor, 9: 18 over 99 becomes 2 over 11. Verify by long division: 2 divided by 11 produces 0.181818..., confirming the match. The choice 18/100 equals 0.18 exactly, with no repeating tail. The choice 9/50 also equals 0.18 exactly and terminates. The choice 1/9 equals 0.111..., a different repeating pattern. Only 2/11 produces the 0.18 repeat shown in the stem.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-17', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'Which fraction has a terminating decimal expansion?', '["1/3","1/6","1/7","1/8"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A fraction in lowest terms terminates exactly when its denominator factors into only 2s and 5s. Check each denominator. 3 has a factor of 3, so 1/3 repeats. 6 equals 2 times 3, so 1/6 repeats. 7 is prime and not 2 or 5, so 1/7 repeats. 8 equals 2 times 2 times 2, with only 2s, so 1/8 terminates. Indeed 1/8 equals 0.125 exactly. Only denominators built from 2s and 5s alone produce terminating decimals.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-18', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'Compare 7/16 and 0.4375.', '["7/16 > 0.4375","7/16 < 0.4375","7/16 = 0.4375","Cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert 7/16 to a decimal by dividing 7 by 16. Long division gives 0.4375 exactly, with no remainder, since 16 equals 2 to the fourth power and produces a terminating decimal. The two values are identical. The choices claiming inequality assume a rounding gap that does not exist here. The choice for cannot be determined is incorrect because exact conversion is always possible when the denominator is a power of 2. Only the equality statement matches the conversion.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'A rectangular rug measures 8 ft by 5 ft. What is its area?', '["13 sq ft","26 sq ft","40 sq ft","45 sq ft"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area of a rectangle is length times width: 8 times 5 equals 40 square feet. Choice 13 sq ft adds the sides instead of multiplying. Choice 26 sq ft computes the perimeter (2 times 8 plus 2 times 5) and confuses it with area. Choice 45 sq ft is 9 times 5, a multiplication slip. Area always carries square units; perimeter carries linear units. When the question asks how much surface a rug covers, you want square feet, which signals area, not perimeter.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'What is the circumference of a circle with radius 6 in? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["18.84 in","28.26 in","37.68 in","113.04 in"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Circumference equals 2 pi r: 2 times 3.14 times 6 equals 37.68 inches. Choice 18.84 in uses pi r and forgets the factor of 2. Choice 28.26 in is pi times r squared divided by 4, a garbled mix of formulas. Choice 113.04 in is the area pi r squared (3.14 times 36), which is square inches, not linear inches. Circumference is a distance around the circle, so the units must be linear inches, not square inches.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'A square patio has sides of 7 ft. What is its perimeter?', '["14 ft","21 ft","28 ft","49 ft"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Perimeter of a square is 4 times the side length: 4 times 7 equals 28 feet. Choice 14 ft doubles the side as if the figure were a line segment with two ends. Choice 21 ft uses three sides only. Choice 49 ft is 7 squared, which gives the area in square feet, not the perimeter in linear feet. Perimeter measures the fence-line distance around the patio, so it must use linear units and count all four equal sides.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'A triangle has a base of 10 cm and a height of 6 cm. What is its area?', '["16 sq cm","30 sq cm","60 sq cm","120 sq cm"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Area of a triangle is one-half base times height: 0.5 times 10 times 6 equals 30 square centimeters. Choice 16 sq cm adds base and height instead of multiplying. Choice 60 sq cm forgets the one-half factor and treats the triangle like a rectangle. Choice 120 sq cm doubles that error. The one-half factor exists because a triangle is exactly half of a rectangle with the same base and height, so any triangle area must include it.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'A right triangle has legs of 6 in and 8 in. What is the length of the hypotenuse?', '["10 in","100 in","14 in","48 in"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Using the Pythagorean theorem, a squared plus b squared equals c squared: 36 plus 64 equals 100, so c equals the square root of 100, which is 10 inches. Choice 100 in forgets to take the square root at the end and reports c squared as if it were c. Choice 14 in adds the legs directly (6 + 8 = 14), skipping the theorem entirely. Choice 48 in multiplies the legs (6 x 8). The 6-8-10 triple is a scaled 3-4-5; recognizing it on sight saves time. The hypotenuse is always the side opposite the right angle and is the longest side.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'What is the surface area of a cube with edge length 4 in?', '["16 sq in","64 sq in","96 sq in","384 sq in"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A cube has 6 identical square faces. Each face has area 4 squared, which is 16 square inches. Total surface area is 6 times 16, which equals 96 square inches. Choice 16 sq in gives only one face. Choice 64 sq in is 4 cubed, the volume in cubic inches. Choice 384 sq in is 6 times 64, mixing volume with the face count. Surface area uses square units; volume uses cubic units. Watching units catches the volume-vs-surface confusion fast.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'A rectangular shipping crate is 5 ft long, 3 ft wide, and 2 ft tall. What is its volume?', '["10 cubic ft","15 cubic ft","30 cubic ft","62 cubic ft"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Volume of a rectangular prism is length times width times height: 5 times 3 times 2 equals 30 cubic feet. Choice 10 cubic ft multiplies only length and height, omitting width. Choice 15 cubic ft multiplies length and width and forgets the height entirely, a common error when people stop at base area. Choice 62 cubic ft is the surface area 2(lw + lh + wh), not the volume. Volume needs all three dimensions and uses cubic units.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'A soda can is shaped like a cylinder with radius 2 in and height 5 in. What is its volume? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["31.4 cubic in","62.8 cubic in","78.5 cubic in","125.6 cubic in"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Volume of a cylinder is pi r squared times height: 3.14 times 4 times 5 equals 62.8 cubic inches. Choice 31.4 cubic in uses pi r h, forgetting to square the radius. Choice 78.5 cubic in is pi r squared times r, using radius instead of height. Choice 125.6 cubic in doubles the answer, likely from using diameter (4) where radius (2) belongs and then squaring. Always square the radius in pi r squared and keep diameter and radius separated.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'A right triangle has one leg of 5 m and a hypotenuse of 13 m. What is the length of the other leg?', '["8 m","12 m","14 m","18 m"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use a squared plus b squared equals c squared, where c is the hypotenuse: 5 squared plus b squared equals 13 squared, so 25 plus b squared equals 169. Then b squared equals 144, and b equals 12 meters. Choice 8 m subtracts 5 from 13 as if the sides were collinear. Choice 14 m adds them. Choice 18 m is 13 plus 5. This is the 5-12-13 triple. The hypotenuse is the longest side and always sits opposite the right angle.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'What is the area of a circle with diameter 10 cm? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["15.7 sq cm","31.4 sq cm","78.5 sq cm","314 sq cm"]'::jsonb, 2, 'First convert diameter to radius: 10 divided by 2 equals 5 cm. Area is pi r squared: 3.14 times 25 equals 78.5 square centimeters. Choice 15.7 sq cm is half the circumference, mixing formulas. Choice 31.4 sq cm is the circumference using the diameter (pi times d). Choice 314 sq cm squares the diameter instead of the radius (3.14 times 100). Whenever a circle problem gives diameter, halve it before using pi r squared so the radius is squared, not the diameter.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 4, 'Two triangles are similar. The smaller has sides 4, 6, and 8 in. The longest side of the larger triangle is 20 in. What is the length of its shortest side?', '["10 in","12 in","15 in","16 in"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Similar triangles have a constant scale factor. The longest side scales from 8 to 20, so the factor is 20 divided by 8, which equals 2.5. The shortest side scales from 4 in, so 4 times 2.5 equals 10 inches. Choice 12 in scales the middle side (6 times 2). Choice 15 in scales the middle side by 2.5 (correct factor, wrong side). Choice 16 in doubles the shortest side using a factor of 2 from a wrong pairing. Always pair corresponding sides before computing the scale factor.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 4, 'A garden is a rectangle 12 ft by 6 ft with a semicircle attached to one short end. What is the total area? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["72 sq ft","86.13 sq ft","100.26 sq ft","172.5 sq ft"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The rectangle area is 12 times 6, which equals 72 square feet. The semicircle sits on the short end, so its diameter is 6 ft and its radius is 3 ft. A full circle would be pi times 9, or 28.26; half of that is 14.13 square feet. Total area is 72 plus 14.13, which equals 86.13 square feet. Choice 72 sq ft skips the semicircle. Choice 100.26 sq ft adds a full circle instead of a half. Choice 172.5 sq ft uses the wrong radius (6 instead of 3) and forgets to halve.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 4, 'A circle has radius 12 in. What is the length of an arc that subtends a central angle of 90 degrees? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["9.42 in","18.84 in","37.68 in","75.36 in"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A 90-degree central angle is one-fourth of the full 360-degree circle, so the arc is one-fourth of the circumference. Circumference is 2 pi r: 2 times 3.14 times 12 equals 75.36 inches. One-fourth of 75.36 is 18.84 inches. Choice 9.42 in halves the radius then takes one-fourth, double-shrinking. Choice 37.68 in is half the circumference (a semicircle, not a quarter). Choice 75.36 in is the full circumference. Match the angle fraction to the full 360 before slicing the circumference.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'What is the surface area of a closed cylinder with radius 3 ft and height 7 ft? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["131.88 sq ft","188.4 sq ft","197.82 sq ft","263.76 sq ft"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Surface area of a closed cylinder is 2 pi r squared plus 2 pi r h. The two circular ends are 2 times 3.14 times 9, which equals 56.52 square feet. The side is 2 times 3.14 times 3 times 7, which equals 131.88 square feet. Total is 56.52 plus 131.88, which equals 188.4 square feet. Choice 131.88 sq ft is the lateral side only and forgets the two ends. Choice 197.82 sq ft is the volume pi r squared h (3.14 times 9 times 7), wrong formula entirely. Choice 263.76 sq ft double-counts the side.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'Two parallel lines are cut by a transversal. One of the angles formed measures 65 degrees. What is the measure of its co-interior (same-side interior) angle?', '["25 degrees","65 degrees","115 degrees","130 degrees"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When parallel lines are cut by a transversal, co-interior (same-side interior) angles are supplementary, so they sum to 180 degrees. 180 minus 65 equals 115 degrees. Choice 25 degrees uses 90 minus 65, treating the angles as complementary, which would only apply if they summed to a right angle. Choice 65 degrees treats them as corresponding or alternate-interior angles, which are equal but not the relationship asked for. Choice 130 degrees doubles 65, a slip. Same-side interior pairs are always supplementary when the lines are parallel.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'In a 30-60-90 triangle, the shorter leg is 5 in. What is the length of the hypotenuse?', '["5 in","10 in","5 times square root of 3 in","10 times square root of 3 in"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In a 30-60-90 right triangle, the side ratios are 1 to square root of 3 to 2, corresponding to the sides opposite the 30, 60, and 90 degree angles. The shorter leg (opposite 30) is 5 in, so the hypotenuse (opposite 90) is 2 times the shorter leg, which is 10 inches. Choice 5 in repeats the shorter leg. Choice 5 times square root of 3 in is the longer leg (opposite 60), not the hypotenuse. Choice 10 times square root of 3 in doubles the longer leg, mixing two ratios. The hypotenuse is always opposite the right angle and is twice the shorter leg in a 30-60-90.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'Which of the following is a prime number?', '["9","15","17","21"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A prime number has exactly two positive divisors: 1 and itself. Check each: 9 = 3 × 3, 15 = 3 × 5, and 21 = 3 × 7, so each has divisors beyond 1 and itself. Only 17 has no positive divisors except 1 and 17, making it prime. A common trap is forgetting that small odd composites like 9, 15, and 21 are not prime just because they look prime at a glance. Another trap is treating 1 as prime, but 1 has only one divisor and is excluded from the primes by definition.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'What is the value of |-12|?', '["-12","0","12","144"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Absolute value gives the distance of a number from zero on the number line, which is never negative. The distance from -12 to 0 is 12 units, so |-12| = 12. A common trap is leaving the negative sign in place and answering -12, but absolute value strips the sign. Another trap is squaring the number to get 144, which confuses |x| with x². A third trap is collapsing the bars to 0, which only applies when the input itself is 0.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'Is 84 divisible by 4?', '["Yes, because 84 ÷ 4 = 21 with no remainder","No, because 84 is odd","No, because 84 is not a multiple of 8","No, because 8 + 4 = 12 is not divisible by 4"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A number is divisible by 4 when its last two digits form a number divisible by 4. The last two digits of 84 are 84, and 84 ÷ 4 = 21 with no remainder, so 84 is divisible by 4. The first No choice is wrong on a factual level: 84 ends in 4 and is even, not odd. The second No choice confuses divisibility by 4 with divisibility by 8 (every multiple of 8 is a multiple of 4, but not the reverse). The third No choice applies the digit-sum rule, which belongs to 3 and 9, not 4. Only the Yes choice supplies a valid verdict and reason.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'What is the smallest prime factor of 30?', '["1","2","3","5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The prime factors of 30 are 2, 3, and 5, since 30 = 2 × 3 × 5. The smallest of these is 2. A common trap is selecting 1, but 1 is not prime and is excluded from any prime factorization. Another trap is forgetting that 2 is prime because it is the only even prime, leading test-takers to skip it and pick 3. The smallest prime factor of any even number is always 2.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the greatest common factor (GCF) of 18 and 24?', '["2","3","6","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Factor each number: 18 = 2 × 3², and 24 = 2³ × 3. The GCF takes the lowest power of each shared prime: 2¹ × 3¹ = 6. The trap of selecting 72 confuses GCF with LCM, since 72 is the least common multiple of 18 and 24. The traps of 2 and 3 stop after finding one shared prime instead of multiplying all shared primes together. The GCF is always less than or equal to the smaller of the two numbers.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the least common multiple (LCM) of 4 and 6?', '["2","10","12","24"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Factor each: 4 = 2² and 6 = 2 × 3. The LCM takes the highest power of every prime present: 2² × 3 = 12. The trap of selecting 2 confuses LCM with GCF, since 2 is the greatest common factor of 4 and 6. The trap of 24 multiplies the two numbers directly, which only gives the LCM when the numbers share no common factor. The trap of 10 adds the numbers instead of building from their prime factorizations.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'How many positive factors does 12 have?', '["3","4","5","6"]'::jsonb, 3, 'List all positive integers that divide 12 evenly: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, and 12. That is 6 factors total. A common trap is excluding 1 or 12 from the count and answering 4, but every positive integer counts itself and 1 among its factors. Another trap is counting only the prime factors (2 and 3) and answering 2 or stopping at 3. A shortcut: 12 = 2² × 3¹, so factor count = (2 + 1)(1 + 1) = 6.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'Which of the following is a perfect square?', '["18","24","36","50"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A perfect square is an integer that equals some integer squared. Check each: √18 ≈ 4.24, √24 ≈ 4.90, √36 = 6 exactly, and √50 ≈ 7.07. Only 36 = 6² is a perfect square. A common trap is picking 50 because it ends in 0 and looks clean, but perfect squares can end in 0, 1, 4, 5, 6, or 9, never in 2, 3, 7, or 8. Another trap is picking 18 or 24 because they are even, but evenness alone does not make a perfect square.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'Which of the following is NOT a prime number?', '["2","11","27","31"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Check each for divisors beyond 1 and itself: 11 and 31 have none, so both are prime. 27 = 3 × 9 = 3³, which is composite. The number 2 is prime because its only divisors are 1 and 2, even though it is even. A common trap is picking 2 because being even feels like it should disqualify a prime, but 2 is the only even prime. Another trap is missing that 27 is 3³, since 27 is odd and looks prime to test-takers who only screen for even composites.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'What is the greatest common factor (GCF) of 12, 18, and 30?', '["2","3","6","60"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Factor each: 12 = 2² × 3, 18 = 2 × 3², and 30 = 2 × 3 × 5. The GCF uses the lowest power of each prime shared by all three: 2¹ × 3¹ = 6. The trap of 60 confuses GCF with LCM. The traps of 2 and 3 stop after finding one shared prime instead of multiplying every prime shared across all three numbers. Note that 5 appears only in 30, so it cannot be part of the GCF; a prime must be in every number to count.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'What is the least common multiple (LCM) of 3, 4, and 6?', '["1","12","24","72"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Factor each: 3 = 3, 4 = 2², and 6 = 2 × 3. The LCM takes the highest power of every prime that appears in any number: 2² × 3 = 12. The trap of 72 multiplies all three numbers together, which overcounts shared primes. The trap of 24 doubles 12 unnecessarily, perhaps by forgetting that 6 is already covered when both 3 and 4 are present. The trap of 1 confuses LCM with GCF, since the GCF of 3, 4, and 6 is 1.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'Is 432 divisible by 9?', '["No, because 432 is not a multiple of 6","Yes, because 4 + 3 + 2 = 9","No, because 432 is not divisible by 3","No, because 432 does not end in 0 or 9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A number is divisible by 9 when the sum of its digits is divisible by 9. For 432, the digit sum is 4 + 3 + 2 = 9, which is divisible by 9, so 432 is divisible by 9 (432 ÷ 9 = 48). The first No fails on its premise: 432 is in fact a multiple of 6 (432 ÷ 6 = 72), and divisibility by 6 is not the test for 9. The second No claims 432 is not divisible by 3, which is false; any multiple of 9 is also a multiple of 3. The last-digit rule belongs to 5 or 10, not 9.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'The product of an even integer and an odd integer is always:', '["Odd","Even","Prime","A perfect square"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Any even integer contains a factor of 2. When that even integer is multiplied by an odd integer, the factor of 2 remains in the product, so the product is even. For example, 4 × 3 = 12 and 6 × 5 = 30. The trap of selecting odd misapplies the rule that odd × odd = odd to a mixed case. The trap of prime ignores that even products greater than 2 cannot be prime, since they have 2 as a factor. The trap of perfect square assumes structure that the rule does not guarantee.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'The sum of two odd integers is always:', '["Odd","Even","Prime","Divisible by 4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Write any odd integer as 2k + 1 for some integer k. The sum of two odd integers is (2a + 1) + (2b + 1) = 2a + 2b + 2 = 2(a + b + 1), which is a multiple of 2 and therefore even. Examples: 3 + 5 = 8 and 7 + 9 = 16. The trap of odd extends the wrong intuition that odd inputs yield odd outputs under addition. The trap of divisible by 4 holds only sometimes (3 + 5 = 8 works, but 3 + 7 = 10 does not). The trap of prime fails for almost every example.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'A trainer wants to split 24 boys and 36 girls into the largest possible teams, with each team having the same number of boys and the same number of girls. How many teams can she make?', '["6","12","60","72"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Largest equal groups across two counts requires the greatest common factor. Factor: 24 = 2³ × 3 and 36 = 2² × 3². GCF = 2² × 3 = 12, so she can make 12 teams, each with 24 ÷ 12 = 2 boys and 36 ÷ 12 = 3 girls. The trap of 60 adds the totals (24 + 36) and treats the result as the team count. The trap of 72 reaches for the LCM, which solves repeat-cycle problems, not equal-grouping problems. The trap of 6 stops at a shared factor without checking whether a larger one exists.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Bus A leaves every 15 minutes and Bus B leaves every 20 minutes. If both buses leave together at 8:00 AM, when will they next leave together?', '["8:35 AM","8:45 AM","9:00 AM","10:00 AM"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The next shared departure time is the least common multiple of the two intervals. Factor: 15 = 3 × 5 and 20 = 2² × 5. LCM = 2² × 3 × 5 = 60, so the buses next leave together after 60 minutes, at 9:00 AM. The trap of 8:35 AM adds the two intervals (15 + 20 = 35). The trap of 10:00 AM multiplies the intervals (15 × 20 = 300 minutes), which overcounts the shared factor of 5. The trap of 8:45 AM picks the next multiple of 15 without checking 20.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-17', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Simplify √72.', '["6√2","2√18","8√3","12√2"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Find the largest perfect-square factor of 72. Factor: 72 = 36 × 2, and 36 is a perfect square. So √72 = √36 × √2 = 6√2. The trap of 2√18 pulls out only a partial factor (4) and leaves a square inside the radical, since 18 = 9 × 2 still has a perfect-square factor. The trap of 8√3 mismatches the factorization (8² × 3 = 192, not 72). The trap of 12√2 doubles the correct coefficient, perhaps from confusing 72 with 144. Always extract the largest perfect square.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-18', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Simplify √50.', '["2√5","5√2","10√5","25√2"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find the largest perfect-square factor of 50. Factor: 50 = 25 × 2, and 25 is a perfect square. So √50 = √25 × √2 = 5√2. The trap of 2√5 swaps the coefficient and the radicand, since (2√5)² = 20, not 50. The trap of 25√2 fails to take the square root of 25 and leaves it as a coefficient. The trap of 10√5 picks the wrong factor pair (10 × 5) where neither 10 nor 5 is a perfect square. The check: (5√2)² = 25 × 2 = 50.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-19', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 5, 'What is the prime factorization of 60?', '["2 × 30","2² × 15","2² × 3 × 5","2 × 3 × 10"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A prime factorization expresses a number as a product of prime numbers only. Break 60 down: 60 = 2 × 30 = 2 × 2 × 15 = 2 × 2 × 3 × 5 = 2² × 3 × 5. Every factor in the final form is prime. The trap of 2 × 30 stops too early, since 30 is composite. The trap of 2² × 15 also stops short, since 15 = 3 × 5 is composite. The trap of 2 × 3 × 10 includes 10, which is composite (10 = 2 × 5). A prime factorization is complete only when every factor is prime.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-20', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 5, 'How many positive divisors does 36 have?', '["6","8","9","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use the divisor-count formula: if n = p^a × q^b, then n has (a + 1)(b + 1) positive divisors. Factor: 36 = 2² × 3². Divisor count = (2 + 1)(2 + 1) = 9. Verify by listing: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 9, 12, 18, 36, which is 9 divisors. The trap of 6 counts only some divisors or confuses divisors with prime factors. The trap of 8 forgets that 36 itself counts as a divisor. The trap of 12 may come from adding the exponents (2 + 2) and multiplying by 3, which is not the correct rule.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-21', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'Three consecutive integers have a sum of 72. What is the middle integer?', '["22","23","24","25"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let the three consecutive integers be n - 1, n, and n + 1, where n is the middle integer. Their sum is (n - 1) + n + (n + 1) = 3n. Set 3n = 72, so n = 24. Check: 23 + 24 + 25 = 72. A useful shortcut for any odd count of consecutive integers: the sum divided by the count gives the middle term directly. The trap of 23 picks the smallest of the three. The trap of 25 picks the largest. The trap of 22 may come from dividing 72 by 3 and then subtracting 2 by mistake.', false, 'draft'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-22', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'What is the sum of the first five prime numbers?', '["18","26","28","39"]'::jsonb, 2, 'List the first five primes in order: 2, 3, 5, 7, 11. Remember that 1 is not prime and 2 is the only even prime. Sum them: 2 + 3 + 5 + 7 + 11 = 28. The trap of 26 counts 9 as prime and lists 2, 3, 5, 7, 9, missing that 9 = 3 x 3. The trap of 39 skips 2 by assuming all primes are odd, listing 3, 5, 7, 11, 13. The trap of 18 counts 1 as prime and lists 1, 2, 3, 5, 7, stopping one prime short of the real first five.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Recycling at home is one of the easiest ways to help the environment. Sorting paper, plastic, and glass takes only a few minutes each week, but it keeps tons of waste out of landfills. Most cities now provide curbside bins at no extra cost, so the equipment is already there. The habit costs nothing and the payoff for local landfills is real. Every household should make recycling part of its weekly routine."

The author''s primary purpose in writing this passage is to:', '["explain how recycling facilities sort materials","encourage readers to recycle at home","compare landfills in different cities","describe the history of curbside recycling"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The closing sentence states the goal directly: "Every household should make recycling part of its weekly routine." That imperative, paired with "easiest ways to help" and "only a few minutes," marks the piece as persuasion. Choice B names that purpose. Choice A picks a technical angle the passage never enters, since sorting is mentioned only as effort the reader spends. Choice C invents a city-to-city comparison that does not appear. Choice D adds historical framing the passage does not provide. Only B fits the directive tone.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The new community park is a wonderful addition to our neighborhood. The walking trails are beautiful, the playground equipment is top quality, and the open lawns give families a perfect place to gather on weekends. The benches along the main path are already filled most evenings, and the new splash pad has been a favorite with children all summer. Residents should be proud of what their tax dollars built."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["skeptical","enthusiastic","indifferent","regretful"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Every adjective in the passage is praise: "wonderful," "beautiful," "top quality," "perfect," "proud." That stacked positive language signals enthusiasm rather than measured approval. Choice B names that tone. Choice A reverses the polarity, treating celebration as doubt. Choice C ignores the value-loaded vocabulary, which is the opposite of indifferent. Choice D imports regret the passage never expresses, since the author closes with pride rather than loss. Only B fits the consistently warm and celebratory language.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Reminder: All employees must complete the annual safety training by the end of the month. The training takes about thirty minutes and can be accessed through the company portal using your standard login credentials. Once complete, your manager will be notified automatically and no paperwork needs to be submitted. Failure to complete the training on time may delay payroll processing for the following pay period."

The author''s primary purpose in this memo is to:', '["praise employees for completing training quickly","inform employees of a deadline and how to meet it","argue that safety training should be made shorter","warn that the company is being investigated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The memo opens with "Reminder" and then lists the deadline, the time required, and how to access the training. That structure is straight notification. Choice B captures the informative purpose. Choice A invents praise the memo never offers, since employees are being prompted rather than thanked. Choice C reverses the position, since the author treats the thirty-minute length as a small ask, not a problem. Choice D escalates the routine consequence "may delay payroll" into an investigation the memo does not mention.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"I bought this blender expecting another disappointment. The last three I tried in this price range either burned out within weeks or struggled with anything thicker than a smoothie. Instead, this one crushed ice on the first try, cleaned up in under a minute, and has run every morning for six months without complaint. The motor still sounds the way it did out of the box. For under fifty dollars, I would call that a small miracle."

The author''s attitude toward the blender is best described as:', '["pleasantly surprised","wildly obsessive","mildly disappointed","coolly analytical"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author primes the reader for letdown with "expecting another disappointment," then flips with "Instead, it crushed ice on the first try" and "a small miracle." That contrast signals surprise paired with approval. Choice A names that exact attitude. Choice B overshoots into obsession, when the praise is measured rather than fanatical. Choice C contradicts the passage by holding onto disappointment the author explicitly drops. Choice D undersells the warmth in "small miracle," treating an excited review as a neutral analysis.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The proposal claims the new policy will save the city millions, but the numbers come from an internal estimate, not an independent audit. The same office that drafted the proposal also produced the financial projections that support it. Supporters keep citing the savings figure as if it were settled fact, and last week a council member quoted it on the radio without noting its source. Until outside reviewers verify the math, residents deserve to ask harder questions."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["openly hostile","skeptical","fully convinced","uninterested"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author flags the source of the numbers as "an internal estimate, not an independent audit" and calls for "outside reviewers" before treating the figure as fact. That is doubt grounded in process, not attack. Choice B names that skeptical tone. Choice A overshoots into hostility, since the author proposes verification rather than condemnation. Choice C reverses the position by treating the savings claim as accepted, which the passage refuses to do. Choice D ignores the active push for harder questions, which is the opposite of disengaged.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"To: All staff. The fourth-floor copier will be out of service Thursday afternoon for scheduled maintenance. Please route urgent print jobs to the second-floor machine, which has the same drivers installed and accepts the same employee codes. Bulk print jobs over two hundred pages should be moved to Wednesday afternoon if possible. Service should be restored by 5 p.m., and a follow-up email will confirm the copier is available again. Thank you for your patience."

The author''s primary purpose in writing this memo is to:', '["apologize for repeated equipment failures","notify staff of a brief outage and offer a workaround","warn that the copier may be permanently removed","request feedback on copier performance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The memo states the outage window, offers the second-floor machine as an alternative, and gives a restoration time. Choice B captures that notify-and-redirect purpose. Choice A reads "thank you for your patience" as apology for repeated problems, but the passage describes one scheduled maintenance event, not a pattern of failures. Choice C invents a permanent removal the memo never raises. Choice D imports a feedback request that does not appear; nothing in the memo asks staff to evaluate the copier.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Walking the same streets where my grandmother sold flowers seventy years ago, I notice that the shopfronts have all changed. The bakery on the corner is now a phone store, and the small market where she bought her ribbon closed before I was born. Yet the morning light hitting the brick still looks the way it did in her old photographs, and the cracked sidewalk near the church has not been repoured. Cities do not stay the same, yet small details survive longer than we expect."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["nostalgic","bitter","scientific","alarmed"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author anchors the present in the past with "my grandmother sold flowers seventy years ago," "her old photographs," and "small details survive." That looking-back warmth is nostalgia rather than complaint. Choice A names that tone. Choice B imports bitterness the passage never voices, since the author notes loss without resentment. Choice C ignores the personal, memory-laden vocabulary, which is the opposite of detached observation. Choice D escalates a gentle reflection into alarm, when the closing sentence is consoling rather than urgent.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Early results from the trial suggest the new treatment may reduce recovery time by about two days. The sample was small, follow-up was short, and outcomes varied across age groups. Patients over sixty saw the largest effect, while younger participants showed almost none. The researchers themselves stop short of recommending broader use, and the published paper calls for a multi-site replication before any guidelines are updated. The findings are promising enough to justify a larger study, though not yet to change clinical practice."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["cautiously optimistic","enthusiastic","dismissive","alarmed"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author balances hope with limits: "promising enough to justify a larger study" sits next to "sample was small" and "not yet to change clinical practice." That paired structure is the signature of cautious optimism. Choice A names it. Choice B overshoots into enthusiasm, ignoring the qualifiers the author keeps inserting. Choice C reverses the position by treating the results as worth dismissing, when the passage explicitly calls them promising. Choice D imports alarm that nothing in the passage supports, since the framing is measured rather than worried.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The mayor''s plan to add bike lanes downtown is a reasonable start, even if it falls short of what the traffic studies recommended. The original review called for protected lanes on twelve streets; the approved plan funds only seven. Half a fix is still better than none, and the lanes that are being built happen to cover the most dangerous intersections, including the two with the highest crash counts in last year''s report. Residents who wanted more should treat this as a foundation, not a finish line."

The author would most likely agree with which statement?', '["The plan is a disappointing failure that should be rejected.","The plan is an acceptable first step that needs to be expanded.","The plan is exactly the right size and does not need additional work.","The plan is irrelevant because traffic patterns will not change."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author calls the plan "a reasonable start" and tells residents to treat it as "a foundation, not a finish line," which combines approval of the current step with a demand for more. Choice B captures both halves. Choice A reads the criticism as outright rejection, ignoring "reasonable start" and "better than none." Choice C drops the call for expansion the author explicitly makes. Choice D invents fatalism about traffic that the passage never expresses, since the lanes are credited with covering the most dangerous intersections.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Coastal communities have always rebuilt after storms. Generations of families have torn out drywall, replaced shingles, and put their lives back together more times than they care to count. What is new is the speed with which the same neighborhoods are being asked to rebuild again, sometimes twice in a single decade. Insurance maps are being redrawn quietly, premiums in flagged zones have doubled in five years, and the cost of staying is no longer just measured in lumber and shingles."

The author''s primary purpose in writing this passage is to:', '["celebrate the resilience of coastal towns","raise concern about rising costs and risks of coastal rebuilding","explain how insurance maps are technically constructed","argue that coastal communities should be abandoned immediately"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author pivots on "What is new is the speed" and notes that "the cost of staying is no longer just measured in lumber and shingles," which signals worry about a shifting situation. Choice B captures that concern. Choice A picks up the opening line about rebuilding but misses the warning that follows. Choice C invents a technical explanation the passage does not provide, since insurance maps are mentioned only as evidence. Choice D overshoots into a call for abandonment the author never makes, since the passage raises stakes without prescribing exit.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The latest software update promises faster load times, sharper graphics, and a redesigned interface that the company describes as a complete rethink of the workflow. Reviewers have been quick to call it a leap forward, and early demo videos have circulated widely. The benchmarks the company released cover load times and rendering speed, both of which are genuinely improved. Whether the new interface actually helps users finish tasks any faster is a separate question, and one the company has not chosen to answer with data."

The author''s attitude toward the update is best described as:', '["openly cynical","skeptical","appreciative","indifferent"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author reports the marketing claims, notes the reviewer praise, then isolates a missing piece: "a separate question, and one the company has not chosen to answer with data." That targeted doubt is skepticism. Choice B names it. Choice A overshoots into cynicism, which would imply the author assumes bad faith rather than asking for evidence. Choice C reverses the position by treating the author as approving, when the closing sentence withholds approval. Choice D ignores the pointed final clause, which is the opposite of disengaged.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The old library building is not beautiful in any conventional sense. Its bricks are dark, its windows are narrow, and the front steps slope at an angle no architect would defend today. But generations have walked those steps to find books they could not afford anywhere else, and that history sits in the walls more firmly than any renovation could."

The author''s attitude toward the library is best described as:', '["admiring","appreciative","sentimental and uncritical","professionally detached"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author acknowledges the building''s flaws plainly: "not beautiful," "dark," "narrow," "slope at an angle no architect would defend." The warmth arrives only in the closing pivot to what the building has meant for readers. That balance is appreciation, valuing the function and history without praising the form. Choice B fits. Choice A overshoots into admiration, which would treat the building itself as worthy of praise. Choice C drops the author''s frank critique of the architecture. Choice D ignores the personal closing line about generations of readers.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The committee''s report concludes that the program has, on the whole, met its stated objectives. A closer reading of the appendix shows that two of those objectives were revised downward halfway through the review period. The remaining metrics are real, and the gains they describe are real, even if the bar they cleared is lower than the one originally set."

The author would most likely agree with which statement?', '["The program is a clear success and the report should be accepted as written.","The program produced genuine gains, but the report''s headline claim overstates the result.","The program failed on every measure and the committee is hiding the truth.","The program''s metrics are unimportant and should be ignored entirely."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author validates part of the report by calling "the gains they describe" real, then flags that "two of those objectives were revised downward" and the "bar they cleared is lower than the one originally set." That is partial credit plus a caveat about the headline. Choice B captures both. Choice A drops the caveat the author insists on. Choice C escalates a calibration concern into total failure and concealment, which the passage does not support. Choice D dismisses the metrics the author explicitly affirms as real.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Critics of the new arts grant point out, fairly, that the selection process favored applicants from a small number of established institutions. The committee has acknowledged the imbalance and promised changes for next cycle. None of that erases the fact that the funded projects, judged on their own merits, are among the strongest the program has produced in a decade."

The author''s position is best described as:', '["fully defending the grant process against any criticism","rejecting the funded projects because of the flawed process","acknowledging the process flaw while still affirming the quality of the results","refusing to take any position on the outcome"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The author concedes the critique with "point out, fairly" and notes the committee''s promised changes, then pivots with "None of that erases the fact" to defend the projects on quality. That two-part move is precisely a process concession plus a results endorsement. Choice C names it. Choice A drops the concession the author openly makes. Choice B drops the endorsement the author insists on with "strongest the program has produced in a decade." Choice D ignores the clear final position, since the author commits to a verdict rather than hedging.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'The Hoover Dam was completed in 1936 after five years of continuous construction. Located on the border between Nevada and Arizona, it stands 726 feet tall. The dam created Lake Mead, which is the largest reservoir in the United States by volume. During its construction, more than 21,000 workers were employed, and 96 of them died on the job. The dam generates approximately four billion kilowatt-hours of electricity each year, serving customers in three states. Originally called the Boulder Dam, it was renamed in 1947 to honor President Herbert Hoover, who had championed the project while serving as Secretary of Commerce.

According to the passage, in what year was the Hoover Dam completed?', '["1931","1936","1947","1921"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The first sentence states, "The Hoover Dam was completed in 1936 after five years of continuous construction." Choice 1931 reflects when construction began (five years before 1936) but is not the completion year, an off-by-one trap on the five-year span. Choice 1947 is when the dam was renamed to honor Hoover, not when it was completed; it is a correct-but-wrong-question trap pulled from the closing sentence. Choice 1921 has no support in the passage; it is a plausible-looking distant date with no anchor in the text. Only 1936 directly matches the topic sentence and the completion question.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'Honeybees communicate the location of food sources through a behavior called the waggle dance. A returning forager performs the dance on the vertical surface of the honeycomb, using a figure-eight pattern. The angle of the straight portion of the dance relative to vertical indicates the direction of the food source relative to the sun. The duration of the waggle phase signals the distance to the source. Karl von Frisch first decoded this behavior in the 1940s, work that earned him a Nobel Prize in 1973. Researchers have since confirmed that bees adjust the dance to account for the sun''s movement across the sky.

According to the passage, what is the name of the behavior bees use to communicate food location?', '["The figure-eight signal","The waggle dance","The forager pattern","The honeycomb dance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The opening sentence reads, "Honeybees communicate the location of food sources through a behavior called the waggle dance." Choice "figure-eight signal" describes the dance''s shape but is not its name. Choice "forager pattern" combines two real words from the passage (forager, pattern) into a label the passage never uses. Choice "honeycomb dance" trades on the location of the dance (the honeycomb) but is not what the behavior is called. Only "waggle dance" appears as the explicit name.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'Solar panels convert sunlight directly into electricity using photovoltaic cells made primarily of silicon. The cells contain two layers of silicon that have been treated with different chemicals to give one layer a positive charge and the other a negative charge. When photons from sunlight strike the cells, they knock electrons loose, creating a flow of current. A single residential solar panel typically produces between 250 and 400 watts of power under ideal conditions. Most home installations use 20 to 30 panels arranged on a roof. The first practical silicon solar cell was developed at Bell Labs in 1954.

According to the passage, what material are photovoltaic cells primarily made of?', '["Copper","Silicon","Aluminum","Carbon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The opening sentence states cells are "made primarily of silicon." Copper is a common electrical material but the passage never mentions it; it is a plausible-sounding contradiction that readers might guess for anything electrical. Aluminum is similarly never named; it is a swap with another common conductor used in real-world wiring. Carbon is mentioned nowhere; it is included as a plausible chemistry-sounding distractor because of its broad role in materials science. Only silicon appears in the topic sentence as the primary material making up photovoltaic cells, so it is the single supported answer.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'The Pony Express was a mail delivery service that operated from April 1860 to October 1861. It used a relay of riders on horseback to carry letters between St. Joseph, Missouri, and Sacramento, California. The route covered approximately 1,900 miles and was usually completed in about 10 days. Riders changed horses every 10 to 15 miles at stations along the route, and they changed riders every 75 to 100 miles. The service ended just two days after the transcontinental telegraph line was completed, making the slower mail relay obsolete. Despite its short life, the Pony Express became a lasting symbol of the American West.

According to the passage, when did the Pony Express begin operating?', '["October 1860","April 1861","April 1860","October 1861"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The opening sentence states the service "operated from April 1860 to October 1861," identifying April 1860 as the start date. Choice October 1860 is a swap of the end-of-service month into the start year, a deliberately mixed pair. Choice April 1861 is a swap of the start month into the end year, the mirror image of the previous trap. Choice October 1861 is the date the service ended, not when it began, a correct-but-wrong-question trap. Only April 1860 matches the start date given explicitly in the topic sentence of the passage.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Coffee plants thrive in a narrow band of climates near the equator known as the bean belt. Brazil leads the world in coffee production, growing roughly one-third of the global supply. The two commercially important species are arabica and robusta. Arabica beans, prized for their smoother flavor, account for about 60 percent of world production but require cooler temperatures and higher elevations. Robusta plants tolerate heat and lower altitudes, and they contain nearly twice the caffeine of arabica. Most premium specialty coffees are arabica. Vietnam is the largest producer of robusta, while Colombia specializes almost entirely in arabica.

According to the passage, which country is the largest producer of robusta coffee?', '["Brazil","Colombia","Vietnam","Ethiopia"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Near the end the passage states, "Vietnam is the largest producer of robusta." Brazil leads in overall coffee production at roughly one-third of global supply, not specifically robusta, so it is a correct-but-wrong-question trap that confuses overall leadership with category leadership. Colombia specializes almost entirely in arabica, the opposite species, making it a plausible swap of roles between the two named producers. Ethiopia is never mentioned and is included as a coffee-knowledge distractor since it is widely associated with coffee origins. Only Vietnam is explicitly tied to robusta leadership in the passage.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'The human skeleton contains 206 bones in adulthood, but newborns are born with about 270. The difference is explained by the fusion of bones during growth, especially in the skull and spine. The longest bone in the body is the femur, located in the thigh, while the smallest is the stapes, found in the middle ear and measuring only about three millimeters. Bones serve several functions, including supporting the body, protecting organs, producing blood cells inside the marrow, and storing minerals such as calcium. Roughly half of all bones in the adult skeleton are located in the hands and feet.

According to the passage, what is the smallest bone in the human body?', '["The femur","The stapes","A bone in the spine","A bone in the hand"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The middle of the passage states, "the smallest is the stapes, found in the middle ear." The femur is named as the longest bone, not the smallest, making it a swap-of-roles trap. "A bone in the spine" plays on the fusion detail mentioned earlier but the passage never names any spine bone as smallest. "A bone in the hand" exploits the closing detail that half of all bones are in hands and feet, an over-generalization. Only the stapes is identified as smallest.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Workplace ergonomics is the science of designing tasks and tools to fit the worker rather than forcing the worker to adapt. A properly configured office workstation places the top of the monitor at eye level, with the screen about an arm''s length away. Chairs should support the lower back, and feet should rest flat on the floor or on a footrest. The keyboard should be positioned so that the elbows form roughly a 90-degree angle. Studies by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration show that ergonomic improvements can reduce repetitive strain injuries by up to 60 percent. Frequent short breaks further reduce fatigue.

According to the passage, where should the top of a computer monitor be positioned?', '["At chin level","At eye level","Slightly above eye level","An arm''s length below eye level"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states, "the top of the monitor at eye level, with the screen about an arm''s length away." "Chin level" is a plausible-sounding contradiction not in the text. "Slightly above eye level" is the kind of detail readers may guess but the passage gives exactly "at eye level," not above it. "An arm''s length below eye level" mashes together two true details (an arm''s length away, eye level) into a false position. Only "at eye level" matches the passage.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Hurricanes are tropical storms that form over warm ocean waters near the equator. To be classified as a hurricane, a storm must produce sustained winds of at least 74 miles per hour. Storms are ranked on the Saffir-Simpson scale, which assigns a category from 1 through 5 based on wind speed. A Category 1 hurricane has winds between 74 and 95 miles per hour, while a Category 5 has sustained winds above 157 miles per hour. The Atlantic hurricane season officially runs from June 1 through November 30, with peak activity typically occurring in mid-September. Hurricanes are called typhoons in the western Pacific.

According to the passage, what is the minimum sustained wind speed for a storm to be classified as a hurricane?', '["95 miles per hour","157 miles per hour","74 miles per hour","60 miles per hour"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage states a storm "must produce sustained winds of at least 74 miles per hour" to be classified as a hurricane. 95 mph is the upper bound of Category 1 on the Saffir-Simpson scale, a correct-but-wrong-question trap pulled from the middle of the passage. 157 mph is the threshold for Category 5, the most severe rating, and represents the opposite extreme of the scale rather than the minimum. 60 mph is a plausible-sounding wind speed for tropical storms but the passage never gives that figure. Only 74 mph matches the stated minimum hurricane classification threshold.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'The Apollo program landed twelve astronauts on the Moon between 1969 and 1972 across six successful missions. Apollo 11, in July 1969, made the first landing, with Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin walking on the surface while Michael Collins remained in orbit. The final mission, Apollo 17, in December 1972, included geologist Harrison Schmitt, the only trained scientist to walk on the Moon. Apollo 13, in April 1970, was intended to land but suffered an oxygen tank explosion and looped around the Moon without landing. The Apollo astronauts collectively returned 842 pounds of lunar samples to Earth.

According to the passage, who was the only trained scientist to walk on the Moon?', '["Neil Armstrong","Buzz Aldrin","Michael Collins","Harrison Schmitt"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage states, "Apollo 17, in December 1972, included geologist Harrison Schmitt, the only trained scientist to walk on the Moon." Armstrong and Aldrin are named as the first to walk on the Moon during Apollo 11, but neither is described as a trained scientist. Collins is named as the Apollo 11 astronaut who remained in orbit and never walked on the surface at all. Among four named astronauts, only Schmitt is explicitly identified as the trained scientist.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'Vaccines work by training the immune system to recognize specific pathogens without causing the disease itself. Live attenuated vaccines, such as the one for measles, use a weakened form of the virus. Inactivated vaccines, like the standard flu shot, use a killed version of the pathogen. Subunit vaccines, such as the one for hepatitis B, contain only specific pieces of the pathogen rather than the whole microbe. mRNA vaccines, used against COVID-19, give cells instructions to produce a harmless piece of the virus to trigger an immune response. Each approach has trade-offs in storage requirements, manufacturing speed, and how long protection lasts.

According to the passage, which type of vaccine is the standard flu shot?', '["Live attenuated","Inactivated","Subunit","mRNA"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states, "Inactivated vaccines, like the standard flu shot, use a killed version of the pathogen." Live attenuated is the category given for the measles vaccine, a correct-but-wrong-question trap among the four types listed. Subunit is the category for hepatitis B, not the flu shot. mRNA is the technology used against COVID-19. Each wrong choice is a real vaccine category from the passage but is tied there to a different disease, not to the flu shot.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'Plate tectonics describes how Earth''s outer shell is divided into roughly a dozen large pieces called plates that move slowly over the planet''s mantle. The plates interact in three main ways. At convergent boundaries, plates collide, sometimes pushing one plate beneath the other in a process called subduction. The Andes Mountains formed this way. At divergent boundaries, plates pull apart, allowing magma to rise and create new crust, as in the Mid-Atlantic Ridge. At transform boundaries, plates slide past each other horizontally, generating frequent earthquakes; California''s San Andreas Fault is the best-known example. Average plate movement is about two to four inches per year.

According to the passage, the Andes Mountains formed at what type of plate boundary?', '["Divergent","Transform","Convergent","Subduction"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage states, "At convergent boundaries, plates collide... The Andes Mountains formed this way." Divergent boundaries are tied to the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, not the Andes. Transform boundaries are tied to the San Andreas Fault and frequent earthquakes, not mountain building. "Subduction" is mentioned in the passage as a process that can occur at convergent boundaries, but it is not itself a type of boundary; it is an over-generalization of a sub-detail. Only convergent matches the boundary type for the Andes.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'OSHA reporting rules require employers to record any work-related injury that meets specific criteria. A case must be logged if it results in death, days away from work, restricted work activity, transfer to another job, loss of consciousness, or a significant injury diagnosed by a licensed health-care professional. Minor cuts treated with a bandage and standard first aid do not have to be recorded. Employers must also report serious incidents directly to OSHA within set time limits: any fatality within 8 hours and any inpatient hospitalization, amputation, or loss of an eye within 24 hours. Records must be retained for five years.

According to the passage, within how many hours must an employer report a work-related fatality to OSHA?', '["24 hours","8 hours","5 hours","48 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states, "any fatality within 8 hours and any inpatient hospitalization, amputation, or loss of an eye within 24 hours." 24 hours is the deadline for hospitalizations, amputations, and eye loss, a correct-but-wrong-question trap that swaps the two reporting windows. 5 hours echoes the "five years" retention period reshaped from years into hours; no such 5-hour rule exists in the passage. 48 hours is a plausible-sounding compliance window often associated with regulatory deadlines but is never mentioned in this text. Only 8 hours matches the fatality-reporting deadline stated explicitly.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 4, 'The Great Barrier Reef, located off the northeastern coast of Australia, is the largest coral reef system in the world. It stretches more than 1,400 miles and is composed of nearly 3,000 individual reefs and 900 islands. The reef supports over 1,500 species of fish, 400 species of coral, and 4,000 types of mollusks. It is visible from space and was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1981. Climate change, agricultural runoff, and crown-of-thorns starfish are the main threats to its survival. Mass coral bleaching events occurred in 2016, 2017, 2020, and 2022.

Which of the following is NOT mentioned in the passage as a threat to the Great Barrier Reef?', '["Climate change","Agricultural runoff","Crown-of-thorns starfish","Commercial fishing"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage lists "Climate change, agricultural runoff, and crown-of-thorns starfish" as the main threats to the reef. Climate change is explicitly named as a main threat, so it does appear. Agricultural runoff is explicitly named in the same sentence and likewise appears. Crown-of-thorns starfish is explicitly named alongside the other two, also appearing in the text. Commercial fishing sounds like a plausible reef threat that readers may guess from outside knowledge, but it never appears in this passage, making it the only option not mentioned and therefore the correct answer to a NOT-mentioned question.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 4, 'A standard home electrical panel in the United States distributes 240-volt service through a series of circuit breakers. Most lighting and outlet circuits operate on 15-amp or 20-amp breakers at 120 volts. Larger appliances draw 240 volts: electric dryers typically use 30-amp breakers, electric ranges use 40-amp or 50-amp breakers, and central air-conditioning condensers use 30-amp or 40-amp breakers. Each breaker is designed to trip when current exceeds its rating, preventing wires from overheating. Modern code also requires ground-fault circuit interrupters in bathrooms, kitchens, garages, and outdoor outlets, and arc-fault interrupters in bedrooms.

Which of the following appliances is NOT mentioned in the passage?', '["Electric dryer","Electric range","Central air-conditioning condenser","Electric water heater"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage names three specific appliances drawing 240 volts: "electric dryers typically use 30-amp breakers, electric ranges use 40-amp or 50-amp breakers, and central air-conditioning condensers use 30-amp or 40-amp breakers." Electric dryer is mentioned by name with its breaker rating. Electric range is mentioned with its breaker rating. Central air-conditioning condenser is mentioned with its breaker rating. Electric water heaters are a real 240-volt appliance and sound plausible to a reader bringing outside knowledge, but they never appear in this passage, making them the only choice not mentioned in the text.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-15', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 4, 'A balanced diet recommended by the U.S. Dietary Guidelines includes five food groups: fruits, vegetables, grains, protein foods, and dairy. Fruits and vegetables should fill roughly half of each plate. At least half of grain servings should be whole grains rather than refined grains. Protein foods include lean meats, poultry, eggs, seafood, beans, peas, nuts, and soy products. Dairy options include milk, yogurt, cheese, and fortified soy beverages. The guidelines also recommend limiting added sugars to less than 10 percent of daily calories, saturated fats to less than 10 percent of daily calories, and sodium to less than 2,300 milligrams per day.

Which of the following is NOT listed in the passage as one of the five food groups?', '["Vegetables","Grains","Fats","Dairy"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage names "fruits, vegetables, grains, protein foods, and dairy" as the five food groups in the U.S. Dietary Guidelines. Vegetables is explicitly named in that list. Grains is explicitly named in that list. Dairy is explicitly named in that list. Fats are discussed only as something to limit, with saturated fats specifically capped at less than 10 percent of daily calories, and they are never listed as a food group. Fats is therefore the only option not in the five-group list, making it the correct answer to the NOT-listed question.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-16', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'A small business tracks its monthly utility bills to budget for the year. In January, electricity costs were $420 and natural gas was $310. By July, electricity had risen to $680 due to air-conditioning demand, while natural gas had fallen to $90. Water charges remained steady at about $75 per month throughout the year. Internet and phone service together cost $185 per month on a flat plan. The owner noticed that combined utility expenses in July exceeded combined utility expenses in January, even though heating costs had dropped substantially during the warmer months.

Based on the passage, by approximately how much did the company''s combined utility bill increase from January to July?', '["$30","$220","$260","$170"]'::jsonb, 0, 'January totals: $420 + $310 + $75 + $185 = $990. July totals: $680 + $90 + $75 + $185 = $1,030. The increase is $1,030 minus $990, which equals $40, closest to $30 among the choices. $260 reflects only the electricity rise ($680 minus $420). $220 over-counts by mixing electricity and gas changes in one direction. $170 conflates partial swings. Only $30 approximates the true net change once gas savings offset most of the electricity increase.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-17', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'A regional hospital reports its emergency department traffic each quarter. In the first quarter, the department treated 4,200 patients, with an average wait time of 38 minutes. In the second quarter, patient volume rose to 5,100 and average wait time stretched to 52 minutes. The third quarter saw 5,400 patients with a wait time of 49 minutes after two additional triage nurses were hired in late June. In the fourth quarter, holiday-related cases pushed volume to 5,800, but wait times held at 50 minutes thanks to the staffing change. Administrators consider any quarter with average wait under 45 minutes a success.

Based on the passage, how many quarters met the administrators'' success criterion?', '["Zero","One","Two","Three"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Success requires average wait under 45 minutes. Q1 wait is 38 minutes, which meets the criterion. Q2 is 52 minutes, which fails. Q3 is 49 minutes, which still fails despite improvement after the triage hires. Q4 is 50 minutes, which also fails. Only one quarter meets the standard. "Zero" overlooks Q1, the lowest wait time in the year. "Two" likely arises from mistakenly treating Q3''s near-45 figure as passing the threshold. "Three" assumes most quarters succeeded, the opposite of what the recorded numbers actually show.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-18', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'A community library tracks book checkouts by category. Fiction accounts for about 45 percent of all checkouts, biography for 15 percent, science and technology for 12 percent, children''s books for 20 percent, and reference for the remainder. In the most recent year, the library logged 60,000 total checkouts. Staff have noticed that biography circulation has roughly doubled since a popular streaming documentary series launched two years ago. The library plans to expand its biography collection if the category exceeds 10,000 annual checkouts in the coming year.

Based on the passage, approximately how many biography checkouts did the library record in the most recent year?', '["6,000","9,000","12,000","10,000"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Biography is stated as 15 percent of 60,000 total checkouts. Computing 15 percent of 60,000 gives 9,000 biography checkouts in the most recent year. 6,000 corresponds to 10 percent and would match the lower-end share but contradicts the stated 15 percent figure for biography. 12,000 corresponds to 20 percent, which is the figure given for children''s books, a correct-but-wrong-question swap between two categories. 10,000 is the trigger number for collection expansion in the coming year, not the current biography total. Only 9,000 is consistent with the stated 15 percent share.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Honeybees navigate using polarized sunlight, even on cloudy days when humans see only diffuse gray sky overhead. Their compound eyes contain specialized receptors that detect the orientation of light waves passing through the atmosphere. When researchers covered hive entrances with polarizing filters that scrambled the natural light pattern, foragers returning from familiar feeding sites became visibly disoriented and circled the hive for extended periods before they could land.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Honeybees rely on detecting polarized light patterns to orient themselves","Honeybees cannot see at all when the sky is cloudy","Honeybees have compound eyes with specialized receptors","Honeybees produce more honey on sunny days than on cloudy days"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage states bees use polarized light for navigation and that scrambling that pattern disoriented even experienced foragers, which directly supports choice A as a one-step inference from cause and effect. Choice B contradicts the passage, which explicitly says bees navigate even on cloudy days when humans see only gray. Choice C is the under-reach trap, restating an explicit detail about receptors without drawing any inference from it. Choice D is off-topic; honey production is never mentioned anywhere in the passage. Choice A is the cleanest one-step read of the evidence.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Concrete poured in freezing weather can fail catastrophically. Water in the wet mix expands as it crystallizes into ice, creating internal pressure that fractures the curing matrix before the cement can develop strength. Contractors working in cold climates use heated enclosures, insulated blankets, or chemical accelerators to keep concrete above 40 degrees Fahrenheit during the first 24 hours after pouring.

Based on the passage, which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["The first day after pouring is the most vulnerable period for concrete in cold conditions","Concrete poured in summer never develops any structural defects","Chemical accelerators are more effective than insulated blankets","Heated enclosures are required by building codes in every cold region"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage specifies that protective measures target the first 24 hours after pouring, which implies that window is when freezing damage is most likely to occur. Choice A captures this one-step inference cleanly. Choice B over-reaches; the passage focuses on cold weather and never claims summer concrete is defect-free. Choice C over-reaches by ranking effectiveness among methods the passage merely lists side by side. Choice D over-reaches by inferring a legal mandate from a description of common practice. The 24-hour detail points clearly to choice A.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Sourdough bread relies on wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria that live in the flour and surrounding air. Unlike commercial baker''s yeast, which produces consistent rise times, wild cultures vary in activity depending on temperature, humidity, and the specific strains present in a kitchen. Two bakers using identical recipes in different homes will often produce loaves with noticeably different textures and flavors.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Environmental conditions affect the outcome of sourdough baking","Commercial baker''s yeast produces better-tasting bread than wild yeast","Lactic acid bacteria are harmful to people who eat sourdough","Professional bakers always control humidity in their kitchens"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage explicitly ties variation in texture and flavor to differences in temperature, humidity, and local strains across kitchens, which supports choice A as a direct one-step inference. Choice B over-reaches by introducing a quality judgment the passage never makes; consistency is mentioned, not superiority. Choice C contradicts the implication that these bacteria are a normal and expected part of sourdough fermentation. Choice D over-reaches by inferring professional behavior from a passage that only describes home bakers using identical recipes. Choice A is the cleanest read.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Modern wind turbines automatically pitch their blades to limit rotation speed during high winds. If a blade caught the full force of a gust without adjusting, centrifugal stress could rip it from the hub. The pitch control system rotates each blade along its long axis, reducing the effective angle that strikes the wind and slowing the rotor before damage occurs.

The passage suggests that pitch control primarily exists to:', '["Protect turbine components from wind-induced mechanical failure","Increase electricity output during periods of low wind","Reduce noise complaints from nearby residents","Allow turbines to operate without any electronic monitoring"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage describes pitch control as a response to dangerous high winds that would otherwise generate centrifugal stress capable of tearing blades from the hub, which supports choice A directly. Choice B contradicts the passage, which describes the system slowing rotation rather than boosting output during low wind. Choice C is off-topic; noise complaints are never mentioned anywhere in the text. Choice D contradicts the implication of an automatic system, which requires monitoring of wind conditions to function. Protection from mechanical failure is the clearest single-step inference.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Lithium-ion batteries lose capacity faster when stored at full charge in warm conditions. A battery held at 100 percent in a hot garage may lose 35 percent of its original capacity within a year, while the same battery kept at 50 percent charge in a cool basement might lose only 4 percent over the same period. Manufacturers therefore recommend storing rarely used devices at moderate charge levels in temperature-controlled spaces.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Storing a laptop fully charged in a warm closet accelerates battery degradation","Lithium-ion batteries last longer than nickel-cadmium batteries","Cool temperatures alone are enough to prevent any capacity loss","Manufacturers recommend never charging a battery above 50 percent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Choice A combines two stated conditions, full charge plus warm storage, to draw a specific applied inference about a laptop in a warm closet, which is the textbook two-step pattern this difficulty level expects. Choice B is off-topic; no other battery chemistry is mentioned for comparison. Choice C over-reaches by inferring complete prevention when the passage shows only reduced loss at four percent rather than zero. Choice D over-reaches by turning a storage recommendation into a charging prohibition; the passage addresses rarely used devices, not daily use.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'City planners studying foot traffic found that pedestrians overwhelmingly prefer routes with continuous shade during summer months. On one downtown corridor, a sidewalk lined with mature oak trees carried four times the foot traffic of a parallel route two blocks away, even though the shaded path added roughly 90 seconds to most trips. After the city removed several diseased oaks, monthly counts on the shaded corridor fell sharply.

Based on the passage, which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Pedestrians will accept modestly longer walks in exchange for shade","Oak trees are the only tree species that attract foot traffic","Removing trees has no measurable effect on pedestrian behavior","Most pedestrians avoid downtown areas during summer entirely"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage states that pedestrians chose the shaded route despite the added 90 seconds and that traffic dropped sharply when trees were removed. Combining these two facts supports choice A as a two-step inference about preference and trade-off. Choice B over-reaches; oaks are the specific example used, not a stated species requirement for foot traffic. Choice C directly contradicts the passage, which explicitly describes a sharp drop after tree removal. Choice D contradicts the high four-times traffic count on the shaded corridor in summer.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Most small claims courts cap awards at amounts between 5,000 and 25,000 dollars depending on the state. Filing fees usually run under 100 dollars, and parties typically argue their own cases without attorneys. Judges aim to resolve disputes within a single brief hearing, often the same morning multiple cases are scheduled. Plaintiffs seeking larger awards or complex remedies must use higher courts, which involve formal procedure and significantly greater expense.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Small claims courts are designed to handle low-value disputes quickly and affordably","Small claims court hearings always last several days","Hiring an attorney is prohibited in small claims court","Higher courts award smaller damages than small claims courts"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Choice A integrates the dollar caps, low filing fees, and same-morning hearing format into a coherent two-step inference about the court''s purpose and design. Choice B directly contradicts the same-morning brief-hearing detail given in the passage. Choice C over-reaches; the passage says parties typically self-represent, which describes practice rather than a legal prohibition on hiring attorneys. Choice D contradicts the passage, which states explicitly that larger awards require moving up to higher courts. Choice A is the synthesis the passage clearly invites a reader to draw.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Coral reefs form only in clear tropical seawater between roughly 73 and 84 degrees Fahrenheit. The animals that build reefs depend on symbiotic algae that photosynthesize inside their tissues, so cloudy water blocks the light those algae need. When ocean temperatures climb above 86 degrees for sustained periods, the corals expel their algal partners and turn white, a condition called bleaching that often kills the colony.

Which conclusion does the passage most strongly support?', '["Reef survival depends on water that is both warm enough and clear enough","Bleached corals always recover if temperatures fall the following week","Tropical seawater never exceeds 86 degrees Fahrenheit","Algae can photosynthesize without any access to sunlight"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage gives a narrow temperature range and a separate clarity requirement, both presented as essential, which supports choice A as a two-fact synthesis about reef-building conditions. Choice B over-reaches with the word always; the passage says bleaching often kills colonies, suggesting recovery is far from guaranteed. Choice C directly contradicts the passage, which describes temperatures climbing above 86 degrees and triggering bleaching. Choice D contradicts the explicit role of light in algal photosynthesis described in the same sentence. Choice A is the disciplined inference.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Cooking shows that emphasize speed and convenience above all else have shaped a generation of home cooks who panic when a recipe calls for resting dough overnight or simmering stock for hours. We have come to treat any process longer than 30 minutes as a failure of efficiency, as if our grandparents wasted their lives by braising. The richest flavors in any tradition arise from patience, and a kitchen that cannot wait is a kitchen that cannot taste.

Which statement does the author most likely believe?', '["Modern media has trained cooks to undervalue time-intensive techniques","Cooking shows should be banned from television","Older generations cooked exclusively with slow methods","Resting dough overnight is the only worthwhile technique"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author''s frustration with speed-focused shows, the rhetorical question about grandparents, and the closing line about waiting and tasting reveal an implicit assumption that modern media has narrowed cooks'' patience for slow technique, which supports choice A. Choice B over-reaches; the author criticizes a trend in programming, not the existence of cooking shows themselves. Choice C over-reaches with the word exclusively, which the passage never claims. Choice D over-reaches by treating a single example of slow technique as the only valued one. Choice A captures the implicit position.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Volunteer firefighting departments in rural counties face a recruitment crisis that no amount of equipment funding can solve. Trucks and gear sit unused not because budgets are tight but because fewer working-age residents remain in these communities, and those who stay often commute too far to respond during daylight hours. Until lawmakers grapple with rural depopulation itself, even generous grants will leave stations short-handed at the moments they matter most.

The passage suggests that the author believes:', '["Equipment grants alone cannot fix what is fundamentally a population problem","Volunteer firefighting is no longer a useful model anywhere","Rural residents are unwilling to volunteer for any community service","Lawmakers have already solved the rural depopulation problem"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author treats funding as misdirected because the root cause is demographic rather than financial, an implicit assumption clearly visible in the contrast between budgets and bodies, which supports choice A. Choice B over-reaches; the author critiques the recruitment shortfall in rural areas, not the volunteer model itself or its use elsewhere. Choice C over-reaches by attributing unwillingness when the passage explicitly cites commuting distance and population loss as the cause. Choice D directly contradicts the passage''s call for lawmakers to begin grappling with the issue.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Public libraries that once defined themselves by their book collections have spent the last decade quietly transforming into community workspaces. Patrons now book private rooms for video interviews, borrow laptop chargers, and use 3D printers as often as they check out novels. Some librarians worry that calling these institutions libraries at all may eventually mislead the public about what they actually offer.

The author would most likely agree that:', '["The traditional definition of a library no longer captures the full range of services offered","Libraries should immediately remove all books from their buildings","Patrons who still read novels are an obstacle to library modernization","Library budgets have grown substantially over the last decade"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage describes a transformation and quotes librarians worried about an outdated name, which together reveal an implicit assumption that the old definition is becoming inadequate, supporting choice A. Choice B over-reaches; the passage describes evolution alongside continued book lending, not the removal of books. Choice C contradicts the neutral tone toward novel-borrowing patrons, who appear in the same sentence as 3D printer users without judgment. Choice D is off-topic; library budgets are never discussed anywhere in the passage. Choice A captures the implicit position about naming and identity.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Manufacturers of premium kitchen knives have begun stamping serial numbers on every blade and offering lifetime warranties tied to the original purchaser. Marketing materials describe these moves as quality assurance, but the practice also makes it harder for buyers to resell knives privately and easier for makers to track which retailers discount their inventory. Consumer advocates have started questioning whose interests these programs really serve.

Which statement does the author most likely believe?', '["Lifetime warranty programs may benefit manufacturers more than buyers","Premium kitchen knives are not worth their listed price","Serial numbers always lower the quality of finished blades","Consumer advocates have proven that all warranty programs are fraudulent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author juxtaposes marketing claims about quality assurance with practical effects that constrain resale and police retailers, an implicit assumption that buyers are not the primary beneficiary of these programs, which supports choice A. Choice B is off-topic; the price-to-value question is never argued or even raised in the passage. Choice C over-reaches by inventing a link between serial numbers and product quality that the passage does not make. Choice D over-reaches; the passage says advocates have started questioning, not that they have proven anything fraudulent.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'A study of urban bicycle commuters found that those who wore high-visibility yellow vests reported feeling safer than those who did not, even though crash data from the same period showed no statistically significant difference in collision rates between the two groups. Researchers cautioned that perceived safety and actual safety can diverge in ways that affect behavior, including how aggressively riders position themselves in traffic.

Which conclusion is best supported by the passage?', '["The perception of being safer does not necessarily reflect actual reductions in crash risk","Yellow vests cause more bicycle collisions than they prevent","Bicycle commuters should stop wearing high-visibility gear","All safety equipment is purely psychological in effect"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage cleanly distinguishes self-reported feelings from crash data and warns explicitly about divergence between perceived and actual safety, which supports choice A without any unsupported leaps. Choice B over-reaches; the data showed no significant difference between groups, not that vests caused additional crashes. Choice C is an unsupported recommendation; the passage offers cautious analysis rather than any prescription for riders. Choice D is the inference-overreach trap, generalizing from one specific finding about vests to a sweeping claim about all safety equipment. Choice A stops exactly where the evidence stops.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Researchers analyzing customer reviews on a major online retailer noticed that products with average ratings between 4.2 and 4.5 stars tended to outsell products rated 4.8 or higher. Interviews with shoppers suggested that perfect or near-perfect ratings raised suspicion of manipulation, while slightly imperfect ratings struck buyers as more credible. The retailer has not announced any plans to change how ratings are displayed.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Shoppers may interpret slightly imperfect ratings as a signal of authenticity","Ratings above 4.5 stars are always the result of manipulation","The retailer is planning to hide perfect ratings from buyers","Customer reviews have no influence on online purchasing decisions"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Shopper interviews tied buyer suspicion to near-perfect ratings and credibility to slightly imperfect ones, which supports choice A as a careful inference about how buyers read review patterns. Choice B is the over-reach trap, converting a buyer perception into a factual claim that high ratings are manipulated. Choice C directly contradicts the explicit statement that the retailer has announced no display changes. Choice D contradicts the passage, which shows ratings clearly influence sales by linking specific rating ranges to outselling. Choice A stops at what the shoppers themselves report.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-15', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'A regional hospital system that switched from paper charts to a unified electronic medical record initially saw medication errors drop 22 percent. Three years later, however, error rates had crept back to within 4 percent of the original baseline. Quality officers attributed the rebound to alert fatigue, the phenomenon in which clinicians begin to ignore safety warnings after encountering too many false positives during routine work.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Technology gains in safety can erode when human responses to that technology change","Electronic medical records ultimately cause more errors than paper charts","Alert fatigue is unique to hospitals that recently switched systems","Reducing the number of safety alerts would eliminate medication errors entirely"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage describes an initial 22 percent gain that eroded as clinicians adapted to alerts, which supports choice A as a precise inference about behavior eroding technical benefits over time. Choice B over-reaches; error rates rebounded close to but not above the paper baseline, so the system did not cause more errors. Choice C over-reaches by claiming uniqueness the passage never asserts about this hospital system. Choice D over-reaches with the word entirely; the passage offers no guarantee that reducing alerts would eliminate every error. Choice A captures exactly what the rebound implies.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-16', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'A 12-year analysis of municipal recycling programs found that cities mandating clear plastic collection bags had higher reported recycling rates than cities using opaque bags, but landfill audits revealed that the clear-bag cities also threw away slightly more recyclable material in regular trash. Researchers theorized that residents avoided putting questionable items in transparent bags out of social embarrassment, preferring to discard them invisibly.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Visibility-based policies can shift where waste appears without changing total recycling behavior","Clear-bag policies cause residents to recycle more material overall","Opaque bag cities have eliminated recycling contamination","Social embarrassment is the strongest motivator of recycling behavior"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Higher reported rates paired with more recyclables found in landfill trash means visibility shifted disposal location without expanding total recycling, which supports choice A as the disciplined synthesis. Choice B is the almost-but-not-quite trap; higher reported rates initially look like more recycling, but the landfill audit cancels that gain by showing recyclables hidden in regular trash. Choice C over-reaches; opaque-bag cities are never described as contamination-free in the passage. Choice D over-reaches by elevating one researcher theory to the strongest motivator when the passage offers it tentatively. Choice A is the precise read.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-17', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'An evaluation of remote-work pilot programs across 14 large companies found that employees reporting the highest job satisfaction were those who worked remotely two or three days per week, not those who worked remotely full time. Fully remote employees often reported satisfaction comparable to fully in-office employees, but they were also significantly more likely to leave their employer within 18 months. Researchers suggested that satisfaction surveys may miss factors like weak peer attachment that influence retention.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Self-reported satisfaction may not fully capture the conditions that keep employees at a job","Fully remote employees are less satisfied than hybrid employees","Companies should require all employees to work in the office at least two days per week","Peer attachment is the only factor that predicts employee turnover"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Comparable satisfaction scores combined with significantly higher attrition imply that the survey instrument misses retention-relevant factors, which is exactly what choice A captures. Choice B is the almost-supported trap; hybrid employees did report the highest satisfaction, but the passage says fully remote workers were comparable to in-office, not lower in a way that proves dissatisfaction drove their exits. Choice C is an unsupported policy recommendation the passage never makes. Choice D over-reaches with only; the passage offers peer attachment as one factor researchers suggested might matter. Choice A respects every qualifier in the evidence.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Hand-washing is the single most effective way to prevent the spread of common illnesses. Soap breaks down the oils on skin that hold germs in place, allowing running water to rinse them away. Twenty seconds of scrubbing is enough to remove most contaminants. Public health agencies continue to promote this simple habit because no vaccine or medication matches its everyday impact. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Twenty seconds of scrubbing removes most contaminants from hands.","Soap dissolves oils that trap germs on the skin.","Public health depends entirely on individual hygiene habits.","Hand-washing is the most effective everyday way to prevent the spread of illness."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The first sentence states the thesis directly and the rest of the passage supports it with mechanism and endorsement. Choice B describes how soap works, a supporting detail, not the central claim. Choice C cites a specific scrubbing duration, again a detail in service of the main point. Choice D over-generalizes by claiming public health depends entirely on hygiene, a stronger claim than the passage makes. Only the keyed option restates the explicit topic sentence without adding or narrowing its scope.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'A library card offers more than free books. Most public libraries now lend audiobooks, streaming films, museum passes, and even hotspots for home internet. Cardholders can attend tax workshops, language classes, and resume clinics at no cost. The card has quietly become one of the most versatile free resources available to residents. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Public libraries are the most important institutions in any community.","Tax workshops and resume clinics are popular library offerings.","A library card gives access to a wide range of free resources beyond books.","Libraries lend internet hotspots to people without home service."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The opening sentence states that a card offers more than books, and the rest of the passage lists examples of that range plus the free-resource framing. Choice B isolates the internet-hotspot service, a single supporting detail. Choice C names two specific workshop programs from the example list, again narrower than the central claim. Choice D inflates the argument to call libraries the most important institutions, language the passage never uses and a clear over-generalization. The keyed option mirrors the opening sentence and captures the variety theme that ties the supporting details together.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Sleep is essential for memory consolidation. During deep sleep, the brain replays the day''s experiences and strengthens the neural connections tied to important information. People who sleep fewer than six hours a night routinely score lower on memory tests the next day. Adequate rest is not a luxury for students; it is part of the learning process itself. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Sleeping less than six hours lowers next-day memory test scores.","Students should treat sleep as more important than studying.","The brain replays daily experiences during deep sleep.","Adequate sleep is essential for forming and retaining memories."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The first sentence names sleep as essential for memory consolidation, and the closing sentence reinforces it by calling rest part of the learning process itself. Choice B reports a specific finding about test scores cited as supporting evidence rather than the central claim. Choice C describes the neural replay mechanism, another piece of supporting detail that explains why the thesis holds. Choice D over-generalizes by ranking sleep above studying, a direct comparison the passage does not make. The keyed answer captures the central claim that sleep and memory formation are tightly linked.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Recycling aluminum saves enormous amounts of energy. Producing a can from recycled aluminum uses about ninety-five percent less electricity than making one from raw ore. The metal can be melted and reformed indefinitely without losing any strength or quality. For every ton of aluminum recycled, the equivalent of several barrels of oil is conserved nationwide. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Recycled aluminum cans require ninety-five percent less electricity to produce.","Aluminum can be melted and reused without losing strength.","Recycling aluminum conserves a large amount of energy.","Industrial recycling could replace most oil production."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The opening sentence states the thesis about energy savings, and the rest of the passage quantifies and reinforces it with electricity figures and oil-equivalent conservation. Choice B is the specific ninety-five percent statistic offered as evidence, a supporting detail rather than the main idea. Choice C addresses the metal''s durability under repeated recycling, another supporting fact that explains why aluminum recycling is so efficient. Choice D wildly over-generalizes by suggesting industrial recycling could replace most oil production, a claim the passage never makes. The keyed option restates the topic sentence in plain terms.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'City planners in many regions are widening sidewalks, lowering speed limits, and adding shaded benches. Cars still dominate most corridors, but pedestrian counts on retrofitted blocks have climbed sharply. Shop owners along these streets report higher foot traffic and longer customer visits. Even short walks in better-designed neighborhoods correlate with improved cardiovascular health in older residents. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Shop owners earn more money when sidewalks are widened.","Older residents have better hearts than younger residents in walkable areas.","Cities should ban cars from downtown corridors.","Walkable street design produces measurable economic and health benefits."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage stacks two parallel results, business gains and health gains, after describing the design changes that produced them. The implied thesis ties pedestrian-friendly design to both outcomes, and it sits across the second and third sentences rather than in one place. Choice B captures only the commercial half and overstates with the word earn, a supporting detail. Choice C distorts the health claim into a generational comparison the passage never makes. Choice D pushes a car-ban policy position the passage avoids, since it explicitly notes cars still dominate most corridors. The keyed answer holds both supporting threads together.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'When a household water heater fails, the symptoms often appear gradually. Showers grow lukewarm over several weeks, and the tank may begin to hum or rattle as sediment builds. Rust-tinted water from the hot tap is a later warning sign. Homeowners who replace a failing unit on a planned schedule typically pay less than those who wait for a flood. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Rust-tinted hot water means a water heater has already failed.","Most water heaters last fewer than ten years before failing.","Sediment buildup is the leading cause of water-heater problems.","Recognizing early warning signs of water-heater failure helps homeowners avoid costly emergencies."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The first three sentences catalogue warning signs and the final sentence links advance recognition to lower cost, implying the thesis. Choice B treats one symptom as a definitive verdict, a misread of late warning sign. Choice C names sediment as the leading cause, a ranking the passage never asserts. Choice D introduces a lifespan figure that does not appear in the passage at all. The keyed answer joins the symptoms half to the cost half.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'A well-written cover letter does more than repeat a resume. It connects past experience to the specific role, names the hiring manager when possible, and uses the company''s own language about its goals. Recruiters often skim a stack of applications in seconds, so the opening lines must give them a reason to keep reading. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Cover letters should always name the hiring manager.","Recruiters spend only a few seconds reviewing each application.","A strong cover letter is tailored to the role and designed to hold a recruiter''s attention.","Resumes are less important than cover letters in modern hiring."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage outlines what a good cover letter does, namely connect experience to the role and mirror the company''s language, and then explains why, the recruiter-skim context. The thesis combines tailoring with attention-holding across the two halves of the paragraph. Choice B repeats the seconds-of-skim detail as if it were the central point, an isolated supporting fact. Choice C absolutizes one suggested practice with the word always, sliding past the passage''s softer when possible. Choice D invents a head-to-head comparison between resumes and cover letters that the passage never makes. The keyed option ties the writing advice to the audience constraint that drives it.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'Honey produced near a beekeeper''s home tastes different from honey produced fifty miles away. Local flora determine the flavor profile because bees forage within a few miles of the hive. Spring honey from orchard country carries a light apple-blossom note, while late-summer honey from a meadow tastes darker and fuller. Even neighboring counties can yield jars with distinct character. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Bees forage within a few miles of their hive.","Local honey is healthier than honey from distant regions.","Honey''s flavor reflects the specific plants bees forage near their hive.","Spring honey is lighter than late-summer honey."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage contrasts honey from different areas and explains the cause: nearby flora that the bees forage on. The thesis sits across the first two sentences and is then reinforced by the spring-versus-summer example. Choice B isolates the foraging range, a mechanism detail that supports rather than states the main idea. Choice C captures one seasonal contrast from the examples, again a piece of evidence rather than the central claim. Choice D introduces a health claim about local honey that the passage never makes. The keyed answer joins the observed flavor variation to its botanical cause, which is what the four sentences collectively argue.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Most modern bicycles use cable-actuated brakes that work well in dry conditions. In wet weather, however, water and grit on the rim reduce the friction that stops the wheel. Riders who ride year-round increasingly switch to disc brakes, which clamp a dedicated rotor near the hub. The rotor stays cleaner and provides consistent stopping power across temperatures. Bike shops report that disc-equipped models now account for the majority of new sales above entry level. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Disc brakes are displacing rim brakes because they perform more consistently in varied conditions.","Most new bicycles sold are now equipped with disc brakes.","Cable-actuated brakes work poorly in wet weather.","Year-round cyclists need specialized equipment to ride safely."]'::jsonb, 0, 'No single sentence states the thesis; it emerges from the contrast between rim and disc performance, the wet-weather problem, and the closing sales trend at bike shops. Choice B captures only the weakness of the older cable-actuated system, a supporting half. Choice C reports the sales detail in isolation without explaining why the shift is happening, an accurate-but-tangential restatement. Choice D over-generalizes about safety and the need for specialized equipment, neither of which the passage actually frames as necessary for year-round cyclists. The keyed answer synthesizes the performance reason and the market shift into one statement.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Community gardens often start with a single empty lot and a handful of volunteers. Within a season, raised beds appear, neighbors begin trading produce, and unfamiliar faces become regulars. Crime statistics on blocks with active gardens tend to drift downward over the following years. City officials in several regions now treat these gardens as low-cost public-safety investments rather than purely agricultural projects. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Crime rates fall sharply on every block with a community garden.","Cities should subsidize gardening supplies for low-income residents.","Community gardens function as social investments that strengthen neighborhoods beyond food production.","Empty lots are the most common starting points for community gardens."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage moves from origin to social effects to municipal reframing without naming a single topic sentence. The synthesized point is that gardens deliver social value far beyond the produce they grow. Choice B grabs the empty-lot starting-point detail, an opening fact rather than the central argument. Choice C overstates the crime trend with sharply and every block, while the passage uses softer hedging like tend and drift downward. Choice D proposes a subsidy policy for gardening supplies that the passage never recommends or even mentions. The keyed answer captures the full arc that the four sentences trace together.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'The cost of solar panels has fallen sharply over the past fifteen years. Battery prices, once the bottleneck for home installations, have also dropped significantly. Utility companies face a new dynamic: customers who once bought every kilowatt now sell power back during peak hours. Some regulators are rewriting rate structures to reflect a grid that flows in both directions. The old one-way model is increasingly difficult to defend. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Regulators are updating rate structures in some regions.","Solar panel prices have fallen over the past fifteen years.","Home solar installations will soon replace traditional power plants.","Cheaper solar and battery technology is reshaping the relationship between utilities and customers."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage threads price drops, customer behavior, regulatory response, and a closing judgment about how hard the old one-way model is to defend. The thesis must tie the technology shift to the changing utility relationship. Choice B reports only the price half of the story, a supporting fact. Choice C captures only the regulatory rate-structure response, again a supporting piece. Choice D predicts that home solar will replace traditional power plants, a far stronger claim than the passage actually makes about a two-way grid. The keyed answer integrates the cause, the customer behavior, and the institutional response into one statement.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Reading aloud to young children does more than entertain. It exposes them to vocabulary and sentence structures that rarely appear in everyday conversation. Children who are read to regularly enter kindergarten with measurably larger vocabularies than peers who are not. Even shared reading at bedtime, lasting only minutes, contributes to the language gap that schools spend years trying to close. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Schools are unable to close the language gap among students.","Vocabulary in books rarely overlaps with everyday speech.","Bedtime stories last only a few minutes for most families.","Reading aloud to young children builds vocabulary that shapes their school readiness."]'::jsonb, 3, 'Four sentences move from the activity to its vocabulary mechanism to its measurable effect on kindergarten readiness and the language gap that follows. The synthesized point ties reading aloud directly to school readiness. Choice B picks up a duration detail about how brief bedtime reading is, an aside rather than the argument. Choice C captures the vocabulary mechanism without naming the educational outcome it produces. Choice D distorts the closing line about schools spending years to close the gap into a flat claim that schools have failed entirely. The keyed answer holds the cause and the educational outcome together, matching what all four sentences build.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 4, 'Many drivers assume premium gasoline cleans their engine better than regular fuel. In most vehicles, however, the octane rating governs only how resistant the fuel is to premature ignition under compression. Detergent additives are mandated for all grades sold in the United States, so cleaning performance is largely equivalent across the pump. Cars whose owner''s manuals specify regular fuel gain no measurable benefit from premium and only pay more per gallon. A small group of high-compression engines does require premium, but for everyone else the upgrade is purely a charge against the wallet. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Premium gasoline cleans engines more effectively than regular gasoline.","Detergent additives are mandated in all grades of gasoline sold in the United States.","Premium gasoline benefits only the small set of engines that require it; for most drivers it is wasted money.","Octane rating measures resistance to premature ignition under compression."]'::jsonb, 2, 'Several factual claims compete for the spotlight: detergent additive rules, the octane definition, the owner''s-manual specification, and the high-compression exception. The primary point is the cost-benefit verdict in the last sentence, framed against the common cleaning-power assumption that opens the passage. Choice B isolates a supporting fact about mandated additives, the mechanism for why cleaning is equivalent. Choice C defines octane, more supporting machinery for the larger argument. Choice D directly contradicts the passage, which is the assumption being refuted from the start. The keyed answer captures the verdict the passage was built to deliver.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 4, 'Many beginning cooks blame their knives when chopping feels slow or unsafe. A dull blade certainly increases the force required and the chance of a slip, and most home knives are duller than their owners realize. Cutting boards matter too; glass and stone surfaces destroy edges within weeks. Yet experienced cooks point out that grip and posture govern far more than equipment. A sharp knife held poorly is still slow, while a modest knife held well moves quickly through onions and herbs. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Glass and stone cutting boards damage knife edges quickly.","Home cooks should buy sharper knives to improve their results.","A dull blade increases the force required to cut and raises the risk of slips.","Technique influences chopping speed and safety more than equipment alone."]'::jsonb, 3, 'Two themes compete inside the passage: equipment matters (dullness, board surface) and technique matters more (grip, posture, knife handling). The yet pivot in sentence four signals which claim is primary, and the closing onions-and-herbs example reinforces it. Choice B captures a supporting detail about how dull blades increase force and slip risk. Choice C captures the cutting-board surface detail, another piece of equipment evidence. Choice D draws an equipment recommendation that the passage explicitly downgrades in favor of technique over gear. The keyed answer reflects the experienced-cooks pivot that organizes the whole passage.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-15', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 4, 'Online customer reviews shape modern purchasing in two directions at once. Buyers consult them before committing money, especially for items they cannot inspect in person, and a single string of negative ratings can sink a product. At the same time, sellers have learned to solicit, edit, and occasionally fabricate reviews to manage their ratings. Platforms publish trust-and-safety reports, but enforcement is uneven and reviewers themselves often cannot tell genuine praise from paid copy. The marketplace runs on a system that buyers depend on and many sellers quietly distort. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Online reviews remain central to purchasing decisions even as their reliability is widely compromised.","Negative reviews can sink a product''s sales on most platforms.","Buyers should stop relying on online reviews when making purchases.","Platforms publish trust-and-safety reports about review fraud."]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage develops two opposing forces: buyer dependence on reviews and seller distortion of them. The closing sentence makes both sides explicit. Choice B captures only the buyer-impact side. Choice C reports a platform action without the broader argument. Choice D draws a prescription the passage never offers, especially given the opening insistence on how central reviews remain. The keyed answer holds the dependence and the distortion in the same statement, matching the closing summary.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-16', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'When a city replaces a stretch of asphalt with permeable pavers, the visible difference is small. The pavers look much like ordinary stone, and traffic crosses them without noticing. Underground, however, rainwater that once ran off the surface and overwhelmed storm drains now seeps through gaps between the stones into a gravel bed below. Local creeks downstream show fewer pollution spikes after heavy storms, and basement flooding complaints drop on neighboring blocks. The repaving looks ordinary, but the watershed quietly works differently. Skeptics often ask why the city did not simply build larger drains; engineers respond that the new surface costs less to maintain across its lifespan and treats the cause rather than the symptom. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Cities should require permeable pavement on every new project.","Permeable paving produces meaningful environmental and economic benefits that are not visible at street level.","Engineers prefer permeable pavers over larger storm drains.","Permeable pavers look much like ordinary stone surfaces."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage hinges on the contrast between appearance and outcome: an ordinary-looking surface delivers downstream environmental and cost benefits. The author''s overall point is that the value is real but hidden. Choice B captures only the appearance half. Choice C grabs the engineers-prefer detail without the broader payoff. Choice D pushes a policy mandate the passage avoids. The keyed answer integrates the invisible-but-meaningful framing that the opening, the middle examples, and the closing engineer comparison all support.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-17', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Productivity advice often centers on tools: a new planner, a tracking app, a different notebook system. New hires especially gravitate to whatever system their manager praises, hoping the right method will close the gap between effort and output. Most observers of long careers tell a different story. The colleagues who consistently finish what they start rarely use unusual tools; they protect their attention from interruption, decide quickly which tasks belong to them, and review their week before it begins. The tools merely record habits already in place. A planner is not a substitute for the underlying discipline, though many buyers hope it will be. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Many new hires copy whatever productivity system their manager praises.","Planners are useful only when paired with a tracking app.","Effective workers protect their attention and plan their weeks in advance.","Lasting productivity comes from underlying habits rather than from the specific tools people adopt."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage contrasts tool-focused hopes with habit-focused reality and closes by saying a planner is not a substitute for the underlying discipline it tries to capture. The author''s overall claim runs through every sentence and emerges only by inference. Choice B captures the new-hire copying detail, a piece of color rather than the thesis. Choice C lists the supporting habits like attention protection and weekly review without naming the tool-versus-habit thesis itself. Choice D invents a recommendation about pairing planners with tracking apps that the passage never makes and would actually contradict. The keyed answer states the underlying argument that organizes the contrast and the closing judgment.', false, 'draft'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-18', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Volunteer firefighters once formed the backbone of rural emergency response in many regions. Decades ago, neighbors who farmed or worked nearby trades could reach the firehouse within minutes of a tone. The economic geography has shifted: fewer residents work where they live, training requirements have grown, and the average volunteer is now over fifty. Recruiting drives produce modest gains that rarely keep pace with retirements. Some counties have begun staffing a paid skeleton crew during weekdays while preserving the volunteer roster for nights and weekends. Communities that once relied entirely on neighbors are quietly reorganizing around a hybrid model, even when local pride still describes the department as volunteer. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["The average volunteer firefighter is now over fifty years old.","Volunteer firefighting is no longer a viable model anywhere in the country.","Rural fire response is gradually shifting from a purely volunteer model to a hybrid arrangement driven by economic and demographic pressures.","Some counties pay a small daytime crew while keeping volunteers for nights and weekends."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage traces a historical baseline, names the pressures, and describes the structural response, closing on the gap between local self-description and reality. The author''s overall point is the underlying transition. Choice B isolates a demographic statistic. Choice C captures the hybrid example without the larger trend it illustrates. Choice D over-generalizes to nowhere viable, while the passage describes a gradual reorganization that still includes volunteers. The keyed answer states the inferential thesis that organizes every sentence in the paragraph.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''The driver was so RECKLESS that he ran three red lights and nearly hit a pedestrian,'' the word RECKLESS most nearly means:', '["careless","skilled","patient","cautious"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The sentence describes a driver running three red lights and nearly hitting a pedestrian, behavior that shows no regard for safety or for traffic law. That evidence pins the meaning to ''careless.'' ''Skilled'' contradicts the near-collision, since skilled driving would avoid that outcome rather than produce it. ''Patient'' contradicts running red lights, which is impatient behavior that refuses to wait. ''Cautious'' is the direct opposite of ignoring traffic signals and endangering people on foot. Only ''careless'' matches a driver who disregards rules and consequences at once.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''Her argument was so COMPELLING that even her opponents agreed she was right,'' the word COMPELLING most nearly means:', '["persuasive","lengthy","confusing","polite"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that even her opponents agreed she was right, an outcome that only happens when an argument actually convinces the people who started out against it. That pins the meaning to ''persuasive.'' ''Lengthy'' describes duration and would not by itself flip opponents to agreement, since long arguments often bore listeners. ''Confusing'' contradicts the outcome, since a confusing argument would not produce agreement from anyone. ''Polite'' describes tone, not force, and politeness alone does not change opponents'' minds. Only ''persuasive'' explains why opponents conceded the point against their own position.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''The hiking trail was so OBSCURE that we had to push aside branches just to see where it went,'' the word OBSCURE most nearly means:', '["hidden","popular","steep","wide"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is having to push aside branches just to see the trail, which means the path was concealed from view. That pins the meaning to ''hidden.'' ''Popular'' contradicts the overgrown condition, since a popular trail would be cleared by foot traffic. ''Steep'' describes incline, not visibility, and pushing branches aside is about seeing the path, not climbing it. ''Wide'' contradicts a trail covered by branches. Only ''hidden'' fits a path that has to be uncovered to follow.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''She was METHODICAL about her morning routine, doing every task in the same order at the same time each day,'' the word METHODICAL most nearly means:', '["systematic","rushed","cheerful","lazy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is doing every task in the same order at the same time each day, which describes a fixed system rather than a loose habit. That pins the meaning to ''systematic.'' ''Rushed'' contradicts a routine performed at consistent times, since rushing varies with pressure and rarely repeats on schedule. ''Cheerful'' describes mood and is not implied by repeating an order of tasks on a clock. ''Lazy'' contradicts the discipline of completing every task daily without skipping any. Only ''systematic'' captures a routine governed by both order and timing.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''After learning he had passed the bar exam, Marcus felt EUPHORIC and called everyone he knew to share the news,'' the word EUPHORIC most nearly means:', '["overjoyed","anxious","exhausted","indifferent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is passing the bar exam and calling everyone he knew to share the news, behavior driven by intense happiness rather than ordinary satisfaction. That pins the meaning to ''overjoyed.'' ''Anxious'' contradicts the celebration, since an anxious person would not broadcast good news to a long list of contacts. ''Exhausted'' would mean wanting rest after the strain of the exam, not picking up the phone to call person after person. ''Indifferent'' contradicts the eagerness to tell everyone, since indifference produces silence. Only ''overjoyed'' explains the impulse to share the achievement so widely.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-6', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''The loss of her grandmother had a PROFOUND effect on her, changing how she viewed family and time,'' the word PROFOUND most nearly means:', '["deep","brief","amusing","unclear"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that the loss changed how she viewed family and time, which describes a fundamental shift in outlook rather than a passing reaction. That pins the meaning to ''deep.'' ''Brief'' contradicts a change in worldview, which by definition persists once it takes hold. ''Amusing'' contradicts grief over a grandmother''s death and the serious reflection that followed. ''Unclear'' contradicts the sentence, which names exactly what changed in concrete terms: her view of family and her view of time. Only ''deep'' fits an effect that reaches a person''s core perspective and reshapes it.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-7', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 3, 'In the sentence ''The monk lived in an AUSTERE cabin with only a wooden bed, a single chair, and one bowl,'' the word AUSTERE most nearly means:', '["plain","luxurious","crowded","cheerful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is a cabin with only a wooden bed, a single chair, and one bowl, an inventory stripped of comfort and limited to bare necessities. That pins the meaning to ''plain.'' ''Luxurious'' is the direct opposite of owning three sparse items made of wood and clay. ''Crowded'' contradicts the short list of furnishings, which signals emptiness rather than abundance of objects. ''Cheerful'' describes mood, and the bare list conveys severity and restraint rather than warmth or decoration. Only ''plain'' fits a dwelling defined by the deliberate absence of extras.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-8', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 3, 'In the sentence ''The climber''s grip on the icy ledge was PRECARIOUS, and a single gust of wind could have sent her falling,'' the word PRECARIOUS most nearly means:', '["unstable","firm","comfortable","permanent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that a single gust of wind could have sent her falling, which describes a hold one small force away from failing completely. That pins the meaning to ''unstable.'' ''Firm'' contradicts the risk of falling from a breeze, since a firm grip would withstand normal weather. ''Comfortable'' contradicts hanging on an icy ledge with no margin for error or rest. ''Permanent'' contradicts a grip that could end in an instant from one passing gust. Only ''unstable'' captures a position that depends entirely on conditions not changing, even for a second.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-9', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 4, 'In the sentence ''Critics called the new album DERIVATIVE, pointing out that nearly every song borrowed melodies from earlier hits by other artists,'' the word DERIVATIVE most nearly means:', '["unoriginal","complex","popular","experimental"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that nearly every song borrowed melodies from earlier hits by other artists, which is the textbook definition of work taken from existing sources. That pins the meaning to ''unoriginal.'' ''Complex'' describes structure and is not implied by copying melodies. ''Popular'' describes reception, not source, and critics are faulting the album rather than praising its sales. ''Experimental'' contradicts borrowing from established hits, since experimentation departs from familiar material. Only ''unoriginal'' matches the critics'' charge.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-10', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 4, 'In the sentence ''The doctor assured the worried parents that the small bump was INNOCUOUS and would fade on its own within a week,'' the word INNOCUOUS most nearly means:', '["harmless","painful","contagious","permanent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is the doctor reassuring worried parents and predicting the bump would fade within a week, two signals that together rule out anything dangerous. That pins the meaning to ''harmless.'' ''Painful'' contradicts reassurance offered to anxious parents, since pain would call for treatment rather than calm. ''Contagious'' would prompt warnings about spread to other family members, not assurance about a quick fade. ''Permanent'' is the direct opposite of fading on its own within a week. Only ''harmless'' fits a finding that calms parents and predicts a quiet resolution without intervention.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-11', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 5, 'In the sentence ''His FACETIOUS remark about the bride''s dress at the rehearsal made everyone uncomfortable, since no one could tell whether he meant the insult or was only joking,'' the word FACETIOUS most nearly means:', '["flippant","sincere","respectful","tearful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that listeners could not tell whether he meant the insult or was only joking, which describes humor offered at an inappropriate moment. That pins the meaning to ''flippant.'' ''Sincere'' contradicts the possibility that he was joking, since sincere speech is meant straight. ''Respectful'' contradicts insulting a bride at her rehearsal. ''Tearful'' describes emotion and does not match a remark that reads as a joke. Only ''flippant'' captures a comment that treats a serious moment as material for humor.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 1, 'The prefix RE- means again or back. Based on this, REPLAY most nearly means:', '["to play before","to play once and stop","to play again","to refuse to play"]'::jsonb, 2, 'REPLAY decomposes into RE- (again, back) plus PLAY. The prefix RE- appears in REWIND, REVISIT, and REBUILD, all signaling repetition or return. Choice A inverts the meaning by swapping RE- for PRE- (before). Choice B drops the prefix entirely and defines only the root. Choice D confuses RE- with the negating prefix REF- in REFUSE, which carries a different Latin origin (re- plus fundere, to pour back). The correct reading combines repetition with the action of playing.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 1, 'The prefix NON- means not or absence of. Based on this, NONFICTION most nearly means:', '["writing that is made up","writing that is not made up","writing that is poorly done","writing that is unfinished"]'::jsonb, 1, 'NONFICTION breaks into NON- (not) plus FICTION (invented narrative). The prefix NON- works the same way in NONSTOP, NONPROFIT, NONVERBAL, and NONSENSE, each simply negating the root that follows. Choice A defines fiction itself and ignores the prefix entirely, the most common error when the test taker rushes past the leading morpheme. Choice C confuses NON- with the Latin MAL- (bad) seen in MALPRACTICE and MALFUNCTION, which carries a moral judgment NON- does not. Choice D confuses NON- with the suffix -LESS or with the prefix UN- as in UNFINISHED. NONFICTION names writing grounded in fact rather than invention.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 1, 'The prefix DIS- means not, opposite of, or away. Based on this, DISLOYAL most nearly means:', '["extremely loyal","loyal at times","not loyal","loyal to a leader"]'::jsonb, 2, 'DISLOYAL splits into DIS- (not, opposite of) plus LOYAL. The same prefix appears in DISAGREE, DISHONEST, and DISCONNECT, each reversing the root. Choice A inverts the meaning by treating DIS- as an intensifier, a common error since spoken stress can sound emphatic. Choice B softens the negation into a partial state the prefix does not allow. Choice D ignores the prefix and defines only the root. DISLOYAL describes someone who fails to keep faith with a person, cause, or country.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The prefix TRANS- means across or beyond. The word TRANSPORT therefore is best defined as:', '["to carry across or from one place to another","to store in a harbor","to repair a damaged vehicle","to load goods onto a ship"]'::jsonb, 0, 'TRANSPORT combines TRANS- (across) with the Latin root PORT (to carry), the same root in PORTER, IMPORT, and EXPORT. The prefix appears in TRANSMIT, TRANSFER, and TRANSCONTINENTAL with consistent meaning. Choice B mistakes PORT the prefix-bearing root for PORT meaning harbor, a homograph trap. Choice C invents a meaning unsupported by either morpheme. Choice D names a specific shipping action but ignores the across or beyond element supplied by TRANS-. TRANSPORT denotes movement of people or goods across distance.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The suffix -LESS means without. Based on this, FEARLESS most nearly means:', '["easily frightened","feeling moderate fear","causing fear in others","without fear"]'::jsonb, 3, 'FEARLESS attaches the suffix -LESS (without) to the root FEAR. The same suffix produces HOPELESS, ENDLESS, and HARMLESS, each signaling absence of the root quality. Choice A reverses the meaning, the kind of error that arises when a reader confuses -LESS with -FUL. Choice B softens the absolute negation the suffix demands. Choice C confuses -LESS with the agentive suffix -SOME as in FEARSOME, which means causing fear. FEARLESS describes a person or action free from fear.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-6', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The suffix -FUL means full of or characterized by. The word PLAYFUL therefore most nearly means:', '["full of or showing a desire to play","without any sense of play","tired from playing too much","skilled at a particular game"]'::jsonb, 0, 'PLAYFUL joins the root PLAY with the suffix -FUL (full of). The same suffix produces JOYFUL, CAREFUL, and HOPEFUL, each meaning full of the root quality. Choice B reverses the meaning by treating -FUL as if it were -LESS. Choice C drifts toward modern colloquial English where playful is sometimes loosely linked to exhaustion, but morphology does not support that reading. Choice D narrows the word to athletic skill, ignoring the broad sense of disposition the suffix supplies. PLAYFUL describes a mood or behavior marked by lighthearted fun.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-7', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The prefix INTER- means between or among. Based on this, INTERSTATE most nearly means:', '["inside a single state","between two or more states","owned by the state government","below the state level"]'::jsonb, 1, 'INTERSTATE pairs INTER- (between, among) with STATE. The same prefix carries through INTERNATIONAL, INTERACT, INTERSECT, and INTERVIEW, each describing something that occurs between or among multiple parties. Choice A confuses INTER- with INTRA- (within), a high-frequency trap since the two prefixes differ by a single letter but reverse the meaning, as in INTRASTATE commerce that stays within one state. Choice C ignores the prefix entirely and assigns government ownership unsupported by the morphology. Choice D confuses INTER- with SUB- (below) or with the suffix -ARY indicating subordinate rank. An INTERSTATE highway runs between states, which is why the federal system carries that label.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-8', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The prefix MAL- means bad or wrongful. The word MALCONTENT therefore is best defined as:', '["a person who is satisfied","a person who avoids conflict","a person who is dissatisfied or rebellious","a person who lacks ambition"]'::jsonb, 2, 'MALCONTENT joins MAL- (bad, wrongful) with CONTENT (satisfied). The same prefix drives MALFUNCTION, MALPRACTICE, MALEVOLENT, and MALICE, each signaling a corrupt or harmful version of the root. Choice A defines CONTENT alone and ignores the prefix entirely, the most common slip when a reader recognizes only the familiar second morpheme. Choice B confuses MAL- with the prefix DIS- (apart, away) or with the idea of withdrawal, but MAL- carries no sense of avoidance. Choice D drifts into a vague personality description unsupported by either morpheme. A MALCONTENT is a person whose dissatisfaction often expresses itself as grumbling or open rebellion against authority.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-9', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The suffix -ISM means a doctrine, belief, or practice. Based on this, BAPTISM most nearly means:', '["the person who performs a religious rite","the practice or rite of baptizing","a building used for religious services","the study of religious texts"]'::jsonb, 1, 'BAPTISM combines the Greek root BAPT (to dip, immerse) with the suffix -ISM (practice, doctrine). The same suffix produces CAPITALISM, JOURNALISM, and CRITICISM, each naming a practice or system. Choice A confuses -ISM with the agentive suffix -IST, which names the person who practices (BAPTIST). Choice C confuses -ISM with -ARY or -ERY (BAPTISTRY, the building). Choice D confuses -ISM with -OLOGY (study of). BAPTISM names the rite itself rather than its practitioner, location, or academic study.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-10', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The word AMBIDEXTROUS contains the prefix AMBI- (both) and the root DEXTR- (right hand, skill). AMBIDEXTROUS most nearly means:', '["unable to use either hand well","able to use both hands with equal skill","preferring the left hand","lacking coordination"]'::jsonb, 1, 'AMBIDEXTROUS decomposes into AMBI- (both) plus DEXTR- (right hand, skill) plus the adjective suffix -OUS. The same prefix appears in AMBIGUOUS (both ways) and AMBIVALENT (both feelings). Choice A inverts the meaning by stripping the positive sense of DEXTR-. Choice C confuses DEXTR- with SINISTR- (left hand), the Latin opposite preserved in SINISTER. Choice D ignores both morphemes and describes a generic lack of physical skill. AMBIDEXTROUS describes a person who handles tools, writing, or tasks equally well with either hand.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-11', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 4, 'The word MISANTHROPE contains the Greek prefix MIS- (hatred of) and the root ANTHROP- (humankind). MISANTHROPE most nearly means:', '["a person who studies human cultures","a person who hates or distrusts humankind","a person who acts wrongly toward others","a person who lives among other people"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MISANTHROPE comes from Greek MIS- (hatred) plus ANTHROP- (man, humankind), the same root in ANTHROPOLOGY and PHILANTHROPY. The trap is that Greek MIS- (hatred, as in MISOGYNY) is spelled identically to the Latin MIS- (wrongly, as in MISJUDGE), but the two prefixes are unrelated. Choice A confuses MISANTHROPE with ANTHROPOLOGIST, swapping the prefix for the suffix -OLOGIST. Choice C applies the Latin MIS- (wrongly) instead of the Greek one. Choice D ignores the hostility carried by MIS- entirely. A MISANTHROPE actively dislikes the human race.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-12', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 4, 'The word BIBLIOPHILE contains the root BIBLIO- (book) and the suffix -PHILE (lover of). BIBLIOPHILE most nearly means:', '["one who writes books","one who fears books","one who loves and collects books","one who sells books"]'::jsonb, 2, 'BIBLIOPHILE pairs BIBLIO- (book) with -PHILE (lover of), the same suffix in AUDIOPHILE and FRANCOPHILE. The trap is the closely spelled -PHOBE (fear of), which reverses the meaning, as in CLAUSTROPHOBE. Choice A confuses -PHILE with the agentive ending in AUTHOR. Choice B applies -PHOBE instead of -PHILE, a high-value distractor because the suffixes look almost identical to a quick reader. Choice D narrows the word to commercial activity not supported by either morpheme. A BIBLIOPHILE is a devoted reader and collector of books.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-13', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 5, 'The suffix -EFY (a variant of -IFY) means to make or cause to become. The word LIQUEFY therefore is best defined as:', '["to make solid","to make liquid","to remove liquid from","to study the properties of liquid"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LIQUEFY joins LIQU- (the root in LIQUID) with -EFY (to make), a rare variant of -IFY preserved in only a handful of words such as PUTREFY and STUPEFY. Most English verbs use -IFY (CLARIFY, MAGNIFY), so spellers often miswrite LIQUIFY, but the dictionary form keeps the older -EFY. Choice A inverts the meaning by treating -EFY as if it carried negation. Choice C confuses -EFY (to make) with the prefix DE- (to remove). Choice D confuses -EFY with -OLOGY (study of). LIQUEFY names the process of melting or dissolving a solid into liquid form.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-14', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 5, 'The word EPIDERMIS contains the Greek prefix EPI- (upon, over) and the root DERM- (skin). EPIDERMIS most nearly means:', '["the deepest layer of skin","the outer layer of skin","the layer beneath the skin","a disease affecting the skin"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EPIDERMIS combines EPI- (upon, over) with DERM- (skin), the same root in DERMATOLOGY. The trap is the prefix APO- (away from), which looks and sounds similar to EPI- but reverses the spatial sense, as in APOSTASY. Choice A confuses EPI- with HYPO- (under), the prefix found in HYPODERMIC (under the skin). Choice C also applies HYPO- or SUB- instead of EPI-. Choice D confuses the prefix with the suffix -ITIS (inflammation) or -OSIS (condition). EPIDERMIS names the outermost protective layer of skin covering the body.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'The root TELE appears in TELEPHONE, TELESCOPE, and TELEVISION. The root TELE most nearly means:', '["far or distant","sound","picture or image","machine"]'::jsonb, 0, 'TELE comes from Greek tele, meaning far or distant. Cognates include telephone (distant sound), telescope (viewing what is distant), television (distant viewing), telegraph (writing at a distance), and teleport (carry across distance). ''Sound'' is a trap because telephone involves sound, but PHON carries that meaning, not TELE. ''Picture or image'' confuses the function of television with the root, since VIS supplies the image meaning. ''Machine'' is a generic association with electronics, but TELE never refers to a device, only to distance.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'The root AUTO appears in AUTOMATIC, AUTOBIOGRAPHY, and AUTONOMY. The root AUTO most nearly means:', '["machine","self","car","moving"]'::jsonb, 1, 'AUTO comes from Greek autos, meaning self. Cognates include autobiography (self-written life story), autonomy (self-rule), automatic (acting on its own without outside help), autograph (a self-written signature), and autocrat (a self-appointed ruler). ''Machine'' confuses AUTO with the English word automation, but the underlying root means self, not the device performing the action. ''Car'' is the most common English association with auto, yet automobile literally means self-moving, where AUTO still means self. ''Moving'' belongs to MOT or MOB (motor, mobile), separate Latin roots unrelated to AUTO.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'The root ZOO appears in ZOOLOGY, ZODIAC, and PROTOZOA. The root ZOO most nearly means:', '["cage or enclosure","animal or living thing","wild","garden"]'::jsonb, 1, 'ZOO comes from Greek zoion, meaning animal or living being. Cognates include zoology (study of animals), protozoa (first-form animals, single-celled), zodiac (originally a circle of animal-shaped constellations), and zoophyte (an animal-plant hybrid such as coral). ''Cage or enclosure'' reflects the modern English word zoo as a place, but the root itself names the creatures inside, not the building around them. ''Wild'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by FER (feral, ferocious), not ZOO. ''Garden'' belongs to HORT (horticulture, horticulturist), unrelated to ZOO.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'Based on the root THERM (meaning heat), the word THERMAL most likely means:', '["relating to cold","relating to heat","relating to weather","relating to light"]'::jsonb, 1, 'THERM comes from Greek therme, meaning heat. Cognates include thermal (relating to heat), thermometer (heat measurer), thermos (heat-retaining container), hypothermia (low body heat), and geothermal (heat from the earth). ''Relating to cold'' is the opposite, the trap students fall into because hypothermia involves being cold, though the root itself names heat. ''Relating to weather'' confuses THERM with general climate words, but weather belongs to METEOR (meteorology). ''Relating to light'' belongs to PHOT (photograph) or LUM, separate roots.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'The root MAR appears in MARINE, MARITIME, and SUBMARINE. The root MAR most nearly means:', '["sand or shore","sea","boat","salt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MAR comes from Latin mare, meaning sea. Cognates include marine (relating to the sea), maritime (concerning sea navigation), submarine (under the sea), mariner (a sailor), and aquamarine (sea-water blue). ''Sand or shore'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by LITTOR (littoral) or AREN (arena, originally sand), not MAR. ''Boat'' confuses the vessel with the body of water, since submarines are boats but MAR points to the sea itself. ''Salt'' belongs to SAL (saline, salary), a different Latin root, even though seas are salty.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-6', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'The root LUM appears in ILLUMINATE, LUMINOUS, and LUMINARY. The root LUM most nearly means:', '["heat","light","color","shadow"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LUM comes from Latin lumen, meaning light. Cognates include illuminate (to light up), luminous (giving off light), luminary (a shining person or body), lumen (a unit of light), and translucent (light passing through). ''Heat'' is a related-but-distinct concept because hot objects often glow, yet heat belongs to THERM or CALOR, not LUM. ''Color'' belongs to CHROM (chromatic), often confused because colored objects reflect light. ''Shadow'' is the opposite of LUM and belongs to UMBRA (umbrella, penumbra), the Latin root for shade.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-7', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'The root HELIO appears in HELIOCENTRIC, HELIOTROPE, and HELIUM. The root HELIO most nearly means:', '["heat","sun","sky","star"]'::jsonb, 1, 'HELIO comes from Greek helios, meaning sun. Cognates include heliocentric (sun-centered), heliotrope (a plant that turns toward the sun), helium (the element first detected in sunlight), and perihelion (closest point to the sun in an orbit). ''Heat'' is a related-but-distinct concept because the sun gives heat, but heat itself is THERM. ''Sky'' belongs to CEL (celestial) or URAN (Uranus), separate roots. ''Star'' belongs to ASTER or STELL (astronomy, stellar), commonly confused with HELIO because both involve space, yet HELIO names only our sun.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-8', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'MONOTONE shares its root with MONOPOLY and MONARCH. The shared root means:', '["money","one or single","voice","rule"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MONO comes from Greek monos, meaning one or single. Cognates include monotone (one tone), monopoly (one seller), monarch (one ruler), monologue (one person speaking), and monogamy (one partner). ''Money'' confuses MONO with monetary words, which actually use MONET (Latin moneta), an unrelated root. ''Voice'' is a trap because monotone involves voice, yet the voice meaning belongs to VOC, while MONO contributes only the one. ''Rule'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by ARCH (monarch, anarchy), which is the second half of monarch, not MONO.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-9', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root AMBI appears in AMBIDEXTROUS, AMBIGUOUS, and AMBIVALENT. The root AMBI most nearly means:', '["around","both","uncertain","skilled"]'::jsonb, 1, 'AMBI comes from Latin ambi, meaning both or on both sides. Cognates include ambidextrous (using both hands), ambiguous (having both meanings), ambivalent (having both feelings), and amphibian (living in both water and on land, from the Greek cognate amphi). ''Around'' belongs to CIRCUM (circumference) or PERI (perimeter), often confused because ambient sound surrounds you. ''Uncertain'' describes the result of ambiguity, not the root itself. ''Skilled'' is the common-cognate trap from ambidextrous, but AMBI supplies both, while DEXTER supplies the skilled or right-handed meaning.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-10', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root MAGN appears in MAGNIFY, MAGNANIMOUS, and MAGNITUDE. The root MAGN most nearly means:', '["strong","great or large","many","powerful attraction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MAGN comes from Latin magnus, meaning great or large. Cognates include magnify (make larger), magnitude (greatness in size), magnanimous (great-souled, generous), magnificent (great in deed), and magnate (a great person in business). ''Strong'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by FORT (fortify) or ROBUST, not MAGN. ''Many'' belongs to MULTI or POLY, often confused with great because both suggest abundance. ''Powerful attraction'' is the common-cognate trap from magnet, an unrelated word borrowed from a place name (Magnesia), not the size root.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-11', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root MIT/MISS appears in TRANSMIT, EMIT, MISSILE, and DISMISS. This root most nearly means:', '["to send","to receive","to throw","to allow"]'::jsonb, 0, 'MIT/MISS comes from Latin mittere, meaning to send. Cognates include transmit (send across), emit (send out), missile (something sent), dismiss (send away), and submit (send under, yield). ''To receive'' is the opposite and belongs to CIP/CEPT (receive, accept), commonly confused because messages must be both sent and received. ''To throw'' belongs to JECT (eject, reject), a related-but-distinct action since throwing and sending overlap. ''To allow'' is the common-cognate trap from permit and admit, where the English meaning has drifted, while the underlying root still means send.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-12', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root JUR/JUS appears in JURY, JUSTICE, PERJURY, and JURISDICTION. This root most nearly means:', '["law or oath","judge","court","punishment"]'::jsonb, 0, 'JUR/JUS comes from Latin jus, meaning law, right, or sworn oath. Cognates include jury (a sworn body), justice (lawful rightness), perjury (false oath), jurisdiction (the speaking of law), and jurisprudence (the study of law). ''Judge'' belongs to JUDIC (judicial, adjudicate), a related-but-distinct root for the person, not the law itself. ''Court'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by CUR (curia, courthouse), where law is applied. ''Punishment'' belongs to PEN or PUN (penalty, punitive), the consequence of breaking law, not law itself.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-13', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 4, 'The root VOR appears in CARNIVORE, HERBIVORE, OMNIVORE, and VORACIOUS. This root most nearly means:', '["to grow","to devour or eat greedily","to hunt","to feed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'VOR comes from Latin vorare, meaning to devour or swallow whole. Cognates include carnivore (meat-devourer), herbivore (plant-devourer), omnivore (all-devourer), voracious (greedy in appetite), and devour itself. ''To grow'' belongs to CRESC (crescendo, increase), an unrelated concept. ''To hunt'' is a related-but-distinct action supplied by VEN (venatic) or PRED (predator), since hunting precedes devouring. ''To feed'' is the gentler common-cognate trap, since carnivores do feed, yet VOR specifically carries the violent, greedy swallowing, not ordinary eating, which is ED or NUTR.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-14', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 4, 'The root NOM/NOMEN appears in NOMINATE, NOMENCLATURE, and IGNOMINIOUS. This root most nearly means:', '["number","name","law","honor"]'::jsonb, 1, 'NOM/NOMEN comes from Latin nomen, meaning name. Cognates include nominate (to put a name forward), nomenclature (a system of names), ignominious (without good name, shameful), pseudonym (false name), and renown (re-named, famous). ''Number'' is the common-cognate trap because numerator and enumerate share the NUM root, a different Latin word that students confuse with NOM. ''Law'' belongs to LEG or JUR, separate roots. ''Honor'' is the opposite of ignominious and is supplied by HONOR or DIGNI (dignity), related-but-distinct concepts shaped by but not equal to a good name.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-15', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 5, 'The root FID appears in FIDELITY, CONFIDE, PERFIDY, and BONA FIDE. The root FID most nearly means:', '["faith or trust","loyalty","secret","promise"]'::jsonb, 0, 'FID comes from Latin fides, meaning faith or trust. Cognates include fidelity (faithfulness), confide (to trust with a secret), perfidy (betrayal of trust), bona fide (in good faith), and infidel (one without faith). ''Loyalty'' is the close common-cognate trap since fidelity often translates as loyalty, yet loyalty itself comes from LEG (lawful), while FID carries the broader trust meaning. ''Secret'' confuses the act of confiding with the root, but secret belongs to SECR (secret, secrete). ''Promise'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by PROMIS or VOW, the result of trust rather than its root.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-16', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 5, 'The root JECT appears in EJECT, INJECT, PROJECT, and DEJECTED. The root JECT most nearly means:', '["to send","to throw","to push","to fall"]'::jsonb, 1, 'JECT comes from Latin jacere, meaning to throw or hurl. Cognates include eject (throw out), inject (throw in), project (throw forward), dejected (thrown down, low in spirit), and trajectory (the path of a thrown object). ''To send'' belongs to MIT/MISS (transmit, missile), a related-but-distinct action commonly confused because both move things outward, yet sending implies a destination while throwing does not. ''To push'' belongs to PEL/PULS (propel, expulsion), the contact-force root. ''To fall'' is the opposite direction, supplied by CAD/CAS (cascade, casualty), often confused with dejected because both involve downward motion.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'CANDID most nearly means:', '["frank","cautious","candied","polite"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Candid means honest and straightforward in expression, as in a candid review that holds nothing back. Frank carries the same sense of open, unguarded speech. Cautious is the antonym trap: a cautious speaker filters and hedges, the opposite of candid. Candied is a sound-alike that means coated in sugar and has no relation to honesty. Polite is a register-confusion distractor; candid speakers may be polite or blunt, but politeness describes manners rather than openness.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'INNOCUOUS most nearly means:', '["harmless","innocent","ignorant","harmful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Innocuous means producing no injury or offense, as in an innocuous comment that no one took badly. Harmless is a direct match. Innocent is a sound-alike and partial-overlap trap; it refers to lack of guilt or moral fault, not lack of harmful effect. Ignorant is another sound-alike pulled by the prefix in, but it means lacking knowledge. Harmful is the antonym, naming the exact quality innocuous denies.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'IMMINENT most nearly means:', '["impending","eminent","immense","distant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Imminent means about to occur, as in an imminent storm that forces the crew indoors within minutes. Impending shares the meaning of a near, unavoidable arrival. Eminent is the classic sound-alike trap; it means distinguished or prominent in reputation and has nothing to do with timing. Immense is another sound-alike that describes great size, not closeness in time. Distant is the antonym, placing the event far from the present.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'AMICABLE most nearly means:', '["friendly","talkative","hostile","amicus"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Amicable means marked by goodwill, as in an amicable settlement that leaves both parties on decent terms. Friendly captures that cooperative warmth. Talkative is a register-confusion distractor; an amicable person may speak little, since the word describes disposition rather than volume of speech. Hostile is the antonym, naming the antagonism amicable resolves. Amicus is a Latin sound-alike root meaning friend, but as a standalone English word it does not mean friendly the way amicable does.', false, 'draft'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'DESPONDENT most nearly means:', '["dejected","responsive","dependent","elated"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Despondent means cast down in spirits to the point of losing hope, as in a despondent candidate who stops returning calls after the rejection. Dejected matches that low, defeated mood. Responsive is a sound-alike pulled from the spond root meaning to answer or pledge, but it describes reactivity, not sorrow. Dependent is another sound-alike that means relying on others, with no emotional content. Elated is the antonym, naming the high spirits despondency lacks.', false, 'draft');
commit;
